1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 { Welcome to my course based on the Trompowsky. This repertoire is based on the opening moves @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 . The related Pseudo-Trompowsky @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 d5 2.Bg5 will also be covered, along with Trompowsky-esque 2. Bg5 against the Dutch Defence 1... f5. A final chapter will deal with other popular first moves Black can choose.

Octavio Figueira Trompowsky de Almeida (1897-1984) was a one time Brazilian chess champion (in 1939) who played a number of games with 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 and here most of his opponents played 2... d5. Around the same time US chess player from Pennsylvania William Allen Ruth also developed the opening.

In the 1980s the opening was analyzed a lot in Spain and then it became popular because of some highly creative games by the English Grandmaster Julian Hodgson. Since then it has developed the reputation as a serious but slightly offbeat opening. Magnus Carlsen has played it a few times, most noteworthy in the first game of his World Championship match against Sergei Karjakin.

The attractive part of the Trompowsky is that it provides a full repertoire for White based on 1. d4, but you only have to study a limited number of lines. So a repertoire based on the Trompowsky is much smaller than a repertoire where you need to develop separate weapons against all of Black's main openings like the Slav, Grunfeld, Queen's Gambit, King's Indian, etc. At the professional level, many players who have 1. e4 as their main weapon have used the Trompowsky to surprise their opponent, and it has become known as a great attacking weapon. } *

