1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1... Nf6 and 2... d5. } ) 
3. Bh4 { In the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} cxd4 
5. exd4 Qb6 { There are different positions where Black can go for Qb6, sometimes with a pawn on c5, sometimes without. To be consistent I have chosen in all lines to sacrifice the pawn. Just remember - we don't play b2-b3 because it weakens the dark squares too much. (Of course to every rule there are one or two exceptions!) } 
6. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} Qxb2 
7. Nbd2 { Forced to save the rook. } e6 
8. Rb1 { Now if Black takes on a2 White will play in similar fashion as in the main line, but because the knight on d2 is not pinned White can claim some advantage. } Qc3 
9. Ne5 { Immediately going forward because Black is weak around his king. } Bb4 { If Black had played Qxa2 he would not have this move, meaning the b-file would still be open. } 
10. Bb5+ Bd7 
11. Nxd7 Nxd7 
12. a3 { A tricky move because after either capture on a3 White will be able to castle kingside and Black is in serious trouble with his king. } Qxd2+ { This is Black's escape to an endgame. } 
13. Qxd2 Bxd2+ 
14. Kxd2 { White now threatens to take on d7 followed by Rxb7+. } b6 
15. c4 {[%cal Gh1c1,Gc4d5,Gc1c7][%csl Re8,Gb5,Gh4]} { White has sufficient compensation for the pawn deficit with his two strong bishops. If the c-file opens White can play Rhc1 and threaten to enter on the 7th rank and White also threatens to take on d5 followed by Rhe1 when the Black king is in danger. More details on this line can be found here. [/variation/21651917] } *

