1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1... Nf6 and 2... d5. } ) 
3. Bh4 { In the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} Nc6 
5. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} g5 
6. Bg3 Bg7 { This concept is recommended by Boris Avrukh. } 
7. c3 { As usual, we play against the bishop on g7, which is not so strong when the pawn on d4 is supported by pawns on e3 and c3. } Qb6 
8. Qb3 ( { White could also have played } 8.Qc2 { but it results in a very different type of play. } ) c4 { Black is going for the most principled approach. } 
9. Qc2 Bf5 { A sharp move that will result in huge complications. } 
10. Qxf5 Qxb2 { Black has sacrificed the bishop on f5 in order to win the rook on a1. } 
11. Qxd5 Nf6 { Not the only move for Black, but quite an obvious one. } 
12. Qxc4 Qc1+ { It is important for Black to first chase the White king forward so he loses the right to castle and cannot easily develop. } 
13. Ke2 Qb2+ 
14. Nfd2 { And not the knight from b1 because White really wants to try to lock up Black's queen on a1. } Qxa1 { So far we are following the line that Boris Avrukh gives in his book Beating 1.d4 sidelines. But the line should not end here! } 
15. d5 Nxd5 
16. Qxd5 { Of course White takes the piece. He now has sufficient material for the rook, but his king is still in the way of the bishop on f1. White will try to unravel on the kingside and exchange the queens. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. [/variation/21651923] } *

