2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1... Nf6 and 2... d5. } ) 
3. Bh4 { In the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} Qb6 
5. c4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Here White can play 5. Nf3 and try to transpose to the line with Black first taking on d4 (cxd4) and then Qxb2. However, Black is not forced to take on d4, so for example after } 5.Nf3 Qxb2 6.Nbd2 { Black can play } 6...c4 { and I don't trust this variation. That is why we don't play 5.Nf3 here. } ) Qxb2 ( { If Black plays } 5...e6 { we will transpose back to the variation 5...Qxb2 with } 6.cxd5 Qxb2 7.Nd2 { . } ) 
6. Nd2 cxd4 
7. cxd5 { One of White's ideas behind playing c2-c4 is that he can take on d5 instead of playing Rb1 followed by exd4. } dxe3 
8. fxe3 g5 
9. Bg3 { The bishop can also go back to f2. It just feels to me that on g3 it is slightly more active, although on f2 it will not be so bad once White gets e3-e4 in. } Bg7 
10. Rb1 {[%cal Gb2f6,Rf1d3,Rd2e4]} Qxa2 ( { With the idea that } 10...Qf6 { (a move some scared black players may go for) is really bad for Black after the simple } 11.Bd3 { followed by Ne4. } ) 
11. Bc4 { White has sacrificed two pawns for a big lead in development. Engines can hold this for Black, but for humans who haven't studied this position before it is extremely hard. } Qa5 {[%cal Rb1b5,Ra5d8,Rg3c7,Rb5c5]} 
12. Ngf3 ( { White also has a move repetition here with } 12.Rb5 Qa3 13.Rb3 Qa1 14.Rb1 { because if after @@StartFEN@@rnb1k1nr/pp2ppb1/7p/q2P2p1/2B5/4P1B1/3N2PP/1R1QK1NR w Kkq - 2 12@@EndFEN@@ 12.Rb5 Black plays 12...Qd8 , his queen will be in trouble after the surprising 13.Rc5! followed by 14. Bc7. } ) Nf6 
13. O-O O-O 
14. Qc2 {[%cal Gf3d4,Gd4f5,Ge3e4,Ge4e5,Gg1h1]} { White has sufficient compensation based on his more active pieces. For the time being the black extra pawns are going nowhere while White's pieces will continue to create threats. Typical next moves for White are Nd4 followed by Nf5, and Kh1 folowed by e3-e4-e5. } *

