1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1... Nf6 and 2... d5. } ) 
3. Bh4 { In the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } g5 ( 3...Nf6 4.Bxf6 { is similar to the lines with 1...Nf6 and 2...d5 where we take on f6. The only difference is that the black h-pawn has moved from h7 to h6, which sometimes doesn't make a difference (when the pawn later moves to h5), but usually is slightly worse for Black because his bishop from f8 can no longer go to h6 directly (Black first needs the extra move h5 and there the pawn might be weak). } ) 
4. Bg3 {[%mdl 32768]} c5 { If Black plays 4... c6 here, his strategy feels like a mix of playing solid (c6) and aggressive (g5) at the same time. It is not that White is winning immediately after c6, but with normal developing moves like 5.e3, Nf3 and Bd3 White will obtain a nice advantage. } 
5. e3 { White doesn't want to give up the center. Taking on c5 is almost never a good option because it helps Black to achieve e7-e5 with a strong center. } Bg7 
6. c3 {[%csl Rf5,Rh5]} { Our setup is similar to the London system, except Black has weakened his kingside a bit with g7-g5. } Nf6 
7. Nf3 O-O 
8. Nbd2 { White is getting ready for a later Ne5 followed by Ndf3. } cxd4 
9. exd4 { I prefer taking with the e-pawn so the position is more dynamic than after the symmetrical cxd4. White now also gets the option to increase control over the e5-square by putting a rook on e1. } Nc6 
10. Bd3 Qb6 
11. Qc2 {[%csl Rf5]} { White takes control over the light squares. Especially the f5-square is weak with the pawn already on g5. } Nh5 
12. O-O-O {[%cal Gc1b1,Gh1e1,Gh2h4,Gf3e5]} { We have a sharp position where objectively it is equal, but in practice it is a bit easier to play with White. He can still put a piece on e5, play Rhe1 or start with h2-h4 to soften Black's kingside further.

Meanwhile, the queen on b6 is in the way of starting an attack on the White king with b7-b5 and if Black does manage this move (e.g. Qa5 Kb1 b5, then after b5-b4 White can respond with c3-c4.

More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. [/variation/21651942] } *

