1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. In this chapter we will deal with setups where Black tries to ignore the bishop on g5. } c5 
3. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} { Usually when Black plays c5 (which is analyzed in chapter 7 [/course/134623/6], Pseudo-Trompowsky: 1... d5 2. Bg5 Others) we answer with e3. We don't want to give away the center by taking on c5 and defending with Nf3 is not ideal because a knight on d4 can easily be chased away. White can sometimes answer c7-c5 with c2-c3, but that results in a symmetrical pawn structure after pawns are exchanged on d4 and I prefer to have a bit more imbalance. } f6 {[%cal Rg8h6,Rh6f5,Gg5h4]} 
4. Bf4 { Whenever Black plays f6 and still has the option of Nh6 we don't play Bh4 because a later Nh6-f5 would be annoying. } Nc6 ( 4...cxd4 5.exd4 Nc6 6.Nf3 Bg4 7.Be2 { is a transposition to the line with 4...Nc6 and 6...cxd4. } ) 
5. Nf3 Bg4 { The human move. } 
6. Be2 { You want to get rid of the pin on the knight on f3 so that the pawn on d4 stays protected. } cxd4 
7. exd4 e5 { This move is not innocent at all. White needs to be careful. } 
8. dxe5 Bxf3 
9. Bxf3 fxe5 { In the long term White has great prospects with his pair of bishops, but in the short term Black controls a lot of squares with his central pawns. } 
10. Bc1 ( { I also analyzed } 10.Bg3 { but it is quite risky. } ) Nf6 
11. O-O e4 
12. Bh5+ g6 
13. Be2 {[%cal Gc1g5,Gd1d5][%csl Rd5]} { We arrive at a strange position. White has no weak pawns and the bishop pair, but because Black has such a powerful center it is difficult for White to get his pieces to the right squares and his king can become vulnerable. Play through the remaining moves to see how the complications that could arise after White targets the central pawns. } Bd6 
14. Bg5 {[%csl Rd5]} { In most of these positions White targets the pawn on d5. } Qe7 
15. Bxf6 Qxf6 
16. Qxd5 { White now has an extra pawn, but this is only the beginning of large complications. } O-O-O {[%cal Gd8d5]} { Threatening Bxh2+. } 
17. Qxe4 Qxb2 
18. Nd2 { The only move to save the rook. } Rhe8 
19. Qg4+ Kb8 { Black has ideas like Bxh2+ followed by Rxd2, but also Ne5 can be annoying. } 
20. Nc4 Qxc2 
21. Nxd6 Rxe2 ( { Now on } 21...Rxd6 22.Qg3 { White can still play for an edge with his strong bishop. } ) 
22. Rfc1 {[%cal Rc2b2,Rc2d2,Ga1b1,Gb1a1,Gc1b1,Gc1d1]} { There is a draw possible here with the Black queen staying on the second rank and the white rooks keep attacking the queen. } *

