1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. In this chapter we will deal with setups where Black tries to ignore the bishop on g5. } c5 
3. e3 { Usually when Black plays c5 (which is analyzed in chapter 7 [/course/134623/6], Pseudo-Trompowsky: 1... d5 2. Bg5 Others) we answer with e3. We don't want to give away the center by taking on c5 and defending with Nf3 is not ideal because a knight on d4 can easily be chased away. White can sometimes answer c7-c5 with c2-c3, but that results in a symmetrical pawn structure after pawns are exchanged on d4 and I prefer to have a bit more imbalance. } f6 {[%cal Rg8h6,Rh6f5,Gg5h4]} 
4. Bf4 { Whenever Black plays f6 and still has the option of Nh6 we don't play Bh4 because a later Nh6-f5 would be annoying. } Nc6 ( 4...cxd4 5.exd4 Nc6 6.Nf3 Bg4 7.Be2 { is a transposition to the line with 4...Nc6 and 6...cxd4. } ) 
5. Nf3 Bg4 { The human move. } 
6. Be2 { You want to get rid of the pin on the knight on f3 so that the pawn on d4 stays protected. } cxd4 
7. exd4 e6 
8. O-O {[%mdl 32768]} { White has castled and is ready to develop his b1-knight. Normally in these types of positions you don't play c2-c4 with White because it would weaken the d4-pawn after ...dxc4. The exception is if almost immediately White would win the pawn on e6. } Nge7 { Black doesn't want to exchange the dark squared bishops and aims to put his knight on g6 to drive away the f4-bishop. } 
9. h3 Bxf3 
10. Bxf3 Ng6 
11. Be3 { White has a pair of bishops and if he manages to open the position Black will be in trouble. } Nh4 { A precise move. Black limits the power of White's bishop pair. } 
12. Be2 Nf5 
13. c4 {[%csl Re8]} { A sharp pawn sacrifice to open the position while Black's king is still in the center. } dxc4 
14. Bxc4 Ncxd4 
15. Bxd4 Nxd4 
16. Nc3 {[%csl Re6,Rf7]} { White is now going to maximize the pressure on e6. Black could at some point play e6-e5, but this creates a lot of weaknesses around his king, especially the squares f7 and e6. } Qb6 
17. Qa4+ Kf7 
18. Rfe1 {[%cal Ge1e2,Ga1e1,Ga4c2,Gc3b5,Gc2f5]} { White has sufficient compensation for the pawn and some good attacking chances. His main idea is to go Nb5 next to exchange the knight on d4 that defends e6. The pawn on e6 is the real target for White and not easy to defend for Black in the long run. So after exchanging knights White may continue with Re2 and Rae1 and Qc2-Qf5 once the bishop is back on c4. } *

