1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. In this chapter we will deal with setups where Black tries to ignore the bishop on g5. } c5 
3. e3 { Usually when Black plays c5 (which is analyzed in chapter 7 [/course/134623/6], Pseudo-Trompowsky: 1... d5 2. Bg5 Others) we answer with e3. We don't want to give away the center by taking on c5 and defending with Nf3 is not ideal because a knight on d4 can easily be chased away. White can sometimes answer c7-c5 with c2-c3, but that results in a symmetrical pawn structure after pawns are exchanged on d4 and I prefer to have a bit more imbalance. } f6 {[%cal Rg8h6,Rh6f5,Gg5h4]} 
4. Bf4 { Whenever Black plays f6 and still has the option of Nh6 we don't play Bh4 because a later Nh6-f5 would be annoying. } Nc6 ( 4...cxd4 5.exd4 Nc6 6.Nf3 Bg4 7.Be2 { is a transposition to the line with 4...Nc6 and 6...cxd4. } ) 
5. Nf3 g5 { A direct approach from Black, not often seen in practice. However, there is one incredible sharp line that I want to share with you. } 
6. Bg3 {[%mdl 32768]} g4 ( { The start of massive complications. After other moves such as } 6...cxd4 { or } ) ( 6...Bg7 { White's play will be similar to other lines in the repertoire. } ) 
7. Nh4 ( { Going back to g1 is too slow and } 7.Nfd2 { is not an option because the pawn on d4 would be lost. } ) cxd4 
8. exd4 f5 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd8h4,Gf5f4][%csl Rh4]} { A very concrete idea: Black wants to win the knight on h4 either by playing f5-f4 and then after Bxf4 Black takes on h4 with his queen or dark-squared bishop, or Black wants to win the knight by playing e7-e6, Be7 and Bxh4. } 
9. Bb5 {[%cal Gg3e5][%csl Rh8]} { The only move! White has to take control over the e5-square for now. Be5 attacking the rook on h8 is a way to save the knight on h4. } Bg7 
10. Nc3 Kf7 {[%cal Gc6d4][%csl Rd4]} ( { With the idea that after } 10...e5 { White takes } 11.dxe5 { and Nxd5 is a big problem for Black. } ) { Unpinning the knight from c6 andthreatening Nxd4. } 
11. Bxc6 { So White exchanges the knight. } bxc6 
12. Ne2 { With the idea that on f5-f4 White has Nxf4 and the knight on h4 remains secure. } Bf6 {[%cal Ge7e6,Gd8h4][%csl Rh4]} { Preparing e7-e6 to play Bxh4. } 
13. h3 {[%cal Gh1h4,Gh3g4,Rh7h5,Ge2f4,Gf4g6][%csl Gh4]} h5 ( { Now after } 13...e6 { there is } 14.hxg4 { and the rook on h1 protects the knight on h4. This is a powerful post for the knight which will aid an ongoing kingside initiative. Play through the remaining moves to see how play could develop. } ) { Now e7-e6 is a threat again because after hxg4 Black also has ...hxg4 and the rook from h8 attacks the knight on h4. } 
14. Nf4 {[%cal Gf4g6][%csl Rg6]} { Now that the black h-pawn is on h5 and no longer h7 there is a hole on g6! } e5 { Black is going for the knight on h4. } 
15. Nfg6 {[%cal Gg6h4,Gg6h8]} { The knight on h4 is protected and the rook on h8 is attacked. } f4 
16. dxe5 {[%cal Gg6h8][%csl Rf6]} ( { The bishop is lost. If it moves to h2 there is } 16.Bh2 Bxh4 { . } ) { Attacking the bishop on f6 which cannot move because of Nxh8+. } fxg3 
17. Nxh8+ Bxh8 { Threatening Qxh4. } 
18. O-O Nh6 ( { But now } 18...Qxh4 { loses to } 19.fxg3+ { check! } ) 
19. fxg3+ Kg8 
20. Qd2 { We arrive at an unclear position. Materially speaking White is doing fine with two pawns and a rook against two light pieces, and White's king is safer than Black's.

The odds that you will ever face this entire line are quite low, but it is good for your self-confidence to know how to save yourself in the complications so you don't need to worry about losing in 15 moves! } *

