1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. In this chapter we will deal with setups where Black tries to ignore the bishop on g5. } Nd7 { Black prepares Ngf6 without allowing doubled f-pawns. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 Trompowsky chapter [/variation/21553258/#/2/b]. } ) 
3. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} Ngf6 
4. Nf3 { White is playing a hybrid of a Torre attack and London system, the main difference being the bishop on g5 and the knight on d7 locking in the bishop on c8 for now. } e6 
5. Bd3 Be7 
6. Nbd2 { The move order is not so relevant. White needs to play c2-c3, Nd2, and Bd3. } O-O 
7. c3 { For the time being White keeps the option open of castling kingside or queenside. } c5 { This position can also be reached by an earlier c7-c5, for example on move 4. } 
8. Ne5 { This move is an essential part of White's strategy and the beginning of an attack. } Nxe5 ( { If Black plays something like } 8...Qc7 { White is happy to support his knight with f4 and after developing his queen and castling queenside he will launch an attack. } ) 
9. dxe5 Nd7 
10. Bxe7 { You don't want to go back with the bishop to f4 where it would be passively staring at its own pawn on e5. } Qxe7 
11. f4 -- ( { If Black now plays passively White is ready to attack } 11...-- 12.Qh5 { . After } 12...h6 { White has queenside castling followed by g4 and if Black plays } { 12...g6 instead of h6 White has 13.Qh6 followed by queenside castling and h2-h4-h5.

More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. [/variation/21651947] } )
