1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist, and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } f6 { Black's most critical reply and I have dedicated a separate chapter to it to make sure you get complicated positions where it is easy to go wrong for your opponent. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 Trompowsky chapter [/variation/21553258/#/2/b]. } ) 
3. Bd2 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { It took many years before Black players realized that after the natural } 3.Bh4 { the move } 3...Nh6 { with the idea } 4.-- Nf5 { is a serious challenge for White's setup. } ) c5 { The start of sharp play. } 
4. dxc5 { White can also play the more quiet 4.e3, but the disadvantage is that Black gets the choice to define the type of play then. } e5 
5. e4 { An aggressive move, opening the road to h5 for the white queen. } dxe4 { This move doesn't really work for Black. } 
6. Nc3 f5 { This is Black's idea, but it doesn't work. } 
7. Nxe4! fxe4 
8. Qh5+ { And now we are having some fun with White! } Ke7 
9. Qxe5+ Be6 
10. Bc4 { The pin on the bishop on e6 turns out to be the decisive factor. The engine gives White a winning advantage, but it is useful to know how to conduct the attack. } Qc8 
11. O-O-O { White should keep adding pieces to the attack. The rook on d1 is useful in a lot of lines. } Nc6 
12. Qxe4 { This is not just about taking a pawn, it opens the e-file and Re1 is a big threat. } Nf6 
13. Qe2 { You want to keep the pressure on e6. Re1 is still a threat. } Nd4 
14. Qe3 Nc6 
15. Re1 { Simple chess: keep increasing the pressure. } Nd8 
16. Nf3 g6 
17. Nd4 { And White will regain the piece on e6 with a completely winning position. Black is likely to lose a lot more material if he wants to avoid mate. } *

