1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 Ne4 { There are many setups Black can choose against the Trompowsky, but there are two main moves for Black that are played most often: 2...e6 and 2...Ne4. In this chapter we will study 2...Ne4. } 
3. Bf4 {[%mdl 32768]} { White wants to prove that the knight on e4 is not stable and if it returns to f6, that White has won a tempo for his development. Black claims that if White pushes his pawn to f3, it is not really that useful and might be in the way of the ideal square for the knight on g1. } ( 3.Bh4 { This move has been played quite a lot in practice but I don't like White's position after the moves } 3...g5 4.f3 gxh4 5.fxe4 { It feels to me that White has unnecessarily weakened the dark squares and that he will struggle to maintain the balance. } ) ( 3.h4 { This is a move typically for blitz games, hoping Black will take on g5 and White will benefit from the half-open h-file. } 3...c5 4.d5 h6 { Now the bishop needs to retreat to f4 or c1 and I don't like my pawn on h4. It could become weak in the long term (pawns never move back!) and I prefer to play these positions with my pawn still on h2 (which is part of the repertoire). } ) d5 { This is a very solid approach for Black. In many of the lines that follow there is no advantage for White if Black plays correctly, but the recommended lines are sharp and give Black ample opportunities to go wrong. } 
4. f3 ( { I also analyzed the options } 4.e3 { (after which I think } 4...c5 { is a good response) and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3PnB2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq d6 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nd2 (the simple 4...Nxd2 or 4...Bf5 are both fine for Black). The move 4. f3 is sharper and is more consistent with other lines in the repertoire where we also play this move. } ) Nf6 
5. Nc3 ( { Instead the move } 5.e4 { is also an option, but the lines quickly become messy and I miss a clear logic in the moves that the engines suggest. } ) c5 
6. e4 { White cannot yet transpose to the lines with Nb5 because with the pawn still on e2 Black has the annoying Qa5+. } dxe4 { This move is probably imprecise. } 
7. d5! {[%cal Rf3e4]} { A great move because White threatens now fxe4 with a clear space advantage in the center. This means the only way for Black to justify his play is to accept the pawn sacrifice, which is dangerous. } exf3 
8. Nxf3 a6 
9. Qd2 { It is essential for White to develop his pieces as quickly as possible to generate some initiative for the pawn. } g6 
10. O-O-O {[%csl Gd5]} { With a great position for White, with more than enough compensation for the pawn. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. [/variation/21785996] } *

