4. c4 {[%cal Rc4d5,Rd7d5]} { The idea is to play c2-c4 as soon as possible so we can take on d5 if Black puts a pawn there. } d5 { This move is recommended by Gawain Jones in his course on the King's Indian. } 
5. cxd5 { Gaining a tempo on Black's queen. } Qxd5 
6. Nc3 Qd8 ( { Black can also play } 6...Bb4 { , but then White plays } 7.e3 { and 8.Nge2 followed by a2-a3, and after Black takes on c3 White takes back with his knight, develops the bishop to e2 and castles. } ) ( 6...Qa5 { is a valid alternative. } 7.e3 Bg7 8.g3 c5 9.Nge2 Nc6 { Black threatens to take on d4. } 10.dxc5 Qxc5 11.Bg2 { followed by O-O and White is a little better. } ) 
7. g3 { This setup with the bishop on g2 we will also see in other lines where Black has doubled f-pawns. We try to stop Black's expansion on the kingside while we generate play on the queenside. } Bg7 { I don't think the bishop is doing much here. Black needs to play on the kingside and the bishop would be much more effective on d6. } ( 7...Bd6 { Black believes that his bishop on d6 is more effective in generating play on the kingside than if it was on g7. } 8.Bg2 O-O 9.e3 { Every time we go for the same setup: bishop to g2, knight to e2 and kingside castling. } 9...f5 10.Nge2 Nd7 { Black can also play this setup with c7-c6 at some point. The move order is not so relevant. I have included a line with 7...c6 where the position is similar to this line and White's play is consistent between the two lines. } 11.O-O Nf6 12.Qc2 { White needs to generate play on the queenside, typically by moving his a- and b-pawns forward and putting a knight on c5. } 12...a6 { If Black plays 12...c6 instead, we have an exact transposition to the line with 7...c6. } 13.Rab1 { Instead, 13.Na4 with the idea Nc5 is also a valid alternative. } 13...h5 14.h4 { Stopping Black's expansion on the kingside. Otherwise Black would have played h5-h4. } 14...Ng4 15.b4 g5 { This is really the only aggressive plan Black has, so that's why I wanted to include this line. } 16.hxg5 Qxg5 17.e4 { An important move to remember as a concept: Black is coming for White's king and in a blitz game between Moiseenko and Supi White got into trouble after 17. Nd5. The idea of 17. e3-e4 is along the classical principle: if your opponent is coming for your king, react in the center! } 17...h4 { This looks quite aggressive, but White is prepared. } 18.e5 { Both bishops have now become passive. } 18...hxg3 { Threatening Qh4 with mate. } 19.f4 { A cool reply combined with White's next move. } 19...Qh6 20.Rf3 { It is no more mate on h2. Black has a check but the queen on h2 would be offside, and Black cannot strengthen his attack further. } 20...Be7 21.Nxg3 { White has a nice advantage here. Black needs to play extremely accurately to keep the balance. The engine says the only way for Black is to play Bh4 and take on g3. I don't think many Black players would play this. White is threatening to take on f5 and if Black defends with } 21...Qg6 { (a logical move), he gets hit with } 22.Nd5 { and White is winning material. } ) 
8. Bg2 {[%mdl 32768]} O-O 
9. e3 { The white plan doesn't change: bishop to g2, knight to e2 and castle kingside. } f5 
10. Nge2 Nd7 
11. O-O { White is ready to start his operations on the queenside while Black can only wait. More in-depth analysis on this line can be found here. [/variation/21553217] } *

