5. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4]} ( { Here I give two recommendations for White: } 5.Nc3 { with complex, tactical play and the more solid } ) ( 5.c3 { . I would recommend you study both so you can mix it up if necessary, and your repertoire will not become too predictable. } ) { A solid move. These lines tend to be a bit more positional compared to the more aggressive 5. Nc3. White is not only defending the pawn on d4, but also it has become less attractive for Black to put his bishop on g7 because thanks to the chain c3-d4 White has firm control over the dark squares. We see this quite often in chess, that you put your pawns on the color of which you have given up your bishop, so White's pawns on c3 and d4 (and possibly e5) supplement his light-squared bishop. } d5 { Black tries to fight against White's central control. } 
6. Nd2 ( { I had a look at } 6.e5 { , a logical move and after } 6...Qd8 { the structure resembles a Caro-Kann in which White has exchanged his dark-squared bishop for a black knight. It seems to me that White has trouble stabilizing his center, especially the pawn on d4, and lines with dxc5 after Black has played c7-c5 are not that much fun either. } ) c5 
7. Bb5+ Nd7 { This move is likely to transpose to structures we have seen in other lines. } 
8. e5 {[%mdl 32768]} Qd8 ( { If Black plays } 8...Qg6 { , White continues with } 9.g3 { and now after, for example, } 9...a6 10.Ba4 cxd4 11.cxd4 Bb4 12.Bc2 Qg5 13.h4 { Black can take on d2 twice, but White is much better and will play f2-f4-f5 after some preparation. Meanwhile, if Black doesn't take on d2 he needs to go back to d8 and the whole journey to g6 was pointless. } ) 
9. Ne2 { White prepares kingside castling and a later f2-f4. } a6 
10. Bd3 Be7 
11. O-O cxd4 
12. cxd4 O-O 
13. Kh1 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gf4f5,Gd2f3,Gd3c2,Gd1d3]} { And White has some advantage, Black's position is quite passive while White is ready for f2-f4 and then either f4-f5 or Nf3 and Bc2/Qd3. } Qb6 
14. f4 f5 
15. g4 { It is important to remember that White almost never takes exf6 if he has already his pawn on f4. The reason is that the pawn on f4 could become weak and taking on f6 is mainly a good plan in combination with Nf3, Qe2 and Rfe1 to control the e5-square with pieces, not with a pawn on f4 that is in the way. } Rf7 
16. Rg1 { Typical play with a black pawn on f5: rook to g1 and g2-g4. } Nf8 ( 16...fxg4 { is just bad for Black, but to your opponent it may not immediately be clear why, so let me show you how White creates a winning attack: } 17.Bg6 Rf8 18.Rxg4 { It turns out that Black struggles to defend the pawn on g7. } 18...Qd8 19.Qg1 { Queen to c2 followed by Rag1 also wins. } 19...Nb6 20.Bh7+ Kh8 21.Rxg7 { And White has a winning attack. } ) 
17. Nf1 { White can also first take on f5. The only advantage of first playing Nf1 is that it gives Black another opportunity to go wrong and take on g4. } Bd7 
18. gxf5 exf5 
19. Ne3 {[%cal Gd1f1,Gf1f3,Gg1g2,Ga1g1][%csl Rd5,Rf5]} { A beautiful square for the knight. Black is already having difficulty in defending both d5 and f5 in time. White can create a powerful attack by simple means. }-- ( { Let me show you a sample line: } 19...Kh8 20.Rg2 Be6 21.Qf1 Rc8 22.Rb1 Qd8 23.Qf3 b6 24.Rbg1 Rc7 25.Qh5 { and the white attack is unstoppable. He just keeps adding pieces and will take on f5 on the next move or after first playing Ng3. } )
