5. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4]} ( { Here I give two recommendations for White: } 5.Nc3 { with complex, tactical play and the more solid } ) ( 5.c3 { . I would recommend you study both so you can mix it up if necessary, and your repertoire will not become too predictable. } ) { A solid move. These lines tend to be a bit more positional compared to the more aggressive 5. Nc3. White is not only defending the pawn on d4, but also it has become less attractive for Black to put his bishop on g7 because thanks to the chain c3-d4 White has firm control over the dark squares. We see this quite often in chess, that you put your pawns on the color of which you have given up your bishop, so White's pawns on c3 and d4 (and possibly e5) supplement his light-squared bishop. } b6 { This is rarely played in practice but it is quite logical to put the bishop on b7, with the pawns on d7 and e6 blocking the bishop on c8. } 
6. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bb7 
7. Nd2 { I also analyzed lines with Ne2 followed by castling kingside, e4-e5 and f2-f4 but it seems that in this line that would only help Black's bishops. } g6 { I am not sure how good this is, but going through a database of blitz games I noticed that a lot of amateur players at some point put their bishop on g7, so I have included this setup in several lines in the repertoire. } 
8. Ngf3 Bg7 
9. h4 { With a simple idea: to play h4-h5 and get the g6-pawn to g5 so that the bishop on g7 is less mobile. } O-O 
10. h5 g5 
11. Nc4 { First castling kingside is also a valid option and likely to transpose. } d6 
12. Ne3 { With the knight on e3 it becomes unattractive for Black to play e6-e5 because there is always Nf5, while after d6-d5, White is ready for e4-e5. } Nd7 
13. O-O Qe7 
14. Bc2 { Preparing Qd3 followed by e4-e5. } c5 { What else? Black has to break somewhere and pawn moves with the d-, e- and f-pawn are not good. } 
15. d5 {[%cal Ga2a4][%csl Rb7]} { And this is the other advantage of playing Ne3. White can counter c7-c5 with d4-d5. Play through the remaining moves to see how play could develop. } Rad8 
16. a4 Nf6 
17. Nh2 {[%cal Gd1h5]} { Defending the pawn on h5. } Rfe8 
18. Nhg4 { And now it is clear why the knight went to h2 and not e1 or d2: White wants to exchange the knight on f6 so that the pawn on h5 doesn't need to be defended by the queen anymore. }exd5 ( { Note that } 18...Nxh5 { is a mistake because of } 19.Nxh6+ Bxh6 20.Qxh5 { . } ) 
19. exd5 Nxg4 
20. Qxg4 {[%cal Gg4c4,Gc4d3,Gd3h7,Ge3f5,Ga4a5,Ga5b6,Ga1a7,Gc4b5][%csl Rb6,Rf5,Rg8,Rh6]} { It seems to me that White has a nice advantage: he threatens Qf5 and if Black defends with 20... Qf6, there is always in the future the possibility that the queen suddenly moves to d3 (probably via c4) followed by Qh7+. And although that is not immediately decisive, it is dangerous if White can play Nf5 on the next move.

Besides these attacking ideas White also has the plan of Qc4 to control the b5-square and then play a4-a5 on the next move. White would then threaten to take on b6 and follow up with Ra7 and/or Qb5. } *

