[Event "The Trompowsky: Simplified"]
[White "1) Trompowsky: 1...Nf6 2.Bg5 e6"]
[Black "3...h6 with 5. c3 - why not 6.Nf3"]
[Date "2023.01.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21518466"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 e6 ( { There are many setups Black can choose against the Trompowsky, but there are two moves for Black that are played the most often: } 2...e6 { and } ) ( 2...Ne4 { . In this chapter we will focus on } ) ( 2...e6 { . } ) 
3. e4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} { One of the main ideas in the Trompowsky against the line with 2...e6 is that White is willing to exchange his bishop on g5 for the knight on f6 in order to create a powerful center and control a lot of squares. } h6 { One of the most played moves at all levels. } 
4. Bxf6 Qxf6 
5. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4]} ( { Here I give two recommendations for White: } 5.Nc3 { with complex, tactical play and the more solid } ) ( 5.c3 { . I would recommend you study both so you can mix it up if necessary, and your repertoire will not become too predictable. } ) { A solid move. These lines tend to be a bit more positional compared to the more aggressive 5. Nc3. White is not only defending the pawn on d4, but also it has become less attractive for Black to put his bishop on g7 because thanks to the chain c3-d4 White has firm control over the dark squares. We see this quite often in chess, that you put your pawns on the color of which you have given up your bishop, so White's pawns on c3 and d4 (and possibly e5) supplement his light-squared bishop. } c5 { Black immediately strikes back in the center. } 
6. Nf3 { This was played in a game between Duda and Giri in 2019. I have made this line with 6. Nf3 informational because the resulting positions are hard to play and not consistent with the rest of the repertoire (I have recommended Benoni pawn structures in multiple places, so here 6. d5 is also the way to go). } cxd4 
7. cxd4 Bb4+ 
8. Nc3 O-O 
9. Bd3 d6 
10. O-O { The position is completely equal but certainly not a draw yet. There is a lot of play left but the reason I don't recommend this line is that it is hard to give you a standard plan for White. It really depends on how Black will continue: will he take on c3 or not, will he play his queen back to d8 so it can help on the queenside, will he push e6-e5, or will he first play solidly with Nc6, Bd7 and Rac8? There are so many options... } Nc6 
11. Qb3 ( { My improvement over the game Duda - Giri Chess.com 2019 in which } 11.Bb5 { was played. } ) Bxc3 { Black's concept is based on taking on c3 at some point. } 
12. Qxc3 { Taking back with the b-pawn is also an option but you need to ensure you keep the c4-square under control (which is not so easy to do) because you don't want a rook on c8 supporting a black knight on c4. } Bd7 
13. Rad1 Rac8 
14. Qa3 { Of course the queen moves away from the rook on c8. } d5 { Black is taking control over the light squares but the bishop on d7 may suffer. } ( 14...e5 { With the light squared bishop on d7 it makes sense that Black puts his central pawns on d6 and e5. } 15.d5 Ne7 16.Nd2 { White wants to play on the queenside. Taking on a7 is also possible but quite dangerous because Black will organize a strong attack with Ng6-Nf4 in combination with Qg6 and it is not so easy to defend for White. } 16...Ng6 17.g3 { Now that White's knight is no longer on f3 this move is possible. } 17...Bh3 18.Rfe1 Nf4 { Of course White cannot take the knight because of Qg6+ and mate on g2. } 19.Bf1 Qg6 20.Bxh3 { This results in a funny move repetition. If White wants to continue the fight he should play Rc1 here. } 20...Nxh3+ 21.Kg2 Nf4+ 22.Kh1 Nh3 23.Kg2 { And a draw is unavoidable. } ) 
15. exd5 exd5 
16. h3 Rfe8 ( { Preventing any Bg4 ideas. Note that } 16...Bxh3 { is not possible as White plays } 17.gxh3 { and after } 17...Qxf3 { there is } 18.Bh7+ { winning the queen. } ) 
17. Qb3 ( { I also looked at the option of playing } 17.Bb1 { followed by Qd3 but doesn't feel dangerous at all after the simple g7-g6, as White lacks a good follow-up. } ) Be6 
18. Rfe1 { The position is equal, but it's not too difficult for White to put pressure on Black. Especially the pawn on d5 is weak, so White can play Re3 (keeping the option open to double rooks on the e- or c-file) followed by rerouting the bishop from d3 via c2 to b3. White can also play Ba4 and take on c6 with his bishop and claim that his knight (which will then go to e5) is much stronger than the bishop. } *

