3. e4 {[%csl Gd4,Ge4]} { One of the main ideas in the Trompowsky against the line with 2...e6 is that White is willing to exchange his bishop on g5 for the knight on f6 in order to create a powerful center and control a lot of squares. } h6 { One of the most played moves at all levels. } 
4. Bxf6 Qxf6 
5. c3 {[%csl Gc3,Gd4]} ( { Here I give two recommendations for White: } 5.Nc3 { with complex, tactical play and the more solid } ) ( 5.c3 { . I would recommend you study both so you can mix it up if necessary, and your repertoire will not become too predictable. } ) { A solid move. These lines tend to be a bit more positional compared to the more aggressive 5. Nc3. White is not only defending the pawn on d4, but also it has become less attractive for Black to put his bishop on g7 because thanks to the chain c3-d4 White has firm control over the dark squares. We see this quite often in chess, that you put your pawns on the color of which you have given up your bishop, so White's pawns on c3 and d4 (and possibly e5) supplement his light-squared bishop. } c5 { Black immediately strikes back in the center. } 
6. d5 {[%mdl 32768]} { Going for a kind of Benoni structure. } exd5 
7. exd5 d6 { I guess some wild black player may go for Bd6 but we would not be impressed, simply continuing our development with Nf3 or Ne2 after Bd3 followed by castling kingside. } 
8. Nf3 a6 { Black wants to make sure White doesn't have Bb5+ ideas. } 
9. a4 { Stopping b7-b5 for now. } g6 
10. Be2 Bg7 
11. O-O O-O {[%csl Rb6,Gc3,Rd6,Rg7]} { The main thing about this position is the weak pawn on d6, the hole on b6 and the pawn on c3 limiting the power of the bishop on g7. Therefore Black is dreaming of b7-b5-b4. } 
12. Na3 { The c4-square is perfect for the knight. } Nd7 
13. Nc4 Rb8 
14. Nfd2 {[%cal Gd2e4,Ga1a3,Ga3b3,Ga4a5]} -- ( { White has a small advantage. On } 14...b5 { he can win a pawn with } 15.Ne4 { followed by taking on d6. Black may first play 14...Re8 but then White will reply 15. f3 so that Ne4 remains a valid option. In the long term White can also play Ra3-Rb3, a4-a5 or even allow b7-b5 and then after playing axb5 axb5 continue with Na5 and Nc6 and perhaps Ra7. } { A sample line continues: 14...Re8 15.f3 Preparing Ne4. 15...Qe7 16.Ne4 Just in time before Black could prevent this move with Nf6. 16...Nf6 Black could no longer defend the pawn on d6, but this is not the end of the complications. 17.Ncxd6 Nxe4 18.Nxe4 Bf5 This was Black's idea: two active bishops and pressure along the e-file. 19.Qd2 19.Ng3 is a valid alternative, but not 19.Bd3 because of 19...c4 (White cannot take on c4 because of Qc5+) when Black gets a lot of activity. 19...Bxe4 20.fxe4 Qxe4 Black is taking a bit of a risk by accepting the pawn on e4. 20...Rbd8 is the best way for Black to maintain the balance, but how many players can resist taking on e4? 21.Qf4 h5 22.Bc4 Rd6 Before White can play d5-d6 in order to take on f7. 23.Rf2 The position is about equal. White's extra pawn is not so relevant with the opposite colored bishops and Black's total control over the squares e5 and d6. Still, it is not a draw at all and White can continue with Rf3, Rb1 and b2-b4 to divert Black's attention to the queenside and hope that defending both the queenside and the center and the pawn on f7 becomes too much. 21.Bf3 Qe3+ 22.Qxe3 Rxe3 23.d6 and White has a clear advantage. It's maybe not winning yet, but it's not easy to defend for Black. White's pawn on d6 is dangerous and easy to support with a rook on d1, the king can come to help via f2 and after a4-a5 there is Ra4-Rc4. } )
*

