10. hxg5 { White now starts an operation that is quite typical for these type of positions and that I also included on move 8 when Black plays a6 instead of Bd7. } hxg5 
11. Rxh8+ Bxh8 { At least for now there are no more Bh6 ideas and Black can also no longer castle kingside. } 
12. e5 dxe5 ( 12...Qf5 { The queen is not safe here. } 13.g4 Qxg4 14.Nb5 { This was White's idea. The pawns on c7 and d6 are both under attack. } ) 
13. d5 {[%cal Rc3e4,Rd5d6]} Nd4 ( { An aggressive way of putting Black's position under pressure. Both } 13...Ne7 { and } ) ( 13...Nd8 { would be quite passive now. White would follow up with } 14.Ne4 { and either d5-d6 or dxe6 and Black's king is still in danger. } ) 
14. Nxd4 ( { White can also play } 14.Ne4 { but the line results in a drawish opposite-coloured bishop endgame. } ) exd4 
15. Ne4 Qf4 
16. dxe6 fxe6 
17. Nxg5 Qxd2+ 
18. Kxd2 {[%cal Gd1e1,Gf1c4,Gd1h1][%csl Gg2]} { The position is equal but certainly not a draw yet. Yes, Black has the pair of bishops, but at the moment both of them are not very active. White has a free passed g-pawn which could especially become a factor if the rooks are exchanged. Meanwhile White can put pressure on Black's weak e-pawn with Re1 and Bc4 or Bd3 or decide to invade with his rook via h-file after Bc4 followed by Rh1. } *

