3. Bf4 {[%mdl 32768]} { White wants to prove that the knight on e4 is not stable and if it returns to f6, that White has won a tempo for his development. Black claims that if White pushes his pawn to f3, it is not really that useful and might be in the way of the ideal square for the knight on g1. } ( 3.Bh4 { This move has been played quite a lot in practice but I don't like White's position after the moves } 3...g5 4.f3 gxh4 5.fxe4 { It feels to me that White has unnecessarily weakened the dark squares and that he will struggle to maintain the balance. } ) ( 3.h4 { This is a move typically for blitz games, hoping Black will take on g5 and White will benefit from the half-open h-file. } 3...c5 4.d5 h6 { Now the bishop needs to retreat to f4 or c1 and I don't like my pawn on h4. It could become weak in the long term (pawns never move back!) and I prefer to play these positions with my pawn still on h2 (which is part of the repertoire). } ) d5 { This is a very solid approach for Black. In many of the lines that follow there is no advantage for White if Black plays correctly, but the recommended lines are sharp and give Black ample opportunities to go wrong. } 
4. f3 ( { I also analyzed the options } 4.e3 { (after which I think } 4...c5 { is a good response) and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3PnB2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq d6 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nd2 (the simple 4...Nxd2 or 4...Bf5 are both fine for Black). The move 4. f3 is sharper and is more consistent with other lines in the repertoire where we also play this move. } ) Nd6 { A funny move, but guess what: amateurs don't always play the engine's top choice, so it is important that in this repertoire we deal with these kind of moves! } 
5. Nc3 c6 ( 5...e6 6.e4 { Now if Black plays } 6...c6 { we transpose to the line [/variation/21519701/#/6/b] with 5...c6 and 6...e6. } ) 
