7. Qd2 Qxb2 
8. Rb1 Qa3 
9. exd5 { White immediately wins back the sacrificed pawn on b2. } Nd7 ( 9...e6 { Although it looks a bit strange, this move is actually not so bad. } 10.dxc6 { Taking on e6 only helps Black to develop his bishop. } 10...bxc6 { Black cannot take back with his knight on c6 because White has the strong d4-d5! } 11.Bd3 { Material is equal but White has a lead in development. } 11...Nd7 12.Nge2 Nb6 { Black would like to put a knight on c4 but White will prevent this. } 13.Rb3 Qa5 14.Ne4 Qxd2+ 15.Nxd2 { Exchanging queens is not a bad thing for White to do.

It's more important that he maintains control over square c4. It makes a big difference for the assessment of the position whether White has pawns on d4 and c4 versus a pawn on d4 with next to it on c4 a black knight. } 15...Be7 16.c4 Nf5 17.Be4 Bd7 18.Kf2 { White has a nice advantage based on the healthier pawn structure and the more active pieces. White's idea is to play a2-a4 on the next move and Black cannot take because Nxa4, Ra1 Nb6 Rxb6! wins the knight.

If Black prevents this by castling kingside, White can gain space on the kingside with moves like g2-g4 and next h2-h4. } ) 
10. Bd3 { White is not in a hurry to take on c6 because for now Black cannot really play e7-e6 since it would leave him with a weak pawn after dxe6, so he first needs to move his knight. } Nb6 ( { Moving the knight to the other side with } 10...Nf6 { is not an improvement. White can choose between simply taking on c6 or playing } 11.Nge2 { , in both cases with a substantial advantage. } ) 
11. Nge2 e6 ( 11...Nxd5 { doesn't work for Black. } 12.Nxd5 cxd5 13.Rb3 { Making use of the fact that 13...Qa4 now loses to first taking 14.Bxd6 exd6 and then 15.Bb5+ winning the queen on a4. } 13...Qxa2 14.Bxd6 exd6 15.Qb4 { And it is game over. White threatens Ra3 and Black doesn't have a good defense without fatally weakening the position of his king. } ) 
12. dxc6 { Of course White takes on c6 and not on e6 where Black could take back with his bishop. } bxc6 
13. Rb3 Qa5 
14. Ne4 { It may look strange to exchange queens, but this is a simple way of implementing White's strategy: gain space and play against the knights on b6 and d6. } Qxd2+ 
15. Nxd2 {[%cal Gc2c4,Ge1g1,Gc4c5,Gd2c4,Gd2e4]} { White has a clear advantage here because Black's pieces do not coordinate. Both knights are badly placed on b6 and d6 and soon White will play c2-c4 (after for example Kf2 or kingside castling) followed by c4-c5 and Ne4 or Nc4 and Black will have a serious lack of space. } *

[Event "The Trompowsky: Simplified"]
[White "2) Trompowsky: 1...Nf6 2.Bg5 Ne4"]
[Black "3...d5 4.f3 Nd6 #2"]
[Date "2023.01.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21519701"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 Ne4 { There are many setups Black can choose against the Trompowsky, but there are two main moves for Black that are played most often: 2...e6 and 2...Ne4. In this chapter we will study 2...Ne4. } 
3. Bf4 { White wants to prove that the knight on e4 is not stable and if it returns to f6, that White has won a tempo for his development. Black claims that if White pushes his pawn to f3, it is not really that useful and might be in the way of the ideal square for the knight on g1. } ( 3.Bh4 { This move has been played quite a lot in practice but I don't like White's position after the moves } 3...g5 4.f3 gxh4 5.fxe4 { It feels to me that White has unnecessarily weakened the dark squares and that he will struggle to maintain the balance. } ) ( 3.h4 { This is a move typically for blitz games, hoping Black will take on g5 and White will benefit from the half-open h-file. } 3...c5 4.d5 h6 { Now the bishop needs to retreat to f4 or c1 and I don't like my pawn on h4. It could become weak in the long term (pawns never move back!) and I prefer to play these positions with my pawn still on h2 (which is part of the repertoire). } ) d5 { This is a very solid approach for Black. In many of the lines that follow there is no advantage for White if Black plays correctly, but the recommended lines are sharp and give Black ample opportunities to go wrong. } 
4. f3 ( { I also analyzed the options } 4.e3 { (after which I think } 4...c5 { is a good response) and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3PnB2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq d6 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nd2 (the simple 4...Nxd2 or 4...Bf5 are both fine for Black). The move 4. f3 is sharper and is more consistent with other lines in the repertoire where we also play this move. } ) Nd6 { A funny move, but guess what: amateurs don't always play the engine's top choice, so it is important that in this repertoire we deal with these kind of moves! } 
5. Nc3 c6 ( 5...e6 6.e4 { Now if Black plays } 6...c6 { we transpose to the line [/variation/21519701/#/6/b] with 5...c6 and 6...e6. } ) 
6. e4 e6 ( 6...Qa5 { Black's idea is to take on e4 twice. } 7.Qd2 e6 8.e5 { White is happy to gain space with tempo. } 8...Nf5 9.g4 Ne7 10.O-O-O { Clearly White is ready to attack if Black were to caste kingside, so Black needs to do something different. } 10...b5 11.Kb1 b4 12.Nce2 c5 { Although Black's king is still in the center, it is not so easy for White to break through. One of the reasons is that the bishop on f4 is misplaced, White would love to have it on for example g3 so he can quickly play f3-f4-f5. } 13.dxc5 { You don't want to allow c5-c4 followed by c4-c3 when White's king is in danger. } 13...Nec6 14.Nc1 Qc7 15.h4 { There is no reason to defend the pawn on e5. If Black plays Nxe5, White has Nd3 and Black will be attacked with g4-g5 after he defends the knight with f7-f6. } 15...a5 16.Be3 Nxe5 { 16...Nd7 Instead of going for the e-pawn, Black targets the c5-pawn. 17.h5 Bxc5 18.Bxc5 Nxc5 19.Bb5 It is okay for White to exchange this bishop. The only good square for it would be d3, but that is covered by the knight on c5. It is more useful to exchange it against the other knight so that White increases his control over square d4. 19...Nd7 20.Bxc6 Qxc6 21.Nge2 And White is a little better with the extra space, control over square d4 and the potential for a kingside attack. Taking 21...Nxe5 is dangerous for Black after 22.Qg5 and if Black castles, White will play f3-f4, Nd4, develop the other knight with Nd3 and then f4-f5. } 17.Qh2 { It is amazing that Black is not immediately lost. Normally such pins are winning for White. } 17...Nbd7 18.Nd3 f6 19.g5 { Opening lines around Black's king. } 19...Nxc5 20.gxf6 gxf6 21.Nxe5 Qxe5 22.Bf4 Qh5 23.Ne2 { White has sacrificed a pawn and the black king is stuck in the middle, but according to the engine Black can hold this. I think in a practical game White has excellent winning chances with his attacking potential. White's next moves could be Nd4-Nb5 and/or Bc1 followed by f3-f4-f5 breaking open the center. } ) 
7. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} { White is just developing his pieces. Black needs to play precisely not to be quickly mated after e4-e5, but the engine of course sees no problems for Black here! } Be7 ( 7...b5 { Instead of using his queen Black decides to push his queenside pawns forward. } 8.Nge2 a5 9.O-O { It just looks less attractive to castle queenside with Black's pawns already so far advanced. } 9...Ba6 { Black has a lack of space so he wants to exchange some pieces. } 10.b3 b4 11.Na4 { White wants to open the c-file later on with c2-c4 so the knight potentially moving to c5 can only be helpful. } 11...Bxd3 12.Qxd3 Be7 13.c4 { The standard way in these type of positions to open the position. The alternative is e4-e5, move the bishop from f4 and play f4-f5. } { 13. ..bxc3 14.Nexc3 Na6 Black lacks good squares for his pieces. 15.Rac1 O-O 16.Qe2 h6 17.h3 White is a little better. He has a better pawn structure (c6 is weak) more space (e4-e5 is always an option) but probably best is to start with moving the king away to h1 (so there are no checks on b6, c5 or d4) followed by Rfd1, and if Black does nothing White can move the knight from c3 to increase the pressure on c6. } ) 
8. Nge2 O-O 
9. O-O { This is a funny position: Black's knight on d6 is misplaced and the bishop on c8 passive, but he doesn't have any weaknesses. White's knight on c3 is in the wrong place (blocking the advance of the c-pawn) and the bishop on f4 is also wrongly placed (White would love to follow up e4-e5 with a quick f3-f4-f5). } b5 
10. b3 { So there is no more Nc4. } Nd7 
11. Qd2 a5 
12. e5 { This is not a must (White can also keep the tension), but White is trying to prove that the knight doesn't have any good squares. } Nf5 
13. g4 Nh4 { So the knight is all the way on the side where it is maybe a little annoying but not as effective as it could have been in the center. } 
14. Bg3 b4 
15. Na4 c5 { The natural break for Black in these types of positions, but luckily for White the knight on a4 does a great job in preventing Bc5 or Qb6. } 
16. Qe3 Bb7 
17. f4 {[%cal Rf4f5,Re7g5,Ga1d1,Gd3b5,Gb5d7]} { And White is a little better in a complex position. For a human it is not easy to play Black's position but objectively Black is still ok here. White may continue with Bb5 and take on d7, he can also start with centralizing his rook with Rad1, just don't play f4-f5 too soon because Bg5 could be really annoying. } *

