1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 Ne4 { There are many setups Black can choose against the Trompowsky, but there are two main moves for Black that are played most often: 2...e6 and 2...Ne4. In this chapter we will study 2...Ne4. } 
3. Bf4 { White wants to prove that the knight on e4 is not stable and if it returns to f6, that White has won a tempo for his development. Black claims that if White pushes his pawn to f3, it is not really that useful and might be in the way of the ideal square for the knight on g1. } ( 3.Bh4 { This move has been played quite a lot in practice but I don't like White's position after the moves } 3...g5 4.f3 gxh4 5.fxe4 { It feels to me that White has unnecessarily weakened the dark squares and that he will struggle to maintain the balance. } ) ( 3.h4 { This is a move typically for blitz games, hoping Black will take on g5 and White will benefit from the half-open h-file. } 3...c5 4.d5 h6 { Now the bishop needs to retreat to f4 or c1 and I don't like my pawn on h4. It could become weak in the long term (pawns never move back!) and I prefer to play these positions with my pawn still on h2 (which is part of the repertoire). } ) d5 { This is a very solid approach for Black. In many of the lines that follow there is no advantage for White if Black plays correctly, but the recommended lines are sharp and give Black ample opportunities to go wrong. } 
4. f3 ( { I also analyzed the options } 4.e3 { (after which I think } 4...c5 { is a good response) and @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/ppp1pppp/8/3p4/3PnB2/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR w KQkq d6 0 4@@EndFEN@@ 4.Nd2 (the simple 4...Nxd2 or 4...Bf5 are both fine for Black). The move 4. f3 is sharper and is more consistent with other lines in the repertoire where we also play this move. } ) Nf6 
5. Nc3 ( { Instead the move } 5.e4 { is also an option, but the lines quickly become messy and I miss a clear logic in the moves that the engines suggest. } ) c5 
6. e4 { White cannot yet transpose to the lines with Nb5 because with the pawn still on e2 Black has the annoying Qa5+. } cxd4 ( 6...e6 7.Nb5 { transposes to the line with 5...e6 and 6...c5 - see the variation [/variation/21519706/#/7/w]. } ) 
7. Qxd4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nc6 {[%cal Rd5d4,Re7e5]} 
8. Bb5 ( { We arrive at a sharp position in which both sides can make mistakes. If White plays } 8.Qd2 { , Black has } 8...d4 { followed by e7-e5 and Black can already claim a clear advantage. } ) Bd7 
9. Qd2 {[%cal Rd5d4,Gb5c6,Gc3e2]} ( { In the book 'Beating 1.d4 sidelines' from Boris Avrukh he only analyzes } 9.Bxc6 { here, but I believe my continuation is more challenging for Black with a higher chance for him to go wrong. } ) e5 ( { If Black now plays } 9...d4 { White takes } 10.Bxc6 { followed by Nce2 and Black is in trouble because he is not able to play e7-e5. } ) { The start of some sharp complications. } 
10. Bxc6 Bxc6 
11. exd5 ( { Stronger than } 11.Bxe5 dxe4 { . } ) exf4 
12. Qe2+ Be7 
13. O-O-O O-O { Some alternatives: } ( 13...Bd7 { This is not ok for Black. } 14.d6 { The only way to win the piece back. } 14...Be6 15.dxe7 Qxe7 16.Qe5 O-O 17.Nge2 { White will win the pawn on f4 and there is no compensation for Black. After taking on f4 White can double rooks on the d-file and any exchanges will only help him to reach a winning endgame. } ) ( 13...Nxd5 14.Nxd5 Bxd5 15.Qb5+ { Stronger than 15. Qe5 after which Black will castle. } 15...Qd7 16.Qxd7+ Kxd7 17.Rxd5+ { White is better in this endgame because Black's extra pawn on the kingside doesn't count, so White is in a way a pawn up (the c-pawn) and Black is fighting for a draw. White's next moves will be Ne2 and Rhd1, and any exchanges of rooks are fine for him. } ) 
14. dxc6 Qc7 
15. Qc4 { Taking on b7 would only help Black in using the open b- and c-file to organize an attack against White's king. } bxc6 
16. Nge2 { Never forget to develop your pieces! } Rab8 { There is no good way to defend the pawn on f4. } 
17. Qxf4 Qa5 
18. Kb1 { White needs to be careful not to get mated. } Rb4 
19. Qc1 Rfb8 
20. b3 {[%cal Gd1d3,Gh1d1,Rf6d5,Gc3d5]} { White is still a pawn up but Black has compensation. I don't see how Black can organize a winning attack. White can strike back with moves like Rd3 and bring the other rook to d1 and any piece exchanges will help White. } *

