1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 Ne4 { There are many setups Black can choose against the Trompowsky, but there are two main moves for Black that are played most often: 2...e6 and 2...Ne4. In this chapter we will study 2...Ne4. } 
3. Bf4 { White wants to prove that the knight on e4 is not stable and if it returns to f6, that White has won a tempo for his development. Black claims that if White pushes his pawn to f3, it is not really that useful and might be in the way of the ideal square for the knight on g1. } ( 3.Bh4 { This move has been played quite a lot in practice but I don't like White's position after the moves } 3...g5 4.f3 gxh4 5.fxe4 { It feels to me that White has unnecessarily weakened the dark squares and that he will struggle to maintain the balance. } ) ( 3.h4 { This is a move typically for blitz games, hoping Black will take on g5 and White will benefit from the half-open h-file. } 3...c5 4.d5 h6 { Now the bishop needs to retreat to f4 or c1 and I don't like my pawn on h4. It could become weak in the long term (pawns never move back!) and I prefer to play these positions with my pawn still on h2 (which is part of the repertoire). } ) g6 { This is not a great setup for Black. } 
4. f3 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
5. e4 d6 { We have now transposed to a kind of Pirc/Modern Defense with an extra tempo for White. } 
6. Nc3 c6 { Black can also play this position with his bishop on g7, which is more in the spirit of Pirc defense but White's moves remain the same, so there is no big difference. } ( 6...Bg7 { is typical play for the Pirc opening but White has one extra tempo. } 7.Qd2 O-O 8.O-O-O { With the extra tempo it makes sense for White to go for a sharp fight. } 8...Re8 9.Bh6 Bh8 { Black has avoided the exchange of his strong bishop. } 10.h4 a6 11.h5 { Now 11...Nxh5 loses immediately because of 12.Rxh5 gxh5 13.Qg5+ and mate. } 11...b5 12.hxg6 hxg6 13.Qf4 Bb7 14.e5 { White is winning. If the knight moves to for example d7, White will play e5-e6 completely opening the kingside and mate is not far away. } ) 
7. Qd2 { Based on White's lead in development the plan is simple: castle queenside and launch an attack either on the kingside or in the center. } Nbd7 
8. g4 b5 { Black is gaining some space but it is not dangerous for White. All of Black's pieces are still in passive positions. } 
9. h4 h6 { Black's idea is to answer h4-h5 with g6-g5. } ( 9...b4 10.Na4 { 10. Nce2 is also a reasonable option. } 10...Qa5 11.b3 { Most of Black's play on the queenside has been stopped. } 11...c5 12.dxc5 { Now on 12...Nxc5 White has the strong 13.a3 . } 12...Bg7 13.a3 { Sacrificing an exchange. } 13...Nxe4 14.fxe4 Bxa1 15.axb4 Qd8 16.Nf3 { White has a knight and a pawn for the rook and is clearly ahead in development. Black is in trouble. } 16...Bb7 { On 16...dxc5 White wins with 17.Qd5! } 17.cxd6 Bg7 { Saving the bishop before it gets locked in. } 18.Bg5 f6 19.Nc5 Nxc5 20.bxc5 { Now on 20...fxg5 White wins with 21.Bb5+ followed by Nxg5 . } 20...exd6 21.Bb5+ Ke7 22.O-O { And White's attack continues. I don't think any player will be able to properly defend Black's position. } ) 
10. Nh3 Bb7 
11. O-O-O {[%cal Ge4e5,Gf1d3,Gh1e1]} { White has a clear advantage: more space, active pieces and ready for action in the center with e4 e5, either directly or after the moves Bd3 and Rhe1. It is hard to see what Black can do against this. } *

