1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 Ne4 { There are many setups Black can choose against the Trompowsky, but there are two main moves for Black that are played most often: 2...e6 and 2...Ne4. In this chapter we will study 2...Ne4. } 
3. Bf4 { White wants to prove that the knight on e4 is not stable and if it returns to f6, that White has won a tempo for his development. Black claims that if White pushes his pawn to f3, it is not really that useful and might be in the way of the ideal square for the knight on g1. } ( 3.Bh4 { This move has been played quite a lot in practice but I don't like White's position after the moves } 3...g5 4.f3 gxh4 5.fxe4 { It feels to me that White has unnecessarily weakened the dark squares and that he will struggle to maintain the balance. } ) ( 3.h4 { This is a move typically for blitz games, hoping Black will take on g5 and White will benefit from the half-open h-file. } 3...c5 4.d5 h6 { Now the bishop needs to retreat to f4 or c1 and I don't like my pawn on h4. It could become weak in the long term (pawns never move back!) and I prefer to play these positions with my pawn still on h2 (which is part of the repertoire). } ) e6 
4. f3 {[%mdl 32768]} Bd6 { A strange setup by Black, but not a bad one at all! } ( 4...Nf6 { is not often played by strong grandmasters and maybe that is the reason it is a bit underestimated. Compared to the line 1.d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 White has the extra move f3, but it is not clear whether that is useful or not. On the one hand it can help with launching a kingside attack with g2-g4, but on the other hand the knight on g1 cannot go to its normal square f3. } 5.e4 d5 { Black can also play Be7 first but sooner or later d7-d5 is the way to go. } 6.e5 { We have transposed to a French opening type of position where the move f3 is not great because usually this pawn needs to go to f4 anyway. } 6...Nfd7 { A logical move but the knight is not so well-placed here. It can go later to b6 but even there White doesn't need to worry. } 7.Be3 c5 8.c3 { The exact move order can differ a bit but in general White puts his bishop on e3, pawns on c3 and f4 and then continues developing. } 8...Nc6 9.f4 cxd4 { If Black releases the tension with c5-c4 White has several options, but I like best the move h2-h4 with the idea h5 to generate play on the kingside. } 10.cxd4 Bb4+ { White doesn't need to be afraid of immediate action by Black in the form of Nb6 and Nc4. White can just take the knight with the f1-bishop and can still claim some space advantage and play against the bad bishop on c8. } 11.Nc3 Nb6 12.Nf3 { If Black now plays Nc4, White can take on c4 followed by f4-f5 opening central lines and potentially opening the way for his d-pawn. } 12...Bd7 13.Rc1 Rc8 14.Bd3 O-O 15.a3 { I also analyzed the bishop sacrifice 15. Bxh7+, but after the black king moves to g6 I wasn't able to find anything clear, while after 15.a3 White can count on a clear space advantage. } 15...Be7 16.O-O { If Black does nothing White can continue with moves like Qc2 and/or g2-g4 followed by f4-f5 with a serious initiative. } 16...f5 { A typical way of stopping White's initiative. In many of these lines it doesn't matter whether Black plays f7-f5 or f7-f6, as White takes usually on f6 anyway. } 17.exf6 Bxf6 18.Bf2 { And White has a nice advantage. He has more space, the pawn on e6 is weak and the bishop on d7 is passive. Typical moves for White are Re1 or Qe2 and Black also needs to watch his kingside becase White always has ideas like Qc2 and after g6 the push h2-h4 or Bb1 and Qd3. } ) 
5. Bxd6 Nxd6 
6. e4 { This looks very strong, but I had trouble demonstrating a clear advantage for White. The reason is that Black doesn't have any structural weaknesses, it is just his knight that is placed in an awkward position. } Nc6 { Black can also start with short castling or even b7-b5. It's likely to result in the same position. } 
7. Nc3 O-O 
8. Qd2 { White is preparing queenside castling, which is the most challenging setup and also it makes it consistent with the rest of the repertoire. If White wants a more quiet game, he could also play Nh3 and Be2 followed by kingside castling, but he needs to be careful Black doesn't take over the initiative with moves like Qh4 or Qf6 in combination with f7-f5. } Rb8 
9. O-O-O b5 { This is not so much the start of an attack, Black is not well organized for that, but he needs more space for his pieces and the c4-square has become an option now for the d6-knight. } 
10. h4 Qe7 
11. Nh3 ( { My engine says that } 11.Qe3 { might be a little stronger, but the difference with } ) ( 11.Nh3 { is not great and the latter fits much better in our overall strategy of developing pieces and then launching an attack. } ) ( 11.Qe3 { is more of a computer move: it works based on some specifics (for example the fact that after d4-d5 the queen can come to c5) but it is not a very human approach. } ) b4 
12. Na4 { There is no need to go back to the passive b1 square from which the knight doesn't have a great future as long as White's queen is on d2. } Nb5 
13. d5 { There was no good way to defend this pawn and opening lines (here the d-file) can only help White who is better developed and has more space. } Ncd4 {[%cal Re6e5]} { If Black takes on d5, White plays exd5 followed by Re1 with a clear advantage. } 
14. dxe6 { Opening lines and files fits in White's strategy while Black was ready to keep the position closed by playing e6-e5. } dxe6 { Black can also take with his knight on e6. White will play Bc4 and is a little better because he has more space and sometimes has the option to invade over the d-file. Also, if the queens get swapped White has some chances because Black's pawn structure on the queenside is suboptimal. } 
15. Bxb5 Nxb5 
16. Nf4 {[%cal Gd2e3,Ga4c5][%csl Rc8]} { White is a little better, he has more space, the bishop on c8 is passive and White dreams of putting a knight on c5 (after for example Qe3). Note that in these types of positions White usually doesn't start running with his g- and h-pawns because Black has no weaknesses on his kingside and therefore such a pawn storm is likely to backfire for White. } *

