4. f3 Bd6 { A strange setup by Black, but not a bad one at all! } ( 4...Nf6 { is not often played by strong grandmasters and maybe that is the reason it is a bit underestimated. Compared to the line 1.d4 Nf6 2. Bf4 e6 White has the extra move f3, but it is not clear whether that is useful or not. On the one hand it can help with launching a kingside attack with g2-g4, but on the other hand the knight on g1 cannot go to its normal square f3. } 5.e4 d5 { Black can also play Be7 first but sooner or later d7-d5 is the way to go. } 6.e5 { We have transposed to a French opening type of position where the move f3 is not great because usually this pawn needs to go to f4 anyway. } 6...Nfd7 { A logical move but the knight is not so well-placed here. It can go later to b6 but even there White doesn't need to worry. } 7.Be3 c5 8.c3 { The exact move order can differ a bit but in general White puts his bishop on e3, pawns on c3 and f4 and then continues developing. } 8...Nc6 9.f4 cxd4 { If Black releases the tension with c5-c4 White has several options, but I like best the move h2-h4 with the idea h5 to generate play on the kingside. } 10.cxd4 Bb4+ { White doesn't need to be afraid of immediate action by Black in the form of Nb6 and Nc4. White can just take the knight with the f1-bishop and can still claim some space advantage and play against the bad bishop on c8. } 11.Nc3 Nb6 12.Nf3 { If Black now plays Nc4, White can take on c4 followed by f4-f5 opening central lines and potentially opening the way for his d-pawn. } 12...Bd7 13.Rc1 Rc8 14.Bd3 O-O 15.a3 { I also analyzed the bishop sacrifice 15. Bxh7+, but after the black king moves to g6 I wasn't able to find anything clear, while after 15.a3 White can count on a clear space advantage. } 15...Be7 16.O-O { If Black does nothing White can continue with moves like Qc2 and/or g2-g4 followed by f4-f5 with a serious initiative. } 16...f5 { A typical way of stopping White's initiative. In many of these lines it doesn't matter whether Black plays f7-f5 or f7-f6, as White takes usually on f6 anyway. } 17.exf6 Bxf6 18.Bf2 { And White has a nice advantage. He has more space, the pawn on e6 is weak and the bishop on d7 is passive. Typical moves for White are Re1 or Qe2 and Black also needs to watch his kingside becase White always has ideas like Qc2 and after g6 the push h2-h4 or Bb1 and Qd3. } ) 
5. Bxd6 Nxd6 
6. e4 f5 { Creative play from Black who is hoping for tricks based on taking on e4 and Qh4+. } 
7. e5 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf7 
8. Nc3 {[%cal Ga1d1,Rd6e5,Rd8d1]} { It is important to start with this move so that if at a later stage Black takes on e5 with his pawn from d6, White can play dxe5 and the queen on d1 is protected by the rook from a1. } d6 
9. f4 dxe5 
10. dxe5 { I don't like taking with the f-pawn here. It would be the standard move, to take towards the center, but in this case Black can continue to attack White's center with c7-c5 and it is not easy to defend. After taking with the d-pawn Black can also try to underminde White's center with g7-g5, but then we still have the option of g2-g3. } g5 
11. g3 Bd7 { Black avoids the exchange of queens. Some alternatives: } ( 11...Qxd1+ { Black decides to swap queens. } 12.Rxd1 Bd7 { Note Black has a threat: 13... Bc6! } 13.h4 { Now the rook can always go to h2. } 13...gxf4 14.gxf4 Rg8 { Black can also play Bc6 after which White will play Rh3. The rook needs to go to h2 if White still has a pawn on g3, but now that White has played gxf4 the rook also has the option of going to h3, the difference with Rh2 is not big, the main thing is that on h3 the rook defends a knight on f3 in case it gets pinned after Bc6. } 15.Be2 { Black was threatening Bc6 and if White's rook moves, the knight on g1 drops. } 15...Bc6 16.Nf3 Nd7 { If Black plays 16...Rg4 , White unpins his rook with 17.Rh3 and then if Black takes 17...Rxf4 , he will end up in a lost position after 18.Ng5 . } 17.Rf1 Ke7 18.Nd4 { White has a nice advantage in this endgame. He can take on c6 at some point after which Black's pawn structure is ruined (Bf3 may already win a pawn) and he also has the threat of playing Bc4 and winning the pawn on e6. } ) ( 11...Nc6 12.Qf3 { Now White avoids the queen swap. Having extra space, he wants to keep pieces on the board. } 12...Qd4 13.Nge2 Qc5 14.O-O-O { This position looks great for White. All of White's pieces are becoming active and Black's king is still in the middle, but there is no direct way for White to strike. } 14...Bd7 15.Bg2 g4 16.Qf1 { 16. Qd3 is an alternative but I prefer not to put the queen on the same line as a black rook (after 16... O-O-O). } 16...O-O-O 17.Qg1 { It may seem strange to exchange queens considering White has more space, but the problem is that there is no way for White to activate the queen while Black's queen is quite active. } 17...Qxg1 18.Rhxg1 { White is a little better. He could consider taking on c6 with the bishop and after bxc6 play Nd4 and prove his knight is stronger than the bishop that needs to defend the pawn on e6. White can also take the simple approach and just play Rd2 and Rgd1. } ) 
12. Qh5 {[%cal Gg1f3,Gf3g5]} { White would love to follow up with Nf3-Nxg5 winning. } Qe7 
13. Nf3 h6 { If Black plays g5-g4, White will play Ng5, exchange twice on f7 and after queenside castling have a clearly better endgame. } 
14. O-O-O Nc6 
15. Bb5 { Completing development. The bishop can go to c4 as well, but it is not easy to increase the pressure against the e6-pawn. } O-O-O 
16. Rhf1 {[%cal Gh5g6,Gf3d4,Gd1d8,Gh8d8]} { White has a nice edge. There is just this annoying pressure on Black's position. There are lines where the rooks get exchanged and suddenly there is Qg6 in combination with Nd4 for White, the knight on f7 cannot move, the pawn on h6 is weak. Yes, engines can probably hold this for Black, but for an over-the-board game I would always pick the white side. } *

