1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 Ne4 { There are many setups Black can choose against the Trompowsky, but there are two main moves for Black that are played most often: 2...e6 and 2...Ne4. In this chapter we will study 2...Ne4. } 
3. Bf4 { White wants to prove that the knight on e4 is not stable and if it returns to f6, that White has won a tempo for his development. Black claims that if White pushes his pawn to f3, it is not really that useful and might be in the way of the ideal square for the knight on g1. } ( 3.Bh4 { This move has been played quite a lot in practice but I don't like White's position after the moves } 3...g5 4.f3 gxh4 5.fxe4 { It feels to me that White has unnecessarily weakened the dark squares and that he will struggle to maintain the balance. } ) ( 3.h4 { This is a move typically for blitz games, hoping Black will take on g5 and White will benefit from the half-open h-file. } 3...c5 4.d5 h6 { Now the bishop needs to retreat to f4 or c1 and I don't like my pawn on h4. It could become weak in the long term (pawns never move back!) and I prefer to play these positions with my pawn still on h2 (which is part of the repertoire). } ) g5 
4. Bc1 {[%mdl 32768]} { White is not impressed by Black's aggressive approach. } h6 { Black can sacrifice the pawn on g5, but he won't find a lot of compensation, so he defends the pawn. } ( 4...g4 { Creative play by Black! } 5.f3 gxf3 6.exf3 Nf6 7.Nc3 { The position looks a lot more normal again compared to when the pawn was on g4. } 7...d5 8.g4 { It's White's turn to use the g-pawn! This move restricts the bishop on c8 and keeps the option open to play g4-g5. } 8...c5 9.g5 { Immediately disrupting Black who was planning to take over the center after 9. dxc5 with 9... e5. } 9...Nh5 10.dxc5 { Now that the knight is no longer on f6, the pawn on d5 hangs. } 10...Bg7 { On 10...d4 White plays 11.Ne4 . } 11.Nge2 d4 12.Ne4 Bf5 13.N4g3 { A nice way to clear the situation. } 13...Nxg3 14.Nxg3 { Now the f1-bishop has space to come out. } 14...Bg6 15.h4 { Threatening h4-h5. } 15...Qc7 16.f4 { Much stronger than 16.Kf2 after which Black has 16...Be5 . } 16...Qxc5 17.Bd3 { Focusing on development. } 17...Bxd3 { Black has to take as f4-f5 was a threat. } 18.cxd3 Nd7 19.O-O { White is clearly better. He has more space and the better bishop, especially after a later f4-f5. White will start with moves like Bd2, Rc1 and Qe2 or Qf3. } ) 
5. f3 Nf6 
6. e4 { Simple chess: White has occupied the center and Black has a pawn on g5 which looks odd. } d5 { This move has rarely been played and Black's setup looks funny, but when I started to analyze it, it became clear White needs to play in a precise way, but if he does, he is likely to end up with a clear advantage. } ( 6...d6 { I think this move is too slow. Black is playing a kind of Pirc/Modern Defense but with pawns on g5 and h6 instead of one on g6, and this structure is a lot more vulnerable. } 7.Nc3 Bg7 8.Be3 { As usual in these structures with a white pawn on f3, White prepares queenside castling. } 8...a6 9.Qd2 b5 10.h4 { This move can also be played after White castles queenside. } 10...g4 { If Black plays b5-b4 White has multiple good options: Nce2 is logical, but Nd1 followed by Nf2 is also fine and there is nothing wrong with Na4. } 11.O-O-O Nbd7 12.Nge2 { It is too early to put pressure on the g4-pawn with Be2 because Black can ignore the threat with Bb7. } 12...Bb7 13.d5 { Black has a bad position - he is close to being lost already. He cannot castle kingside, he doesn't have a lot of space and has no active plan. White is ready to play Nd4 and Nf5 is already a big threat, but if Black manages to defend against that, White can also put pressure on the g4-pawn with Be2. If Black needs to take on f3 there will soon be a white rook on g1. And if Black manages to defend against all this, White can also consider playing f3-f4 followed by e4-e5, escpially if there is a rook on e1, opening lines against Black's king. } ) 
7. e5 { What grabs more space in the center. } Nh5 
8. g4 {[%cal Gh5f4,Rh2h4,Rh1h8,Rc1f4]} Ng7 ( { White knows that if Black plays } 8...Nf4 { here, he will answer } 9.h4 { , exchange rooks on the h-file and exchange the knight on f4, leaving Black with no compensation for the weaknesses in his pawn structure. } ) 
9. h4 { White immediately attacks Black's g-pawn before Black has time to stabilize his position. Note how badly placed the knight on g7 is. To give it a future Black needs to play Ne6, which means for the time being he should refrain from playing e7-e6. } gxh4 
10. Be3 h5 { Black wants to get rid of his weak pawn on h6, but it is not that easy. } 
11. Rxh4 c5 { Black has to take action. If White gets the chance to stabilize and develop his pieces he will have a large advantage because of the extra space, the more active pieces and Black's weak h-pawn. } 
12. Ne2 { It is better for White to keep on developing than to support his center with c2-c3 which is a bit passive. } Nc6 
13. Nbc3 { Continuing to develop and preparing queenside castling. } e6 
14. Rh2 { There is not a big difference between Rh2 and Rh1, I just like the idea that now White still has the option to play Rdh1 or the rook from h2 can come to d2. In both cases White will quickly manage to double rooks. } Be7 
15. Qd2 Bd7 
16. O-O-O {[%cal Rf3f4,Rf4f5]} { White is clearly better here. If Black were to play something like c5-c4, taking away all the pressure on White's center, White will be close to winning after f3-f4-f5. So Black has to take some action. }-- ( { Let me give a sample line so you have an idea of typical play here: } 16...Qa5 17.dxc5 { It may look strange to take on c5 but White wants to open lines against Black's king. } 17...Nxe5 { If Black takes on c5, White exchanges bishops followed by the crushing Qg5. } 18.Nd4 O-O-O 19.Bf4 { And now Black needs to weaken his pawn structure with f7-f6 because } 19...Nc6 { would lose the queen after } 20.Nb3 { . Once Black has played f7-f6, White can simply play Nb3 and later put his rooks on the e-file and Black faces some serious difficulties. } )
*

