He is not in a hurry but there is always the potential to play his h2-pawn to h5 and g4-g5-g6 to soften the defense of the black king. } 9...b4 10.Nce2 a5 11.Ng3 { The main idea of putting the knight on g3 is that if in the future White plays d4-d5 and Black responds with e6-e5, he will have a weak square on f5 where the White knight will jump to. There is also a second idea that if White plays g4-g5, Black no longer has Nh5 to stop White's advance of the h-pawn. } 11...c5 12.g5 Nfd7 13.d5 { White has a nice advantage and especially in an over-the-board game Black players will struggle to keep their position together.

