1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 Ne4 { There are many setups Black can choose against the Trompowsky, but there are two main moves for Black that are played most often: 2...e6 and 2...Ne4. In this chapter we will study 2...Ne4. } 
3. Bf4 { White wants to prove that the knight on e4 is not stable and if it returns to f6, that White has won a tempo for his development. Black claims that if White pushes his pawn to f3, it is not really that useful and might be in the way of the ideal square for the knight on g1. } ( 3.Bh4 { This move has been played quite a lot in practice but I don't like White's position after the moves } 3...g5 4.f3 gxh4 5.fxe4 { It feels to me that White has unnecessarily weakened the dark squares and that he will struggle to maintain the balance. } ) ( 3.h4 { This is a move typically for blitz games, hoping Black will take on g5 and White will benefit from the half-open h-file. } 3...c5 4.d5 h6 { Now the bishop needs to retreat to f4 or c1 and I don't like my pawn on h4. It could become weak in the long term (pawns never move back!) and I prefer to play these positions with my pawn still on h2 (which is part of the repertoire). } ) c5 
4. f3 Nf6 
5. d5 ( { My main recommendation is } 5.dxc5 { , but I want to show why I'm not opting for } ) ( 5.d5 { instead. } ) Nh5 
6. Bc1 { This is quite slow and Black immediately takes action. } ( 6.Be3 { This has also been tried in practice and with a slight delay we will end up in a kind of Benoni-Modern Defense hybrid. } 6...d6 7.Nc3 g6 8.g4 { White's best chance to play for an advantage. } 8...Nf6 9.h4 h5 { Of course Black puts a stop to White's plans, who now needs to focus on the long-term plan of achieving f3-f4-f5. } 10.g5 Nfd7 11.Bd2 { Making space for the e-pawn. } 11...Bg7 12.e4 Na6 { The position starts to look more familiar after this strange series of opening moves. } 13.f4 Nc7 14.Nf3 Rb8 { White plays on the kingside, Black on the queenside. } 15.a4 a6 16.Bh3 b5 17.f5 Nb6 { And Black has active counterplay on the queenside. } ) e6 
7. dxe6 fxe6 ( { Note that } 7...Qh4+ { looks winning for Black but it actually becomes messy after } 8.g3 Nxg3 9.exf7+ { and the complications are likely to end in White's favor. } ) 
8. Nh3 Nc6 
9. e4 Nf6 { Both sides complete their development. } 
10. Nc3 Be7 
11. Bc4 O-O 
12. O-O Ne5 
13. Be2 d5 { And objectively speaking the position might still be in balance, but I prefer Black. His position looks a lot more natural than White's with his knight on h3 and the pawns on f3-e4. } 
*

