13. h5 {[%cal Rh7h6,Gh5g6][%csl Rg6]} { If Black doesn't want to deal with a thorn on h6 for the rest of the game, he better play ...h6, after which taking on g6 will give Black a weakness on the kingside, meanwhile our queenside is safe and sound. Play through the remaining moves to see how the game could develop. } h6 
14. hxg6 fxg6 { White has achieved a weak pawn on g6 and (potential) weak squares on d5 and e6. Kingside castling no longer looks like an option for Black. } 
15. g5 Nh5 
16. Nge2 {[%cal Rh5f4,Ge2f4,Gf4g6,Re6f7,Gf4d5]} hxg5 ( { If Black now takes on } 16...Nxf4 { , White plays } 17.Nxf4 { and g6 can only be defended by } 17...Bf7 { , but then there is also } 18.Nfd5 { . } ) 
17. Bxg5 O-O-O { The only place for the black king to hide. } 
18. Bh3 Bxh3 
19. Rxh3 Bg7 
20. Be3 {[%cal Gf3f4,Gf4f5,Gd1h1,Gd1g1][%csl Rg6,Rh5]} { White has a nice advantage. He has the idea of playing f3-f4-f5 in combination with Rdh1, but also the simple Rg1 targeting the pawn on g6 is a good option. } *

