7. b3 {[%mdl 32768]} { In practice the move Bc1 is also often played, but I like simple chess: 1) we don't sacrifice the pawn in b2 for crazy complications in any of these Trompowsky lines and 2) we want to develop all our pieces and attack, so why would we go back with the bishop to c1 if we have an equally good alternative in b2-b3? } g6 { Black wants to put his bishop on g7 so White has to play c4 now and his knight to c3 before Black can take control over the long diagonal. } 
8. c4 Bg7 
9. Nc3 d6 { Black has no tricks based on the knight on c3. White is always in time. } 
10. e4 O-O 
