le bit better with his beautiful knight on c6 and the potential to double on the c-file. If Black now takes on c6, White has dxc6 followed by Nd5. } ) 
12. Bh6 { White really wants to get rid of the strong g7-bishop. } Bxh6 
13. Qxh6 exd5 
14. cxd5 { If possible, we take with the c-pawn back on d5 so that the e-file stays closed and square c4 becomes available for a white knight. } Nbd7 
15. Nh3 {[%cal Gh3f2,Gf2g4,Gf1e2,Ge1g1]} { This knight usually finds a good spot on f2 in this structure, it takes control over essential squares and later in the game White is ready for f3-f4.

It may appear a kingside attack is lurking, but don't forget to get your king to safety. White's biggest asset in this position is the extra central space. Play through the remaining moves to see how the middlegame might continue. } Ne5 
16. Nf2 Bd7 
17. Qd2 { It is not a must to play this move at this point, but White realizes that a direct kingside attack is unlikely to succeed. It is more important to first stabilize the position and then push Black back with f3-f4. } Rac8 
18. Be2 c4 { A very typical plan for Black. He wants to create play on the queenside, but it is not easy without the g7-bishop. } 
19. Rb1 cxb3 
20. Rxb3 Qc5 
21. O-O {[%cal Gf3f4,Gf1b1][%csl Rd6]} { White is a bit better here because he has the better pawn structure, more space and he can at some point push Black back with f3-f4. In these type of positions Black really misses his bishop on g7. White also has the option to exchange queens, since in most endgames he will be better because of the half-open b-file and the weakness of the d6-pawn. } *

