1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 d5 { Black immediately occupies the center so that if White later wants to play c2-c4, he has the option to take on c4, which leads to very different play than we have seen in the previous two chapters. } 
3. Bxf6 {[%mdl 32768]} { Just to be consistent, if we can give Black doubled pawns we will do so! } gxf6 { An ambitious way of recapturing, and one that has been chosen by strong Grandmasters such as Anand, So, MVL and Giri. } 
4. e3 { If Black now plays passively, White has the option to play Qh5 and target the weaknesses in Black's pawn structure. } Bf5 
5. c4 { Of course, with the bishop gone from c8 White is happy to attack the light squares on Black's queenside. } c6 
