Objectively speaking, all these moves (including 6. g3) result in an equal position when you analyze with the engine. However, the move 6.Bb5 often means you need to take on c6 and play a position of two knights against two bishops. For grandmasters this is fine, but on an amateur level I would not recommend this, as there is too much strategic risk that you open the position at the wrong moment and the bishops become monsters.

So I considered the alternatives on move six, but also kept in mind that if we play something unusual we make it a lot harder for our opponents, despite the fact that the engine gives equal play. } ) Qa5+ { Black takes the safe way and immediately wins back the pawn on c5. } 
