1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 { In this chapter we will study the lines where Black keeps his knight on f6 and is not afraid of doubled f-pawns. } g6 
3. Bxf6 { Just to be consistent, we take to give Black doubled pawns. There are other alternatives for White but it would mean a different middlegame structure. } exf6 
4. c4 {[%cal Rc4d5,Rd7d5]} { The idea is to play c2-c4 as soon as possible so we can take on d5 if Black puts a pawn there. } Bg7 ( 4...Bb4+ { Not many players will play like this (Bg7 is the natural move) but the engine says it is ok for Black. } 5.Nd2 { The knight could have gone to c3 as well, but then Black has the option to take on c3 and we get a pawn structure we have not seen anywhere else in the repertoire so I decided to avoid it. } 5...c6 6.a3 Be7 7.e3 { The pawns on d4 and b2 are both vulnerable to Qb6 attacks so that is why it is a good idea to play e3 now and not later. } 7...d5 { Black needs to play this move sooner or later. With his bishop on e7 it doesn't make sense to put the pawn on d6. } 8.cxd5 cxd5 9.g3 Nd7 { Putting the knight on c6 is not effective because the d4-pawn is well defended, the b4-square is not available for the knight and there is no e7-e5 break to support. It is more logical to put this knight either on f6 (and maybe later e4) or on b6 (and maybe later c4). } 10.Bg2 Nb6 11.Ne2 { White prefers his knight on e2 compared to f3 because now it can go to either f4 or c3 to increase the pressure on d5. } 11...O-O 12.O-O Kg7 13.Rc1 { White is maybe a little better, maybe it is equal, but in a practical game White players will feel more comfortable: White can play on the queenside and put pressure on d5 with moves like Nf4-Nd3, Nb3-Nc5 and Qb3 and for Black it is not easy to become active. } ) 
5. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} { In these systems with doubled f-pawns, White's long term play will be on the queenside, but first he needs to develop his pieces. Typically the knights go to e2 and c3 and the bishop to g2. } f5 
6. g3 O-O 
7. Bg2 d6 
8. e3 c6 {[%csl Gd4,Ge3]} { Black can put his knight on c6 but it would not be very effective because White's pawn on d4 is well defended and there is no e7-e5 push to support. So more logical for Black is to play his knight via d7 to f6 and maybe later to e4. } 
9. Nge2 Nd7 
10. O-O Nf6 
11. b4 { Now that White has castled it is time to expand on the queenside. } Be6 
12. Qd3 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5,Gf1b1,Gb4b5]} { The position is about equal, maybe a little better for White, but more importantly: it is easier to play for White. He can play on the queenside with moves like a2-a4-a5, Rfb1, b4-b5 and if Black defends with Rc8, take on c6 and play Rb7 and double rooks on the b-file.

For Black it is hard to become active, he can play g6-g5, but it is only weakening because there is no f5-f4 any time soon. Maybe he should not have gone Be6, but Bd7, and then Re8 and Qe7 and Ne4, he has then a bit more control in the center but still no threats. If Black ever plays d6-d5, White's standard reaction is c4-c5 followed by b4-b5. } *

