1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 c5 { A direct attack on White's center. } 
3. d5 {[%mdl 32768]} { The first alternative I looked at was to take on f6, similar to the lines where Black plays d7-d6 on move two. However, here Black can push his pawn to d5 in one go after he has recaptured on f6 with his e-pawn if White plays with e3 and c3, and if White plays d4-d5 then Qb6 is annoying. } ( { A sample line to illustrate why I believe } 3.Bxf6 { is not critical: } 3...exf6 4.Nc3 d5 { As said, the pawn immediately goes to d5. } 5.e3 Be6 6.Nge2 Nc6 { Black just completes development. } 7.a3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Bd6 9.Be2 O-O 10.O-O { Black is fully developed and now starts a specific operation to increase the effectiveness of his pair of bishops. } 10...Nxd4 11.Qxd4 { Taking back with the pawn also doesn't equalize. } 11...Be5 12.Qa4 Qc7 { And Black is already a little bit better. That is not how we want to play the Trompowsky! } ) Ne4 { This is a typical knight jump that we see in many different Trompowsky lines. } 
4. Bc1 { Of course, moving the bishop to f4 is a valid alternative as well. The reason I don't recommend it is 1) Black can play Qb6 and then Bc1 is the best move and 2) with the bishop on f4 Black can later offer an exchange of bishops with Bd6 and this takes us away from the typical Trompowsky play we are aiming for. } ( 4.Bf4 { This is a sample line to illustrate why I don't like Bf4. } 4...e6 5.f3 Bd6 { Modern chess. Black has less space than White and White has a potential weakness on a dark square (e3) so Black is happy to offer the exchange of bishops. } 6.Bxd6 Nxd6 7.e4 b5 { Active play by Black. } 8.Nc3 b4 9.Na4 { The knight is a bit offside here, but Nce2 would really slow down White's development. } 9...Qc7 10.Ne2 O-O 11.Ng3 { Now that Black has a pawn on e6, the f5-square is not available for the knight on g3. The knight is not so well positioned on g3 but it had to make room for the bishop on f1. } 11...Ba6 12.Bxa6 Nxa6 13.O-O Nb5 { And we have a position with mutual chances but it is also a bit static, not the type of dynamic play that we look for when we play the Trompowsky! } ) Qa5+ { This is a smart move order by Black where he prevents White from supporting his d-pawn with c2-c4. } ( { Note that the retreating move } 4...Nf6 { would transpose directly to the line @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@ 1.d4 c5 2.d5 Nf6 , discussed in the final chapter [/variation/21673588/#/2/b] of this course. } ) ( { If Black plays } 4...g6 { , White continues with } 5.f3 Nf6 6.e4 Bg7 7.Nc3 { . These types of positions we have seen before, and they are called Benoni structures, either with a pawn on c4 and then Nc3 or immediately Nc3. If Black allows, we play Bb5+, otherwise we can play Bd3, a2-a4 (preventing b7-b5!), Nf3 and O-O. } ) 
5. c3 ( 5.Nd2 { feels awkward after Black plays c5-c4 and } ) ( 5.Bd2 { is not in the spirit of the sharp, complex fight we are looking for. } ) e6 
6. f3 { Consistent with other lines in the repertoire, we play this move to chase away the knight from e4. } Nf6 
7. e4 d6 
8. Na3 { The idea is to put a knight on c4 so that we target the weak pawn on d6. } exd5 
9. exd5 Nbd7 
10. Nh3 { The best square for the knight. It may look strange, but on f2 it will be fine and going to e2 isn't great because Black can play Nb6 and attack the pawn on d5. } Be7 ( 10...Nb6 { The most principled approach from Black and it is important for us to understand why it doesn't work. } 11.Bb5+ Bd7 12.Bxd7+ Kxd7 { Taking back with the knight would mean the d5-pawn is no longer hanging. White would castle kingside and have a nice advantage based on extra space, the weak pawn on d6 and the queen on a5 that is offside. } 13.O-O Nbxd5 14.Ng5 { It's unusual, but Black cannot really defend the pawn on f7. } 14...h6 15.Nxf7 Rg8 16.c4 { White will get his 'trapped knight' out by simple means. } 16...Nc7 17.Ne5+ { And White is winning. The black king is in great danger and the white knight on f7 got out. Moreover, the pawn on d6 is weak and White can target it with Ng6, take on f8 and Bf4 and Nb5. } ) 
11. Nc4 { This was always White's idea. c4 is a good outpost for the knight. } Qc7 
12. a4 { You don't want to play Nc4 and then one or two moves later be chased away by b7-b5, so a2-a4 is the way to go. } Ne5 { Standard play. Black is short on space so he wants to exchange pieces. } 
13. Nf2 Nxc4 
14. Bxc4 O-O 
15. O-O { White has extra space based on the pawn on d5 and the pawn on d6 is a bit weak. White can consider gaining more space one day by playing g2-g4, limiting the effectiveness of the bishop on c8 and under the right circumstances threatening to play g4-g5. Play through the remaining moves to see how play could develop. } Bd7 
16. b3 { This move can also be played later. } a6 
17. Re1 { Black wanted to play b7-b5 but he first needs to defend the bishop on e7. } Rfe8 
18. Bf1 Rab8 ( { And now again } 18...b5 { is not possible because White takes } 19.axb5 axb5 { , then exchanges rooks } 20.Rxa8 Rxa8 { and takes the bishop with } 21.Rxe7 { . } ) 
19. c4 { b7-b5 cannot be stopped, but White has made sure it is not dangerous anymore. } b5 
20. axb5 axb5 
21. g4 { Gaining space on the kingside. } Bf8 
22. Bd3 g6 
23. Bf4 {[%cal Gg1g2,Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Ge1h1,Gg4g5,Gf2e4][%csl Rd6,Rg8]} { White has some advantage. He can target the pawn on d6 by playing g4-g5 followed by Ne4, but he can also start a kingside attack by playing Kg2, Rh1 and h2-h4-h5. Meanwhile Black doesn't have any concrete plans. } *

