1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 c5 { A direct attack on White's center. } 
3. d5 { The first alternative I looked at was to take on f6, similar to the lines where Black plays d7-d6 on move two. However, here Black can push his pawn to d5 in one go after he has recaptured on f6 with his e-pawn if White plays with e3 and c3, and if White plays d4-d5 then Qb6 is annoying. } ( { A sample line to illustrate why I believe } 3.Bxf6 { is not critical: } 3...exf6 4.Nc3 d5 { As said, the pawn immediately goes to d5. } 5.e3 Be6 6.Nge2 Nc6 { Black just completes development. } 7.a3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Bd6 9.Be2 O-O 10.O-O { Black is fully developed and now starts a specific operation to increase the effectiveness of his pair of bishops. } 10...Nxd4 11.Qxd4 { Taking back with the pawn also doesn't equalize. } 11...Be5 12.Qa4 Qc7 { And Black is already a little bit better. That is not how we want to play the Trompowsky! } ) Ne4 { This is a typical knight jump that we see in many different Trompowsky lines. } 
4. Bc1 { Of course, moving the bishop to f4 is a valid alternative as well. The reason I don't recommend it is 1) Black can play Qb6 and then Bc1 is the best move and 2) with the bishop on f4 Black can later offer an exchange of bishops with Bd6 and this takes us away from the typical Trompowsky play we are aiming for. } ( 4.Bf4 { This is a sample line to illustrate why I don't like Bf4. } 4...e6 5.f3 Bd6 { Modern chess. Black has less space than White and White has a potential weakness on a dark square (e3) so Black is happy to offer the exchange of bishops. } 6.Bxd6 Nxd6 7.e4 b5 { Active play by Black. } 8.Nc3 b4 9.Na4 { The knight is a bit offside here, but Nce2 would really slow down White's development. } 9...Qc7 10.Ne2 O-O 11.Ng3 { Now that Black has a pawn on e6, the f5-square is not available for the knight on g3. The knight is not so well positioned on g3 but it had to make room for the bishop on f1. } 11...Ba6 12.Bxa6 Nxa6 13.O-O Nb5 { And we have a position with mutual chances but it is also a bit static, not the type of dynamic play that we look for when we play the Trompowsky! } ) d6 { This can transpose to other setups, but here we will look at something specific. } 
5. f3 {[%mdl 32768]} { As usual, chasing the knight away from e4 at the first opportunity. } Qa5+ ( { If Black immediately returns with } 5...Nf6 { , White can continue with } 6.e4 { , Nc3, Bd3, a4 and Nge2 followed by castling. These types of positions with Benoni pawn structures are discussed in more detail in other parts of the course. } ) 
6. Nd2 ( { White could also play } 6.c3 { when we are likely to transpose to the line with 4...Qa5+ - see the variation [/variation/21553223/#/5/w]. } ) Nf6 
7. e4 e6 
8. Kf2 { An original way of defending the pawn on d5: if Black now takes twice, he gets hit by Nb3 or Nc4. The knight is no longer pinned now that the king has moved to f2. } Qc7 
9. Nc4 { Black threatened to take on d5 and White wants to make space for his bishop on f1. } b5 { A principled approach from Black and one of the rare occasions in our repertoire that Black gets the chance to push b7-b5. } ( 9...exd5 { Black is playing his standard setup. } 10.exd5 Nbd7 11.a4 { We always want to prevent b7-b5. } 11...Be7 { Note that Black doesn't have time to fianchetto his bishop to g7 due to Qe1+. } 12.g4 { We have seen this move also in other lines where Black castles kingside. Here we will look at how to play if Black castles queenside. } 12...Ne5 13.Ne3 { White has a space advantage so he would like to keep as many pieces on the board as possible. } 13...Bd7 14.h4 O-O-O 15.Ne2 { And we have a complex position. The engine thinks that Black's top three choices are Rdf8, Rhf8 and Ng8 and I don't expect any human to play like that against you! White's plan is to play Ng3-Ngf5 and then start some actions on the queenside with c2-c3 followed by b2-b4, perhaps after Be2 so that the rook from h1 can quickly join the attack. } ) 
10. Ne3 a6 
11. a4 { Black would like to keep his pawn on b5 so he has control over the c4-square, but White doesn't allow it. } exd5 
12. exd5 b4 { Now the c4-square is under White's control. } 
13. h4 Nbd7 
14. h5 { White is grabbing space on the kingside. } h6 ( { The engine also suggests } 14...g6 { but I cannot imagine any human playing like that. White would take on g6 so that after fxg6 there is a big hole on e6. } ) 
15. Ne2 Be7 
16. g4 { With similar play to other lines. The main difference is that here Black's pawn is on b4 instead of b7, but the c4-square is still under White's control. } O-O 
17. Ng3 Re8 
18. Kg2 {[%cal Gc2c3,Gf1d3,Gd3c2,Gd1d3,Gf3f4,Gg4g5,Ga1e1,Gg3f5,Ge3f5]} { White has some advantage based on the extra space. White is not in a hurry, but in the long term he has good attacking chances with moves like c2-c3, Bd3-Bc2 and Qd3 followed by f3-f4 and g4-g5. Before that it is always useful to put a knight on f5 and to activate the rook on a1. } *

