5. c4 {[%mdl 32768]} Qa5+ ( { A critical move, but Black also has alternatives - for example, } 5...b5 { and then White should probably play } 6.Nd2 { . } ) ( { Instead of } 5...b5 { Black can also go } ) ( 5...Be7 { and White will just continue development with } 6.Nf3 { . } ) 
6. Nd2 { There is no reason to give up the bishop with Bd2. } b5 { Black is playing in the spirit of the Benoni/Benko Gambit. } 
7. e3 ( { The engine gives a sharp alternative with the move } 7.b4 { but I recommend simple play: create space to develop the bishop to d3 if Black plays something like a7-a6. } ) bxc4 
8. Bxc4 Bb7 ( { If Black plays } 8...Nd6 { I would wonder whether he is checking the position with an engine! Anyway, we can just drop back with our bishop } 9.Be2 { and if Black takes the pawn on d5 we will win it back later after playing Ng1-h3-f4. } ) 
9. dxe6 fxe6 { Black is taking an aggressive approach: he has weakened his pawn structure but hopes to gain more control in the center than if he would have taken back with his d-pawn. } ( 9...dxe6 { is a more solid approach. } 10.Ngf3 { White needs to complete development and castle before taking any action. } 10...Be7 11.O-O Nd6 12.Bd3 { A logical square for the bishop. It has its eye on h7 and also prepares a later e3-e4. } 12...O-O 13.Qc2 { Not just looking at h7 but also at the weak c5-pawn. } 13...Nc6 { Black is using a small trick: if White were to take on h7 with check he would be in trouble because after Kh8 Black has two threats: g7-g6 and Nb4 and it is hard for White to defend against both. } 14.a3 { Now if Black plays Rac8, White just continues with b2-b3, Bb2 and Rac1 with a stable advantage. } 14...c4 { A typical engine suggestion. } 15.Nxc4 Nxc4 16.Bxc4 { These types of positions are also known from other openings, for example the Chebanenko Slav, where Black has active play as compensation for the pawn. } 16...Ne5 17.Nxe5 Qxe5 18.Bd2 { It is essential for White to complete his development. } 18...Rac8 19.b3 { Objectively speaking the position is about equal, but I still see an extra pawn for White that Black doesn't win back so easily. White's next moves include Bc3, maybe Qe2 so that the queen can help defending the king, one rook to c1 or d1 maybe after a3-a4. The other rook can stay on f1 for now, and if things are getting really scary around White's king, he always has the option of playing f2-f4. } ) 
