1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 c5 { A direct attack on White's center. } 
3. d5 { The first alternative I looked at was to take on f6, similar to the lines where Black plays d7-d6 on move two. However, here Black can push his pawn to d5 in one go after he has recaptured on f6 with his e-pawn if White plays with e3 and c3, and if White plays d4-d5 then Qb6 is annoying. } ( { A sample line to illustrate why I believe } 3.Bxf6 { is not critical: } 3...exf6 4.Nc3 d5 { As said, the pawn immediately goes to d5. } 5.e3 Be6 6.Nge2 Nc6 { Black just completes development. } 7.a3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Bd6 9.Be2 O-O 10.O-O { Black is fully developed and now starts a specific operation to increase the effectiveness of his pair of bishops. } 10...Nxd4 11.Qxd4 { Taking back with the pawn also doesn't equalize. } 11...Be5 12.Qa4 Qc7 { And Black is already a little bit better. That is not how we want to play the Trompowsky! } ) d6 { Black is indicating that he would like to transpose to a typical Kings-Indian - Benoni type of structure with his bishop on g7. } 
4. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} { If White plays c2-c4, we actually have transposed to lines of the Benoni where Black gets the extra move h7-h6 for free and I think that can only help him because g6-g5 is a standard move in Benoni setups. So I prefer to avoid such a transposition and that's why we play 4.Nc3 instead. } h6 { Black is asking White a difficult question: do you want to take on f6? } ( 4...a6 { doesn't have independent value. } 5.a4 Nbd7 6.e4 h6 7.Bc1 { The bishop can also go to e3 and we have a typical kind of Benoni structure with the some advantages for White: he has his pawn on c2, so c4 is still available for a knight, Black hasn't played e7-e6 yet and the h-pawn is on h6, not on h7 and could become weak. } { The reason I inidicate 7.Bc1 here is that it soon transposes to another line, but in a blitz game based on intuition I would probably play 7.Be3 . } 7...g6 8.Bd3 { And we have transposed to the line with 4... h6. } ) 
5. Bc1 { I analyzed 5. Bxf6 but could not find an easy way of playing for White. The lines become quite complex and often Black will attack White's center with f6-f5. Dropping back to c1 is consistent with other lines and keeps things relatively simple. } g6 { Both sides will now play like it is a Benoni with the main difference that White's pawn is still on c2. } 
6. e4 Bg7 
7. Bd3 ( { This is a bit more aggressive than } 7.Be2 { . Maybe one day we can benefit from the weakening of the g6-pawn now that Black has already played h7-h6. } ) a6 
8. a4 { In general I always try to avoid b7-b5 if possible. } e6 
9. h3 { So Black can forget about Bg4 ideas after exchanging on d5. } O-O 
10. Nf3 { This move is possible because on move 12 White still has Be3. If that were not the case than either h2-h3 was too slow or White should have played 10.Nge2. But here we are in time and f3 is the natural square for the knight. } exd5 
11. exd5 Re8+ 
12. Be3 Nbd7 ( { Black has no way to take advantage of White's somewhat slow approach, there is no Ng4 or Ne4 and after } 12...Rxe3+ { Black lacks a good follow-up. } ) 
13. O-O {[%cal Ge3f4,Gd2c4,Gc3b1,Gb1d2]} { Maybe it is equal, maybe a little better for White, but the position is certainly easier to play for White. He has more space and it is hard for Black to get b7-b5 in. Yes, Black may play Ne5 at some point, but White can always take and after Rxe5 play Bf4 when the pressure on the weak pawn on d6 grows. In the long-term White could even consider playing Nb1-Nd2 (or Na3) followed by Nc4. Another option for White is just to play Qd2, simple chess. If Black plays h5 he has a hole on g5 and if Black plays Kh7, the king is in the line of the bishop on d3 and a future f2-f4-f5 can become dangerous. } *

