2. Bg5 c5 { A direct attack on White's center. } 
3. d5 { The first alternative I looked at was to take on f6, similar to the lines where Black plays d7-d6 on move two. However, here Black can push his pawn to d5 in one go after he has recaptured on f6 with his e-pawn if White plays with e3 and c3, and if White plays d4-d5 then Qb6 is annoying. } ( { A sample line to illustrate why I believe } 3.Bxf6 { is not critical: } 3...exf6 4.Nc3 d5 { As said, the pawn immediately goes to d5. } 5.e3 Be6 6.Nge2 Nc6 { Black just completes development. } 7.a3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Bd6 9.Be2 O-O 10.O-O { Black is fully developed and now starts a specific operation to increase the effectiveness of his pair of bishops. } 10...Nxd4 11.Qxd4 { Taking back with the pawn also doesn't equalize. } 11...Be5 12.Qa4 Qc7 { And Black is already a little bit better. That is not how we want to play the Trompowsky! } ) e5 { Black is going for a closed setup which is a bit passive here. } 
4. d6 { This is a sharp move that I think can also give White some advantage. The reason to play this is if you enjoy sharp play, the reason not to play it is that it requires specific knowledge that you don't see coming back in other lines. The main idea of the move d6 is to reduce the mobility of Black's pieces. If White can keep the pawn he will have a large advantage. The critical lines are the ones where White loses the pawn and the question is whether Black loses so much time that White can still claim some advantage. } Qb6 { Probably Black's best response to 4.d6. } ( 4...Qa5+ 5.Nc3 Ne4 { This has to be the idea of 4... Qa5+, but it is not sufficient to equalize. } 6.Bd2 Nxd6 { The only way for Black to fight for equality is to win the pawn on d6, but this specific line is not ok for him. } { 6...Nxd2 is way too slow. 7.Qxd2 There is no way for Black to win the pawn on d6 and that makes his position miserable, as there is no space to develop his pieces. 7...Nc6 8.Nf3 With the tactical point that if Black now plays 8...Nd4 to win the pawn on d6, White wins with 9.Nxe5 Bxd6 10.Nc4 Qc7 11.e3 . 8...g6 9.h4 Black doesn't have sufficient defenders around his king. 9...Bg7 10.h5 O-O 11.e4 Very simple but effective play from White. Black can barely move a piece. 11...a6 12.hxg6 hxg6 13.Bc4 And White will soon win in the attack after castling queenside and bringing his queen to g5. } 7.e4 Be7 8.f4 { Making use of the unfortunate position of the knight. } 8...Nc6 { Taking on f4 is too slow for Black. White will get a large advantage with Nd5 followed by Bxf4. } 9.Nf3 O-O { Giving back the pawn. } 10.fxe5 Ne8 11.Bf4 { Now Black can forget about breaking free with d7-d6. } 11...Nc7 12.Be2 Ne6 13.Bg3 Ncd4 14.O-O { White has completed his development and is ready to start attacking. } 14...Nxe2+ 15.Qxe2 b6 16.Nd5 Bd8 17.c4 { With a large advantage for White. He is not even material down and his pieces are so much more active and have a lot more space. He can either attack the black queen with moves like a3 and b4 or start an attack on the king by first playing Be1, then Qf2-Qg3 followed by Bd2 and h2-h4-h5. } ) ( 4...h6 5.Bh4 g5 { This doesn't look great for the bishop on f8. } { 5...Qb6 6.Bxf6 gxf6 7.Nc3 is basically a transposition to the line 4...Qb6 except that Black's pawn is now on h6 instead of h7, but I cannot see why that would make a relevant difference. }{ 5...Nc6 6.Nc3 g5 7.Bg3 Transposes to the line with 5...g5. } 6.Bg3 Nc6 7.Nc3 Bg7 8.e3 { I like this more than 8. e4 when Black gets the d4-square for his knight. } 8...Qa5 9.h4 { Weakening the g5-pawn. } 9...g4 10.Bb5 O-O 11.Nge2 Re8 12.a4 { So that Black can forget about any kind of b7-b5 break. } 12...a6 13.Bd3 Qb4 { Black wants to play e5-e4. } 14.f3 gxf3 15.gxf3 { Now the g-file is open which White can use to attack. } 15...Na5 16.Kf2 { Stronger than kingside castling because now g1 is available for a rook and the king is safe on f2. } 16...b6 { Finally developing the bishop on c8, but once White plays e3-e4, the bishop will still be passive. } 17.h5 { Making the h4-square available for the bishop to help in the attack. } 17...Bb7 18.Bf5 Nc4 19.Bh4 { There are other strong moves as well, such as 19.Rg1. } 19...Kh8 20.e4 { And Black is lost. Both his bishops are still passive while White is launching a big attack with Rg1, b3 followed by Qd2 and there is no defense for Black while White can keep bringing more resources to the kingside. } ) 
5. Bxf6 { As always in this repertoire, if we can give Black doubled f-pawns, we will! } gxf6 
6. Nc3 { White has to play actively because the pawn on d6 could be lost, so moves like b2-b3 don't come into consideration. } Qxb2 ( 6...Na6 7.e4 Qxb2 8.Nd5 { White threatens to take on a6 followed by Nc7+. } 8...Nb4 { Now Nxc2+ is something that needs to be addressed. } 9.Rb1 Qxc2 { Black would get an even worse version of the endgame if he plays 9...Qd4. } { 9...Nxc2+ just loses a piece. 10.Kd2 Bh6+ 11.f4 And White wins the knight on c2. } 10.Qxc2 Nxc2+ 11.Kd2 Nd4 { And now it is time for White to pick up the rook on a8. } 12.Nc7+ Kd8 13.Nxa8 Bxd6 14.Ne2 { White needs to develop his pieces. There is no way to save the knight on a8, so he has to maximize the activity of his other pieces. } 14...b6 15.Nc3 Bb7 16.Nxb6 { In this way White gets two pawns for the knight. } 16...axb6 17.Rxb6 Kc7 18.Rb2 { Keeping b1 open for the other rook. } 18...f5 { If White now takes on f5, Black gets some active play after 19.exf5 Rg8 . } 19.Bc4 Bxe4 20.Nxe4 fxe4 21.Bd5 { The engine only gives around +1 for White here, but I think in a game between amateurs White will pretty much always win this position: he is an exchange up and has a dangerous passed a-pawn and his rooks can become active along the b-file. } ) ( 6...Bxd6 { is a very risky approach by Black. } 7.e4 Qxb2 8.Nge2 { Now on Be7 White has the familiar Nd5-Nc7+ winning. } 8...Bc7 { At least Black has now in certain lines Ba5+ to save him. } 9.Rb1 Qa3 10.Rb3 Qa5 11.Rb5 Qa3 { The queen has few squares left. } 12.Nd5 Ba5+ 13.c3 { The pawn on f6 cannot be defended. } 13...Nc6 14.Rb3 Qxa2 15.Ng3 { White is in no hurry to take on f6. } 15...h5 16.Nf5 Kf8 17.Nd6 { With two powerful knights, you don't need an engine to understand that White has a large advantage. His threat is Bc4 followed by moving the rook and the black queen is in trouble, but in general with the bishop on c8 and the rook on a8 it is clear that Black cannot be ok here. } ) ( 6...Qxd6 { doesn't work for Black: } 7.Qxd6 Bxd6 8.Nb5 { Black loses material. After 8... Ke7 there is 9. Rd1 or queenside castling. } 8...Be7 9.Nc7+ Kd8 10.Nxa8 { Contrary to a similar line we've seen previously, here Black has no compensation for the lost exchange. } 10...b6 11.O-O-O Bb7 12.Nxb6 axb6 13.e3 { White is a full exchange up and will put Black's center under pressure by playing Ne2-Nc3. Ideally Black would play d7-d5, but this pawn is hard to defend on d5 and even on d4 it will be exchanged against the e3-pawn. White can then play Nb5 followed by c2-c3 and Black's center will be gone with open lines for White's rooks. } ) 
7. Nd5 { One of the key ideas in this line: sacrificing the pawn on d6 to occupy the d5-square so that Black will be stuck with a backward d-pawn and passive pieces. } Bxd6 
8. e3 Nc6 { Threatening Nb4 when White would suddenly be lost. } 
9. c3 Ne7 
10. Nxf6+ Kf8 
11. Rc1 { Stronger than defending with Ne2 after which the bishop is stuck on f1. } Bc7 
12. Bc4 Qb6 
13. Qf3 { Threatening Nxd7+ followed by Qxf7 mate. } d5 { Returning the extra pawn to exchange some pieces and create space for the bishop on c8. } 
14. Bxd5 Nxd5 
15. Nxd5 Qc6 
16. Ne2 { White needs to quickly complete his development because Black has managed to open the position a bit and the bishop on c8 can finally become active. } Rg8 
17. e4 { Now that the knight on d5 is defended, the queen can freely move. } Bg4 
18. Qe3 Bd8 { A new future for the dark-squared bishop. } 
19. O-O Bg5 
20. f4 { The only way to avoid losing material, but strategically also fine because White wants to open the f-file with Black's king on f8. } Bh6 
21. Rce1 Re8 
22. c4 {[%cal Ge2g3,Gh2h3,Ge3f2,Gf4e5]} { White has some advantage, but it might be the smallest advantage compared to the other lines in the 4.d6 overview. Black has activated both his bishops, although he probably needs to exchange the one on g4 for the e2-knight soon because otherwise he may be hit by Ng3, h3 and Nf5 at some point. White is happy to open the f-file, but he needs to be a bit careful with his pawn on e4 and first the pin with the bishop on h6 needs to be resolved, for example by playing Qf2. } *

[Event "The Trompowsky: Simplified"]
