[ECO "A45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21553229"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 c5 { A direct attack on White's center. } 
3. d5 { The first alternative I looked at was to take on f6, similar to the lines where Black plays d7-d6 on move two. However, here Black can push his pawn to d5 in one go after he has recaptured on f6 with his e-pawn if White plays with e3 and c3, and if White plays d4-d5 then Qb6 is annoying. } ( { A sample line to illustrate why I believe } 3.Bxf6 { is not critical: } 3...exf6 4.Nc3 d5 { As said, the pawn immediately goes to d5. } 5.e3 Be6 6.Nge2 Nc6 { Black just completes development. } 7.a3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Bd6 9.Be2 O-O 10.O-O { Black is fully developed and now starts a specific operation to increase the effectiveness of his pair of bishops. } 10...Nxd4 11.Qxd4 { Taking back with the pawn also doesn't equalize. } 11...Be5 12.Qa4 Qc7 { And Black is already a little bit better. That is not how we want to play the Trompowsky! } ) e5 { Black is going for a closed setup which is a bit passive here. } 
4. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%csl Gc4]} { Consistent with other lines in the repertoire I prefer to keep the pawn on c2 and immediately play Nc3, so that at a later stage the c4-square is available for the bishop or the f3-knight via d2. } h6 ( 4...d6 { A slight change in move order from Black but it doesn't impact White much. } 5.e4 Be7 6.Bb5+ { The alternative Be2 is also fine but now Black has to play a7-a6 at some point and that weakens his queenside (square b6). } 6...Nbd7 { Of course 6... Bd7 is also a move, but from a positional point of view White is happy to exchange his light-squared bishop for Black's bishop with his central pawns on light squares. } 7.a4 a6 8.Be2 { White has induced a weakening of Black's queenside, and now it is time to bring a knight to c4. } 8...O-O 9.Nf3 b6 10.O-O { White has a stable advantage with his extra space and the weak pawns on b6 and d6. White can bring his knight to c4, queen to d2 and either play f2-f4 or b2-b4. } ) 
5. Bxf6 { As usual in the Trompowsky, we take on f6. Going back to h4 is also a valid option, but it's more of an engine move because in many lines White takes on f6 a few moves later anyway and for humans it is really hard to first play Bh4 and then Bxf6. } Qxf6 
6. a4 { Immediately taking control over the queenside. } d6 
7. Nf3 a6 
8. Nd2 { Preventing any Bg4 ideas after e2-e4. You don't want to allow Black to exchange one of his light pieces because that would help alleviate his lack of space. } b6 
9. h4 { This move may look strange, but these type of moves have become a lot more normal with the strong engines nowadays. White is grabbing space on the kingside, making it unattractive for Black to put his bishop on g7 and White could launch a kingside attack later. } Qd8 
10. e3 { Yes this pawn can go to e4 as well, but it makes the bishop on f1 slightly more passive while now White can still use d3 for his bishop to attack the black king. } Nd7 
11. g4 { Here we go! Modern chess supported by the engines, White launches a kingside attack. } Nf6 
12. Rg1 Be7 { Castling queenside is not really an option for Black either, as White can easily open the position there with b2-b4. } 
13. g5 Nh7 
14. g6 { I think Black players would feel quite uncomfortable here. My engine says already +1.1! } fxg6 
15. Bd3 O-O 
16. Rxg6 {[%cal Gd1e2,Ge2h5,Ge1c1,Gd1g1][%csl Rg8]} { White has the advantage with good attacking chances against Black's king, especially after castling queenside and playing Qe2, Rdg1, O-O-O and Qh5. } *

