3. d5 { The first alternative I looked at was to take on f6, similar to the lines where Black plays d7-d6 on move two. However, here Black can push his pawn to d5 in one go after he has recaptured on f6 with his e-pawn if White plays with e3 and c3, and if White plays d4-d5 then Qb6 is annoying. } ( { A sample line to illustrate why I believe } 3.Bxf6 { is not critical: } 3...exf6 4.Nc3 d5 { As said, the pawn immediately goes to d5. } 5.e3 Be6 6.Nge2 Nc6 { Black just completes development. } 7.a3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Bd6 9.Be2 O-O 10.O-O { Black is fully developed and now starts a specific operation to increase the effectiveness of his pair of bishops. } 10...Nxd4 11.Qxd4 { Taking back with the pawn also doesn't equalize. } 11...Be5 12.Qa4 Qc7 { And Black is already a little bit better. That is not how we want to play the Trompowsky! } ) b5 ( 3...e6 4.e4 { is a transposition to the line 1.d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6 3.e4 c5 4. d5 - see the variation [/variation/21518443/#/4/w]. } ) 
4. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} { I prefer to play this position in a kind of Benoni style and not to give up the bishop. } ( 4.Bxf6 { is an alternative for White, but I think with accurate play Black gets the type of position he is hoping for in these type of lines. } 4...exf6 5.e4 a6 6.a4 bxa4 { The move b5-b4 is also an option, but it keeps the position more closed and it will be easier for White to create some pressure with a knight on c4. } 7.Nf3 d6 8.c3 Nd7 9.Qxa4 Be7 10.Bd3 { Both sides complete their development. } 10...O-O 11.O-O Bb7 12.Nbd2 f5 { A typical breakthrough that is best played once Black has finished development. He will now get a lot of counterplay and overall we have a balanced position with mutual chances. } ) Ne4 ( 4...Qb6 { Defending the knight on f6 from the side. } 5.a4 b4 6.e3 g6 { If Black plays a7-a5, White gets a nice outpost for his bishop on b5. } 7.a5 Qd8 8.Bxf6 { A typical Trompowsky exchange. } 8...exf6 9.d6 { Limiting Black's coordination. } 9...Bb7 10.Bc4 a6 11.O-O { We have a sharp position where White is a little better. Next he will play c2-c3 and move one of the knights via d2 to b3 to put pressure on Black's pawns on b4 and c5. } ) 
5. Bf4 Bb7 
6. a4 { Creating weaknesses on the queenside. } b4 { Now White has a nice square on c4 for one of his knights. } 
7. Qd3 Nf6 
8. e4 { If White gets the chance to protect d5 with c2-c4, then e4-e5 is next with a completely winning position. } e6 
9. c4 d6 { Black is just in time to stop White, but the bishop on b7 is passsive now that d5 is protected. } 
10. h3 Be7 
11. Be2 O-O 
12. O-O {[%cal Gf4h2,Gf2f4,Gb1d2,Re6e5,Ga1d1][%csl Rd6]} { White is a little better based on the extra space and the weak pawn on d6. Next White could play Nbd2, Rad1 and if Black ever goes e6-e5, White can play Bh2 and prepare f2-f4. } *

