1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 c5 { A direct attack on White's center. } 
3. d5 { The first alternative I looked at was to take on f6, similar to the lines where Black plays d7-d6 on move two. However, here Black can push his pawn to d5 in one go after he has recaptured on f6 with his e-pawn if White plays with e3 and c3, and if White plays d4-d5 then Qb6 is annoying. } ( { A sample line to illustrate why I believe } 3.Bxf6 { is not critical: } 3...exf6 4.Nc3 d5 { As said, the pawn immediately goes to d5. } 5.e3 Be6 6.Nge2 Nc6 { Black just completes development. } 7.a3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Bd6 9.Be2 O-O 10.O-O { Black is fully developed and now starts a specific operation to increase the effectiveness of his pair of bishops. } 10...Nxd4 11.Qxd4 { Taking back with the pawn also doesn't equalize. } 11...Be5 12.Qa4 Qc7 { And Black is already a little bit better. That is not how we want to play the Trompowsky! } ) b5 ( 3...e6 4.e4 { is a transposition to the line 1.d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6 3.e4 c5 4. d5 - see the variation [/variation/21518443/#/4/w]. } ) 
4. Nf3 { I prefer to play this position in a kind of Benoni style and not to give up the bishop. } ( 4.Bxf6 { is an alternative for White, but I think with accurate play Black gets the type of position he is hoping for in these type of lines. } 4...exf6 5.e4 a6 6.a4 bxa4 { The move b5-b4 is also an option, but it keeps the position more closed and it will be easier for White to create some pressure with a knight on c4. } 7.Nf3 d6 8.c3 Nd7 9.Qxa4 Be7 10.Bd3 { Both sides complete their development. } 10...O-O 11.O-O Bb7 12.Nbd2 f5 { A typical breakthrough that is best played once Black has finished development. He will now get a lot of counterplay and overall we have a balanced position with mutual chances. } ) d6 
5. a4 {[%mdl 32768]} { Weakening Black's queenside. } b4 { Now there is a nice square on c4 for a white knight or bishop. } ( 5...bxa4 { Opening the position, but White has not taken on f6 so he has not given up his pair of bishops. } 6.Rxa4 Nbd7 7.Nc3 { First moving the knight out before playing e4 because the rook that defends e4 can easily be attacked with Nb6. } 7...g6 8.e4 Bg7 9.h3 { Preventing Black from playing Bg4 after Nb6. Usually in these types of positions Black is happy to exchange his light-squared bishop because it struggles to become active while the f3-knight covers a lot of essential squares. } 9...O-O 10.Ra3 { This move is not forced but at some point the rook needs to move. } 10...h6 11.Bf4 Re8 12.Be2 { Time to complete development. The nice thing about the e2-square is that if Black plays e6, White can take on e6 and the pawn on d6 is under attack from queen and bishop. Even if White doesn't take immediately on d6, it will continue to be a problem for Black. } 12...Rb8 13.O-O { I prefer this over 13.b3 after which Black plays 13...Rb4 , attacking the pawn on e4 and after 14.Nd2 Black hits with 14...Nh5 , attacking the bishop on f4 and the knight on c3 with the bishop on g7 and it all becomes messy. } 13...Rxb2 14.Qc1 Rb4 15.Bxh6 { It is important to take this pawn and not the one on a7 or defend the pawn on e4, because White's strategy is to set up a kingside attack. } 15...Nxe4 { The start of a series of exchanges. } 16.Bxg7 Kxg7 17.Nxe4 Rxe4 18.Bd3 Rb4 19.Ng5 { Threatening Bxg6 when fxg6 is not possible because of Ne6+ and Kxg6 loses to Rg3 followed by a knight check. } 19...Nf6 20.c4 { White could have taken on a7, but he has a much stronger plan. } 20...Qb6 { A very human move but not good. Black should probably play 20...a5 but even then White will get a nice attack by playing f2-f4-f5, while Black's a-pawn is not going anywhere. } 21.Ne6+ fxe6 22.Qg5 { White has a dangerous attack. It is not directly winning, but my engine gives +2 after Black's best defense } 22...Rh8 23.Bxg6 Kf8 24.Rf3 { . It is clear that the black king will not find a safe place. } ) 
6. e4 { A sharp approach by White, but the alternatives are less strong. } Nbd7 { A standard move for Black if he wants to continue with g6 and Bg7 and play a kind of Benoni structure. } 
7. Nbd2 { Note that on Bd3 White always need to take c5-c4 into account, so Nbd2 is much simpler. } g6 
8. Bb5 Bg7 
9. e5 { The point of White's play. If you don't play this but let's say castle kingside, then Bb5 was also not needed and you could have gone instead Be2. } dxe5 ( 9...Nxd5 { loses material in a simple way: } 10.exd6 { White can also play 10.Ne4 and after 10...Bb7 there is 11.Nxd6+ and Black loses material. } 10...O-O 11.Bc6 { And it is game over, Black cannot save both pieces. } ) 
10. Nxe5 a6 { Black's most accurate defense. } ( 10...O-O { Now the black queen gets in trouble. } 11.Nc6 Qe8 12.O-O a6 13.Re1 { Suddenly it turns out that e7 cannot be defended and the queen has nowhere to go. } 13...axb5 14.Rxe7 { White wins the queen and although it is not completely over, Black doesn't have sufficient compensation. White can push his pawn to d6, play Ne7+ followed by h2-h4 and start a kingside attack. } ) 
11. Qe2 Qc7 
12. Bxf6 { The only reason to take here is that it is the start of a forced sequence that will give White the advantage. } Bxf6 
13. d6 { A temporary pawn sacrifice. } Qxd6 
14. Nxd7 Bxd7 
15. Ne4 { This is the follow-up to d5-d6, attacking the queen that needs to keep defending the bishop on f6 and has to let go of the bishop on d7. } Qe5 
16. Bxd7+ Kxd7 
17. Nxf6+ Qxf6 
18. O-O-O+ { This is what White has been aiming for: his own king is safe while Black has lost the right to castle and is in danger. White's more active pieces will win the day; check out the remaining moves to see how it might finish. } Ke8 { With the idea to escape with the king to g7. } 
19. Rhe1 Kf8 
20. Rd7 { It's always nice if you can land a rook on the seventh rank. } Kg7 
21. Qxe7 Qxf2 ( { Now } 21...Qxe7 { leads to a lost endgame for Black after } 22.Rexe7 Rhf8 23.Ra7 { and the a-pawn falls. } ) 
22. Qe5+ Qf6 
23. Qxf6+ Kxf6 
24. Rf1+ Kg5 
25. Rfxf7 {[%cal Gc1d2,Gd2d3,Gd3c4,Gd2e3,Ge3f3,Gg2g3,Gh2h4,Gf7h7][%csl Ra6,Rc5,Rg5,Rh7]} { Maybe an engine can hold this endgame for Black, but in a practical game White will nearly always win. His rooks are active, Black's king is in danger, and the pawns on h7, c5, and a6 are weak. White also has the plan to enter with his king on the queenside with Kd2-Kd3-Kc4 or walk over to the kingside, for example f3, to mate the black king. } *

[Event "The Trompowsky: Simplified"]
[White "4) Trompowsky: 1...Nf6 2.Bg5 Others"]
[Black "2...c5 3.d5 b5 #4"]
[Date "2023.01.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21553232"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 c5 { A direct attack on White's center. } 
3. d5 { The first alternative I looked at was to take on f6, similar to the lines where Black plays d7-d6 on move two. However, here Black can push his pawn to d5 in one go after he has recaptured on f6 with his e-pawn if White plays with e3 and c3, and if White plays d4-d5 then Qb6 is annoying. } ( { A sample line to illustrate why I believe } 3.Bxf6 { is not critical: } 3...exf6 4.Nc3 d5 { As said, the pawn immediately goes to d5. } 5.e3 Be6 6.Nge2 Nc6 { Black just completes development. } 7.a3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Bd6 9.Be2 O-O 10.O-O { Black is fully developed and now starts a specific operation to increase the effectiveness of his pair of bishops. } 10...Nxd4 11.Qxd4 { Taking back with the pawn also doesn't equalize. } 11...Be5 12.Qa4 Qc7 { And Black is already a little bit better. That is not how we want to play the Trompowsky! } ) b5 ( 3...e6 4.e4 { is a transposition to the line 1.d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6 3.e4 c5 4. d5 - see the variation [/variation/21518443/#/4/w]. } ) 
4. Nf3 { I prefer to play this position in a kind of Benoni style and not to give up the bishop. } ( 4.Bxf6 { is an alternative for White, but I think with accurate play Black gets the type of position he is hoping for in these type of lines. } 4...exf6 5.e4 a6 6.a4 bxa4 { The move b5-b4 is also an option, but it keeps the position more closed and it will be easier for White to create some pressure with a knight on c4. } 7.Nf3 d6 8.c3 Nd7 9.Qxa4 Be7 10.Bd3 { Both sides complete their development. } 10...O-O 11.O-O Bb7 12.Nbd2 f5 { A typical breakthrough that is best played once Black has finished development. He will now get a lot of counterplay and overall we have a balanced position with mutual chances. } ) d6 
5. a4 { Weakening Black's queenside. } b4 { Now there is a nice square on c4 for a white knight or bishop. } ( 5...bxa4 { Opening the position, but White has not taken on f6 so he has not given up his pair of bishops. } 6.Rxa4 Nbd7 7.Nc3 { First moving the knight out before playing e4 because the rook that defends e4 can easily be attacked with Nb6. } 7...g6 8.e4 Bg7 9.h3 { Preventing Black from playing Bg4 after Nb6. Usually in these types of positions Black is happy to exchange his light-squared bishop because it struggles to become active while the f3-knight covers a lot of essential squares. } 9...O-O 10.Ra3 { This move is not forced but at some point the rook needs to move. } 10...h6 11.Bf4 Re8 12.Be2 { Time to complete development. The nice thing about the e2-square is that if Black plays e6, White can take on e6 and the pawn on d6 is under attack from queen and bishop. Even if White doesn't take immediately on d6, it will continue to be a problem for Black. } 12...Rb8 13.O-O { I prefer this over 13.b3 after which Black plays 13...Rb4 , attacking the pawn on e4 and after 14.Nd2 Black hits with 14...Nh5 , attacking the bishop on f4 and the knight on c3 with the bishop on g7 and it all becomes messy. } 13...Rxb2 14.Qc1 Rb4 15.Bxh6 { It is important to take this pawn and not the one on a7 or defend the pawn on e4, because White's strategy is to set up a kingside attack. } 15...Nxe4 { The start of a series of exchanges. } 16.Bxg7 Kxg7 17.Nxe4 Rxe4 18.Bd3 Rb4 19.Ng5 { Threatening Bxg6 when fxg6 is not possible because of Ne6+ and Kxg6 loses to Rg3 followed by a knight check. } 19...Nf6 20.c4 { White could have taken on a7, but he has a much stronger plan. } 20...Qb6 { A very human move but not good. Black should probably play 20...a5 but even then White will get a nice attack by playing f2-f4-f5, while Black's a-pawn is not going anywhere. } 21.Ne6+ fxe6 22.Qg5 { White has a dangerous attack. It is not directly winning, but my engine gives +2 after Black's best defense } 22...Rh8 23.Bxg6 Kf8 24.Rf3 { . It is clear that the black king will not find a safe place. } ) 
6. e4 { A sharp approach by White, but the alternatives are less strong. } Nxe4 
7. Bb5+ {[%mdl 32768]} Bd7 
8. Qe2 { White is giving up the bishop on g5 in exchange for an initiative based on his lead in development. } Nxg5 
9. Nxg5 { Now Qf3 is a key idea for White, so Black chases away the knight. } h6 
10. Ne4 { Threatening mate in one with Nxd6. } Qc7 
11. Nbd2 { White can also first castle kingside, but I prefer to immediately put pressure on d6. } g6 
12. Nc4 { Renewing the threat to take on d6 with the knight from e4. } Kd8 
13. O-O f5 
14. Ned2 { White is not in hurry. The black king on d8 will not find a safe place for a long time and the pawn on e7 is weak. } Bg7 
15. Rfe1 Bf6 ( { Black can also defend with } 15...Re8 { after which White plays } 16.Qf3 { with the idea Re6. } ) 
16. c3 { Opening lines on the queenside and making use of the fact that the bishop on f6 needs to keep on defending the pawn on e7. } bxc3 
17. bxc3 a6 
18. Bxd7 Nxd7 
19. Rab1 {[%cal Ge2d3,Ge1e6,Gd3h3,Gd3g3][%csl Ra6,Rd8,Re7,Rg6,Rh6]} { White has a large advantage despite the fact that he is a pawn down. White's pieces are much better coordinated, Black's rooks are uncoordinated, his king is vulnerable and he has several weak pawns (e7, a6, g6 and h6). White is happy to exchange a pair of rooks. If Black does nothing White can increase the pressure with Qd3-Qg3 or Re6 and Black will struggle to keep h6, g6 and f5 all defended at the same time. } *

