1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 c5 { A direct attack on White's center. } 
3. d5 { The first alternative I looked at was to take on f6, similar to the lines where Black plays d7-d6 on move two. However, here Black can push his pawn to d5 in one go after he has recaptured on f6 with his e-pawn if White plays with e3 and c3, and if White plays d4-d5 then Qb6 is annoying. } ( { A sample line to illustrate why I believe } 3.Bxf6 { is not critical: } 3...exf6 4.Nc3 d5 { As said, the pawn immediately goes to d5. } 5.e3 Be6 6.Nge2 Nc6 { Black just completes development. } 7.a3 cxd4 8.Nxd4 Bd6 9.Be2 O-O 10.O-O { Black is fully developed and now starts a specific operation to increase the effectiveness of his pair of bishops. } 10...Nxd4 11.Qxd4 { Taking back with the pawn also doesn't equalize. } 11...Be5 12.Qa4 Qc7 { And Black is already a little bit better. That is not how we want to play the Trompowsky! } ) Qb6 
4. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} { In a lot of the Trompowsky lines White defends this pawn on b2 with Qc1 (here this is not possible because d5 hangs) or even b2-b3, but that would weaken the black squares too much. Luckily White has a strong alternative in 4. Nc3. } Qxb2 ( 4...d6 { I find this a strange move. Why play Qb6 and then don't take on b2? If you want to play a kind of Benoni setup, it is much better to do so with the queen still on d8. But we need to be prepared, we may face it over the board, perhaps our opponent got cold feet after playing Qb6 and then you want to have an idea of how to continue with White. } 5.e4 Nbd7 6.Bd2 { Making it unattractive to take on b2 now that the knight on c3 is defended. The bishop wasn't so effective on g5 anymore after Nbd7. } 6...g6 7.Nf3 Bg7 8.Be2 O-O { Both sides focus on development, but now that Black has castled, Qxb2 becomes an option again. } 9.a4 { Now 9...Qxb2 loses the queen to 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 } 9...a6 10.Qc1 Re8 11.O-O { White is ready to start becoming active with Bh6, Nd2-Nc4 and f2-f4 followed by e4-e5 if Black stays passive. } 11...e6 { A standard operation, looking for counterplay. } 12.dxe6 fxe6 13.Re1 d5 { Black is looking for activity but his center can also become weak. } 14.a5 Qc6 15.Bd3 c4 { Winning some time but Black's center is now becoming static, it won't move any further and there is a big gap on d4 and a weak pawn on d5. } 16.exd5 exd5 17.Rxe8+ Nxe8 18.Bf1 Nc7 19.Bh6 { White has a clear advantage. Black's pieces do not coordinate well, the pawn on d5 is weak and soon a white knight will be on d4. White can also play g3 at some point followed by Bg2 to attack d5 further. } ) 
5. Bd2 { Black's queen is in danger and White is ahead in development. } Qb6 
6. e4 d6 
7. f4 { Preparing e4-e5. } e6 { It seems that this is playable for Black, although it is a very slippery road. } 
8. Nf3 exd5 
9. e5 { This is the big challenge, White is going for it. } dxe5 
10. fxe5 Ne4 ( { Now on } 10...Qe6 { White plays } 11.Bb5+ { followed by 12. Bf4 and the pawn on d5 is likely to fall. } ) 
11. Nxd5 Qd8 ( { Now } 11...Qc6 { would lose to } 12.Bb5 { and if Black takes the bishop there is Nc7+. } ) 
12. Bc4 ( { I believe this move to be stronger than } 12.c4 { as played in McShane - Ni, Bled 2002. } ) Be6 
13. O-O Nc6 ( 13...Bxd5 14.Ba5 { Now on Qxa5 White wins with Qxd5, hitting f7, e4 and b7. } 14...Nc3 15.Bxd8 Nxd1 16.Bxd5 Nc6 17.Raxd1 Nxd8 18.Ng5 { And White wins the pawn on f7 with a large advantage as a result. } ) 
14. Be1 {[%cal Ge1h4,Gd1d3,Ga1d1]} { Suddenly the bishop is not going to a5 but to h4! White has superior control of the important d5-square which they will bolster with Qd3 and Rd1. Play through the remaining moves to see how play could develop. } Qd7 { Black plans to increase the pressure on the white knight on d5. } 
15. Qd3 O-O-O 
16. Rd1 ( { Defending the knight for now, but it is not the end of the complications. Instead } 16.Qxe4 { gives Black the advantage after } 16...Bxd5 { . } ) Nd4 { Now the white knight on d5 hangs, Black's knight on e4 can be taken and White decides to attack another piece. } 
17. Bh4 ( { I guess } 17.Ba5 { comes down to the same thing. } ) ( 17.Qxe4 { would have resulted in an equal position. } ) Bxd5 
18. Bxd5 Qxd5 
19. c4 { Much stronger than taking on d8, the queen needs to leave its ideal square d5. } Nxf3+ 
20. Qxf3 Nd2 { The only move. } 
21. cxd5 Nxf3+ 
22. Rxf3 Rd7 { Black has to defend the f7-pawn. } 
23. Bg3 h5 
24. h4 {[%cal Gg1f2,Gf2e3,Gd1f1,Ge5e6,Gd5d6,Ge3e4,Ge4d5]} { And despite being a pawn down, White does have some winning chances. He can hope that one day his e-pawn will start moving forwards, the pawn on f7 could fall and it is easier for White to activate his king in the center. } *

