4. Nc3 { In a lot of the Trompowsky lines White defends this pawn on b2 with Qc1 (here this is not possible because d5 hangs) or even b2-b3, but that would weaken the black squares too much. Luckily White has a strong alternative in 4. Nc3. } Qxb2 ( 4...d6 { I find this a strange move. Why play Qb6 and then don't take on b2? If you want to play a kind of Benoni setup, it is much better to do so with the queen still on d8. But we need to be prepared, we may face it over the board, perhaps our opponent got cold feet after playing Qb6 and then you want to have an idea of how to continue with White. } 5.e4 Nbd7 6.Bd2 { Making it unattractive to take on b2 now that the knight on c3 is defended. The bishop wasn't so effective on g5 anymore after Nbd7. } 6...g6 7.Nf3 Bg7 8.Be2 O-O { Both sides focus on development, but now that Black has castled, Qxb2 becomes an option again. } 9.a4 { Now 9...Qxb2 loses the queen to 10.Rb1 Qa3 11.Rb3 } 9...a6 10.Qc1 Re8 11.O-O { White is ready to start becoming active with Bh6, Nd2-Nc4 and f2-f4 followed by e4-e5 if Black stays passive. } 11...e6 { A standard operation, looking for counterplay. } 12.dxe6 fxe6 13.Re1 d5 { Black is looking for activity but his center can also become weak. } 14.a5 Qc6 15.Bd3 c4 { Winning some time but Black's center is now becoming static, it won't move any further and there is a big gap on d4 and a weak pawn on d5. } 16.exd5 exd5 17.Rxe8+ Nxe8 18.Bf1 Nc7 19.Bh6 { White has a clear advantage. Black's pieces do not coordinate well, the pawn on d5 is weak and soon a white knight will be on d4. White can also play g3 at some point followed by Bg2 to attack d5 further. } ) 
5. Bd2 { Black's queen is in danger and White is ahead in development. } Qb6 
6. e4 d6 
7. f4 { Preparing e4-e5. } Qc7 ( { Black is defending against e4-e5, which would have been White's idea after } 7...Nbd7 8.Nf3 Qc7 9.Qe2 { . } ) ( { Instead of 7...Qc7 the queen can also go back to d8, but White can still claim some advantage after } 7...Qd8 8.a4 { followed by 9. Bc4. } ) ( { On } 7...Bg4 { White is happy to trade pieces with } 8.Be2 Bxe2 9.Qxe2 { and soon e4-e5 will follow. } ) 
8. a4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { White has time to lock the queenside. On } 8.Nf3 { with the idea e4-e5 Black still has } 8...e5 { . } ) a6 
9. Bc4 { White trusts that by putting his pieces on active squares he will reach a good position. } g6 
10. Nf3 ( { Instead White can also play } 10.h3 { , a logical move to prevent Black, who is suffering from a lack of space, from exchanging on } { f3 . } ) Bg4 
11. O-O Nbd7 
12. h3 { White takes the pair of bishops. } Bxf3 
13. Qxf3 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5,Gh3h4,Gh4h5]} { This position is very dangerous for Black. White is ready for moves like g2-g4 followed by g4-g5 and then even h3-h4-h5. Black is in serious trouble because of his lack of counterplay and limited space for his pieces. } *

[Event "The Trompowsky: Simplified"]
[White "4) Trompowsky: 1...Nf6 2.Bg5 Others"]
[Black "2...d6 3.Bxf6 gxf6 #1"]
[Date "2023.01.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "A45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21553237"]

1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 d6 { This move is not so often played. Black is inviting White to damage his pawn structure and if White doesn't do it now, he may no longer get a chance after Nbd7. } 
3. Bxf6 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { White could also have gone for for a more traditional setup with Nc3 with likely transpositions to lines of other openings, not the Trompowsky. One example is } 3.Nc3 Nbd7 4.e4 e5 5.Nf3 Be7 { and we are in a Philidor type of position. } ) gxf6 { Black is taking more risk by taking on f6 this way. He hopes to benefit from the half-open g-file and the extra influence the f6-pawn gives in the center. } 
4. e3 { White has other moves as well but I like this move for its logic: White is opening the d1-h5 diagonal which we will see becomes important later. } ( { The main alternative, } 4.e4 { , I don't like so much because of } 4...f5 { . } ) f5 ( 4...e5 { is an alternative given by Kryavkin. It doesn't change much about how White should play the position, which is to restrict Black's bishops: } 5.Qh5 { Now Bf5 is no longer an option and White can dream about putting a knight on f5. } 5...c6 6.Nd2 { White has other moves as well, but I like the idea of keeping the option open to play c2–c3 while already preparing queenside castling. } 6...Be6 7.g3 exd4 8.exd4 f5 { Opening the diagonal for the f8-bishop once it gets to g7, but this makes the bishop on e6 very passive. } 9.Ne2 { So that Black cannot sacrifice a pawn with f5–f4 because of Nxf4. } 9...Nd7 10.Nf4 Qf6 11.c3 d5 12.O-O-O { White is a little better. Especially for humans it is difficult to play such a passive position with Black. White can play Bg2 or even sometimes Bh3, the move Rhe1 is obvious and White can also continue Nf3 and put the other knight on d3 to maintain central control. } ) 
5. Ne2 { If Black plays the standard Bg7 here, he gets hit with Ng3 followed by Nh5! This was the idea of playing e2-e3 followed by Ne2. } c5 
6. c3 { White is supporting the pawn on d4 so that the position maintains a close character in which his knights will be more powerful than Black's bishops. } h5 {[%cal Rh5h4]} 
7. h4 {[%cal Ge2f4,Gf1e2][%csl Rh5]} { Simple chess: there is no reason to allow Black the option of h5-h4, especially if our knight would be on g3. Moreover, the pawn on h5 can become weak. } Nd7 
8. g3 { It is important to realize that White should not go pawn hunting while not fully developed. So lines with Ng3 followed by Be2 and taking on h5 are not recommended because Black plays a combination of Qb6, taking on d4 and playing e7-e5, all aimed at targeting the black squares and White will struggle. Remember: the pawn on h5 is not going anywhere and can also be captured at move 20 or 30! } Qb6 
9. Qd2 { So that after Qc6 White can still play d4-d5, which would not be possible if White would have played 9.Qc2. } Nf6 
10. Bg2 Bd7 
11. O-O {[%cal Ge2f4,Gb1a3,Gb2b4,Ga1b1]} { My engine says this position is about equal, but I think in an over-the-board game Black players will struggle. First off, the engine says Black should play d6-d5 here which is not a very human move. Secondly, White can continue developing his knight from b1 to a3, play Rab1, sometimes followed by b2-b4 or first Nf4 and Black doesn't have a clear active plan. Whenever he pushes his pawns, for example e7-e5, he is creating new weaknesses and he risks that the bishops become passive. } *

