1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 d6 { This move is not so often played. Black is inviting White to damage his pawn structure and if White doesn't do it now, he may no longer get a chance after Nbd7. } 
3. Bxf6 ( { White could also have gone for for a more traditional setup with Nc3 with likely transpositions to lines of other openings, not the Trompowsky. One example is } 3.Nc3 Nbd7 4.e4 e5 5.Nf3 Be7 { and we are in a Philidor type of position. } ) gxf6 { Black is taking more risk by taking on f6 this way. He hopes to benefit from the half-open g-file and the extra influence the f6-pawn gives in the center. } 
4. e3 { White has other moves as well but I like this move for its logic: White is opening the d1-h5 diagonal which we will see becomes important later. } ( { The main alternative, } 4.e4 { , I don't like so much because of } 4...f5 { . } ) c5 
5. c3 {[%mdl 32768]} { Similar to other lines White stabilizes his center. } e6 ( 5...f5 6.Ne2 { This is a transposition to the line with 4...f5 and 5...c5 if Black continues with 6...h5 here ( see the variation [/variation/21553237/#/6/b]). } 6...Bg7 { We will now look at a different setup for Black, one where he refrains from playing h5. } 7.Ng3 Nc6 8.Nh5 { The logical consequence of Black not playing ...h5: White wants to exchange Black's strong bishop. } 8...O-O 9.Be2 cxd4 { Black is quickly opening the position before White can consolidate, castle and complete development. Note that at the moment Black has a small lead in development. } 10.cxd4 e5 { Again trying to open the position. } 11.Nxg7 Kxg7 12.Nc3 { A precise move. } { If White would have castled, he would need to sacrifice a pawn after 12.O-O exd4 13.exd4 Qf6 as the pawn on d4 is hard to defend. } 12...exd4 13.exd4 Qf6 14.d5 { Because there is a knight on c3 this advance is possible. Black doesn't have Qxb2 as in the line where White would have castled on move 12. } 14...Ne5 15.f4 { Again a precise move. Black's idea was to play f5-f4 to create a nice spot on f5 for his bishop. } 15...Nd7 16.O-O Nc5 17.Rc1 { White is slightly better, he has a little more space and his pawn structure is a bit better, but it is a big fight because Black can play Bd7, Rfe8 and Ne4. White has ideas like Nb5 targeting d6 and after a6 Nd4 followed by b2-b4 and Rc7. } ) 
6. Nf3 ( { An alternative is to play } 6.Ne2 { and then either continue with Ng3-Nh5 or with g2-g3 followed by Bg2. } ) Nc6 
7. Be2 Qb6 
8. Qc2 { Defending with Qc1 would be a bit passive and if Black now takes on d4 we take back with the c-pawn. There is no need to be afraid of Nb4. } Be7 
9. O-O O-O 
10. d5 { A powerful pawn sacrifice to open the position. } exd5 
11. Nbd2 Be6 
12. Nh4 { This is White's idea: a knight on f5 will be worth a pawn because Black's structure is so bad. } Kh8 
13. Bd3 Bd8 { Black's play is tricky: if White now takes on h7, he loses material after f6-f5 as both the knight on h4 and the bishop on h7 remain hanging. } 
14. Ndf3 { Now Bxh7 is a threat and Black cannot defend the pawn, so he gives up his weak f-pawn instead. } f5 
15. Nxf5 Ne5 
16. Be2 {[%cal Ga1d1,Gb2b3,Gc3c4,Gf5d6][%csl Rd5,Rd6,Gf5]} { And White has a nice advantage based on his better pawn structure and the powerful knight on f5. His next moves will be to put a rook on d1 and play b2-b3 followed by c3-c4 and if Black ever takes on c4 he may lose the pawn on d6. } *

