1. d4 Nf6 
2. Bg5 d6 { This move is not so often played. Black is inviting White to damage his pawn structure and if White doesn't do it now, he may no longer get a chance after Nbd7. } 
3. Bxf6 ( { White could also have gone for for a more traditional setup with Nc3 with likely transpositions to lines of other openings, not the Trompowsky. One example is } 3.Nc3 Nbd7 4.e4 e5 5.Nf3 Be7 { and we are in a Philidor type of position. } ) exf6 { This is a more solid approach by Black where White needs to be a bit careful. } 
4. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} g6 
5. c4 { In general in these type of positions White will eventually try to advance on the queenside and Black on the kingside. It is important that White picks the right setup because you don't want to be waiting for the black pawns on the kingside to start attacking your king. } c6 
6. Nc3 h5 {[%cal Rh5h4]} ( { If Black plays less aggressively with, for example, } 6...Bg7 { or } ) ( 6...Nd7 { , White can continue with the standard plan of g3, Bg2 and Ne2. If Black throws in a later h7-h5, White can still respond with h2-h4. } ) 
