1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 {[%mdl 32768]} { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist, and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } f6 { Black's most critical reply and I have dedicated a separate chapter to it to make sure you get complicated positions where it is easy to go wrong for your opponent. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 Trompowsky chapter [/variation/21553258/#/2/b]. } ) ( 2...Nc6 { is typical for Chigorin players, so I wanted to include one little line against it. } 3.e3 f6 4.Bh4 { The only time in the entire repertoire we go to h4 while Black can still put the knight on h6! } 4...Nh6 5.Nc3 Nf5 6.Bg3 h5 { Black is going to win a piece, but at what price? } 7.Be2 g6 8.Nf3 h4 9.Bf4 g5 10.Nxg5 fxg5 11.Bh5+ Kd7 12.Bxg5 { My engine says 0.00, but my eyes tell me that it will be very hard to defend this with Black as a human player. } ) 
3. Bd2 ( { It took many years before Black players realized that after the natural } 3.Bh4 { the move } 3...Nh6 { with the idea } 4.-- Nf5 { is a serious challenge for White's setup. } ) Nc6 
4. c4 {[%cal Re7e5]} { Before Black can occupy the center with e7-e5 (the main idea behind 3... Nc6) White attacks the d5-pawn. } e5 { This move is recommended by Chessforlife in his 'Beat 1.d4 systems' course. } 
5. cxd5 Nxd4 { This is not such a great move, as the knight will soon have to make some more jumps. } 
6. Nc3 {[%csl Rd4]} { Defending the pawn on d5 with e2-e4 is not a good idea because then Black's knight on d4 would be ideally positioned. } Bc5 ( 6...Ne7 7.e3 { With tempo White occupies the center. } 7...Ndf5 8.e4 Nd6 9.Qb3 c6 { There is no reason for White to take on c6. The pawn on d5 takes away some important squares from the black pieces. } 10.f4 Ng6 11.f5 { Grabbing more space, White continues to take away squares from Black's pieces and they struggle to develop. } 11...Ne7 12.dxc6 Nxc6 13.Nf3 { Black has lost control over the light squares b3-g8 and cannot castle kingside for the foreseeable future. } ) 
7. e3 Nf5 { This is a suboptimal square for the knight as it is not very active here. Maybe it can go to d6, but even there its effectiveness depends on how much pressure it can put on a white pawn on e4. } 
8. b4 {[%cal Rc5b4,Gd1a4]} { Gaining space by making use of the fact that Black cannot take the b4-pawn because of Qa4+. } Bd6 
9. Nf3 { Black's main problem is that the knights are in each other's way. } Nge7 
10. e4 Nd4 ( { Now } 10...Nh6 { looks really bad after } 11.Bxh6 { . } ) 
11. Nxd4 exd4 
12. Nb5 O-O { Now White needs to be careful with just taking the pawn on d4. Black is almost fully developed and can quickly generate counterplay. } 
13. Bc4 Kh8 ( { If Black plays } 13...f5 { , White wins material with } 14.e5 Bxe5 15.d6+! ) 
14. Nxd6 ( { Much stronger than taking } 14.Nxd4 { after which Black plays } 14...Be5 15.Be3 f5 { , opening the position with compensation for the pawn. Because the king has moved to h8, White has no longer tricks with e4-e5 (but he did manage to develop the bishop with tempo to c4). } ) Qxd6 { Taking back with the c-pawn on d6 doesn't help Black to generate counterplay. } 
15. O-O { White has great central control, and if Black goes pawn hunting with c6, followed by taking twice on d5, it will take time during which White will organize pressure on Black's weak d-pawn. White will be better in the resulting positions with the bishop pair. Play through the remaining moves to see how play could develop. } c6 
16. Re1 cxd5 { Black goes pawn hunting. } 
17. exd5 Nxd5 
18. Re4 { White will win back the pawn on d4. } b5 
19. Bb3 Be6 ( 19...Nxb4 { is too risky for Black: } 20.Qh5 { Suddenly Rh4 is a winning threat. } 20...g6 { Other moves also lose, but this leads to a pretty mate! } 21.Qxh7+ Kxh7 22.Rh4+ Kg7 23.Bh6+ Kh8 24.Bxf8# ) 
20. Qf3 {[%cal Ga1e1,Ge4d4,Ge4e6]} { Black has some problems to solve. White is threatening to play Rxe6 and if Black defends against it, White can continue with Rae1 or take on d4 with the rook. In all cases it is an open position with two strong bishops for White and pressure on the bishop on e6 and attacking chances via h7. } *

