6. dxe5 {[%mdl 32768]} { There was so much pressure on the d4-pawn that White doesn't have a good alternative to taking on e5. } Be6 { Black is offering a pawn on f6 and although White could accept it, Black will always have compensation because of his lead in development. So in general in this repertoire, we don't take such pawns. } 
7. Nc3 Qd7 
8. Nf3 { White is trying to catch up with Black's lead in development. } Nxe5 
9. Qc2 ( { White could also have taken } 9.Nxe5 fxe5 { and followed up with } 10.e4 { and even offer a queen exchange with } { 10.Be3 , but I like to keep things a bit sharper with Qc2 and queenside castling. } ) O-O-O 
10. O-O-O Qf7 ( { Moving the queen away from the d-file makes sense. Black could also have played } 10...Qc6 { after which White plays } 11.e4 { and continues with his development. } ) 
11. e4 Ne7 
12. Bb5 { The most logical square for the bishop. On e2 it would be a bit passive. } N7c6 
13. Be3 Bb4 
14. Nxe5 Nxe5 
15. Qa4 {[%cal Gc3d5,Ga2a3,Ra7a5]} -- ( { And Black is in some trouble. He probably needs to play } 15...a5 { , but how many humans would even consider such a move? The problem is that after } ) ( 15...Bxc3 { White first takes on a7 with his queen. So } ) ( 15...a5 { is really the only move. White can then temporarily sacrifice a pawn with } 16.Nd5 { because White always has this idea of a2-a3, chasing away the bishop and then taking on a5 with the queen. An engine can hold it for Black, but I think without engine help it is difficult. } )
