5. cxd5 Qxd5 
6. dxe5 { There was so much pressure on the d4-pawn that White doesn't have a good alternative to taking on e5. } Bc5 { Black is offering the pawn but we don't take on f6. In fact f2 feels a bit weak with that bishop on c5, so let's play it safely. } 
7. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} Be6 
8. Nc3 Qxe5 
9. Nf3 { Winning tempi on the black queen by developing both knights can never be bad. } Qf5 
10. Rc1 ( { White could also go for a queen swap after } 10.Nh4 Qg4 { ( } { 10...Qg5 is not great because of 11.Ne4 ), but the position is quite symmetrical, so it's not so easy to create winning chances. } ) Nge7 
11. Be2 O-O-O 
12. O-O Qg6 { Repositioning the queen and taking a slower approach with the attack. } ( { If instead Black plays } 12...g5 { , White will continue with } 13.Nb5 { followed by Qa4. Although the pawn on g5 looks threatening, it is not easy for Black to create a mating attack. Perhaps he needs to go h7-h5-h4. } ) 
13. a3 { A standard move in these type of positions to prepare b2-b4. } Kb8 
14. b4 Bb6 
15. Qc2 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gc3a4,Ga4c5,Ga3a4,Ga4a5,Gb4b5]} { You may think it is strange to offer a queen swap, but even without queens White's initiative on the queenside will continue. The reason for putting the queen on c2 is that there is simply no better square. White's next moves will likely be Na4-Nc5, Rfd1 and a3-a4. } *

