1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist, and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } f6 { Black's most critical reply and I have dedicated a separate chapter to it to make sure you get complicated positions where it is easy to go wrong for your opponent. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 Trompowsky chapter [/variation/21553258/#/2/b]. } ) ( 2...Nc6 { is typical for Chigorin players, so I wanted to include one little line against it. } 3.e3 f6 4.Bh4 { The only time in the entire repertoire we go to h4 while Black can still put the knight on h6! } 4...Nh6 5.Nc3 Nf5 6.Bg3 h5 { Black is going to win a piece, but at what price? } 7.Be2 g6 8.Nf3 h4 9.Bf4 g5 10.Nxg5 fxg5 11.Bh5+ Kd7 12.Bxg5 { My engine says 0.00, but my eyes tell me that it will be very hard to defend this with Black as a human player. } ) 
3. Bd2 ( { It took many years before Black players realized that after the natural } 3.Bh4 { the move } 3...Nh6 { with the idea } 4.-- Nf5 { is a serious challenge for White's setup. } ) Nc6 
4. c4 {[%cal Re7e5]} { Before Black can occupy the center with e7-e5 (the main idea behind 3... Nc6) White attacks the d5-pawn. } e5 { This move is recommended by Chessforlife in his 'Beat 1.d4 systems' course. } 
5. cxd5 Qxd5 
6. dxe5 { There was so much pressure on the d4-pawn that White doesn't have a good alternative to taking on e5. } fxe5 
7. Nc3 { This line is similar to the line where Black first plays Qf7, the main difference that here the knight is on c3 and not on d2. } Qf7 
8. Nf3 Nf6 
9. e4 {[%mdl 32768]} { As usual White doesn't want to allow e5-e4. } h6 { Black wants to avoid Ng5 type of moves so that developing with Be6 becomes an option. } ( 9...Bd7 { prepares queenside castling, but now White has time for Ng5. } 10.Ng5 { This results in a pawn sacrifice where White will have good compensation. } 10...Qe7 11.Bc4 h6 12.Bf7+ Kd8 13.Nd5 { The only move. Otherwise White loses material. } 13...Nxd5 { On a move like 13... Qd6 White can just go back with the knight to f3. } 14.exd5 Nd4 15.Ne6+ Kc8 16.Bh5 { A little stronger than 16. Bg6 because the bishop is more of a target on g6. } 16...Nxe6 17.dxe6 Qxe6 18.O-O Kb8 19.Bf3 { I think White has sufficient compensation for the pawn and the engine seems to agree. Black's rook on a8 is not participating and White can start slowly an attack with a2-a3, b2-b4, Rb1 and a3-a4-a5 and b4-b5 while for Black it is much harder to organize anything on the kingside. Besides, White can combine all this by targeting the pawn on e5, which is a weakness. } ) 
10. Qa4 Bd6 { Defending the pawn on e5 as White was threatening Nxe5. } 
11. Bc4 ( { I like } 11.Bb5 { less because Black could sacrifice a pawn by playing } 11...O-O { and with his pair of bishops he can quickly become active. } ) Be6 
12. Bxe6 Qxe6 
13. O-O O-O { A more strategic move than castling queenside. } ( 13...O-O-O { Black takes the game into more aggressive territory. } 14.Rfc1 Kb8 15.Ne2 { White could also have played 15.Nb5 with the idea to sacrifice an exchange on c6. There are many lines where White than makes a draw by giving perpetual check on b5 and c6/a6, but the intent of Ne2 is keep the game going. Sacrificing on c6 remains an option and also Be3, b2-b4 (sometimes sacrificing the pawn on e4 to gain time for the attack, so e. g. b4, Nxe4 Be3 with a lot of threats against Black's king) and Rc2 followed by Rac1 are typical moves for White. } ) 
14. Ne2 { The knight is better positioned on g3, defending the pawn on e4, threatening Nf5 and opening the c-file for action with b2-b4-b5. } a6 
15. Ng3 Rad8 
16. Rac1 {[%cal Ga4c4,Gb2b4,Gb4b5,Gc1c6,Gg3f5]} { The position is about equal but certainly not a draw yet! White can consider sacrificing an exchange on c6, although it feels still a bit early. White can also play b2-b4 followed by b4-b5 to disrupt Black's queenside and White has the standard move Nf5. And even offering a queen swap with Qc4 is quite reasonable. } *

