1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist, and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } f6 { Black's most critical reply and I have dedicated a separate chapter to it to make sure you get complicated positions where it is easy to go wrong for your opponent. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 Trompowsky chapter [/variation/21553258/#/2/b]. } ) ( 2...Nc6 { is typical for Chigorin players, so I wanted to include one little line against it. } 3.e3 f6 4.Bh4 { The only time in the entire repertoire we go to h4 while Black can still put the knight on h6! } 4...Nh6 5.Nc3 Nf5 6.Bg3 h5 { Black is going to win a piece, but at what price? } 7.Be2 g6 8.Nf3 h4 9.Bf4 g5 10.Nxg5 fxg5 11.Bh5+ Kd7 12.Bxg5 { My engine says 0.00, but my eyes tell me that it will be very hard to defend this with Black as a human player. } ) 
3. Bd2 ( { It took many years before Black players realized that after the natural } 3.Bh4 { the move } 3...Nh6 { with the idea } 4.-- Nf5 { is a serious challenge for White's setup. } ) Nc6 
4. c4 {[%cal Re7e5]} { Before Black can occupy the center with e7-e5 (the main idea behind 3... Nc6) White attacks the d5-pawn. } Nxd4 { By far Black's best move in the position. } ( 4...dxc4 { is not a great move. Black loses control over some important squares. } 5.e3 { Defending the pawn on d4 and preparing to take on c4 after which the light squares from b3 to f7 on Black's side feel exposed. } 5...e5 { Black wants to play as actively as possible. } { If he defends the pawn on c4 with 5...Be6 , White starts with 6.Nf3 followed by Qa4 or Qc2. } 6.Bxc4 { If I were Black I would be worried about my light squares. } 6...Bd6 7.Nc3 exd4 8.exd4 Bf5 { Black can take 8...Nxd4 as there is no direct refutation. However, after 9.Nge2 White has a large lead in development and Black's king struggles to find a safe place because of the weak light squares. } 9.Nf3 { This is White's standard setup in this line: an isolated pawn on d4, knight to f3 and kingside castling. } 9...Qd7 10.O-O O-O-O 11.d5 { This pawn has to move forward at some point, so why not immediately? } 11...Ne5 12.Nxe5 Bxe5 13.Rc1 { It's always nice to put the rook on the half-open file facing the king. } 13...Kb8 14.Qb3 { The first attacking ideas are becoming visible: Ba6 and alternatively Be3 followed by Qa3. } 14...Ne7 15.Be3 Bxc3 { on 15...Nc8 White plays 16.Rfd1 and then continues to develop his attack. } 16.Qxc3 { Now on 16...Qd6 White defends his pawn again with 17.Rfd1 followed by threatening mate, and once a black pawn moves forward (a6 or b6) White will push his a- and/or b-pawn forward. } 16...Nxd5 17.Bxd5 Qxd5 18.Qxc7+ Ka8 { It is amazing that there is no direct win for White. Normally with opposite colored bishops the one who starts attacking wins because the defending side cannot offer a bishop exchange. } 19.Rc5 Qd7 20.Qf4 { White is clearly better. The threat is Ra5 or Rc7, but also simply h2-h3 followed by Rfc1 is strong. In a practical game it will be hard for Black to survive. } ) ( 4...e6 { is a bit passive. } 5.Nf3 { We have to develop our pieces! } 5...Nge7 6.e3 g5 { Black is grabbing some space on the kingside before continuing with development. } { On the immdiate 6...Ng6 White has 7.h4! With a clear initiative. } 7.Nc3 Ng6 { On 7...g4 White would have answered 8.Nh4 , but now that is no longer possible so White prevents the advance of the g-pawn. } 8.h3 Bg7 9.Qc2 O-O 10.a3 { A useful move, taking out Nb4 ideas and next Bd3 is a logical move to make. } 10...Rf7 11.O-O-O { Instead I think 11. Bd3 followed by kingside castling also gives White some advantage, but it feels to me that Black's advanced g-pawn could be a nice target for White's attack, so I prefer the more aggressive queenside castling. } 11...f5 { Going for a kind of Stonewall setup. } 12.Bd3 Rb8 13.cxd5 { Black had the idea to take on c4 followed by b7-b5-b4, so it makes sense to take on d5 in order not to lose a tempo with the bishop. Also, now the pawn on f5 becomes weak. } 13...exd5 14.h4 Nxh4 { 14...g4 tries to keep the kingside closed, but it fails tactically: 15.Ng5 Rf8 16.Nxd5 And White is winning because 16...Qxd5 is met by 17.Bc4 . } 15.Nxh4 gxh4 16.Ne2 { Immediately g2-g3 is a valid option, but I believe this move to be even stronger. } 16...Bf6 17.g3 { This was White's idea with Ne2. } { After 17...hxg3 there is 18.Nxg3 and Black's position collapses. } 17...Kh8 18.gxh4 Bg7 19.Nf4 { White has a large advantage based on the open g-file. He is ready to play Rdg1 followed by Rg5 and then either Rhg1 and Nh5 targeting the bishop on g7 or first taking on f5. Black doesn't have any counterplay, as b7-b5-b4 is way too slow here. } ) 
5. Bc3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { It is also possible to play } 5.e3 Nc6 6.Qh5+ { , but after } 6...g6 7.Qxd5 Bd7! { I don't trust White's position. } ) e5 ( 5...Ne6 { is a strange square for the black knight. } 6.cxd5 Nc5 7.Nf3 e6 8.e4 { Making use of the fact that 8...Nxe4 fails to 9.Qa4+ . } { 9...Qd7 9.Nbd2 Sacrificing the d5-pawn. 9...exd5 10.exd5 Ne7 } { 10...Qxd5 Black should really not accept the poisoned pawn: 11.Bc4 Qh5 12.b4 Nd7 13.O-O White has a winning advantage with his lead in development and the weaknesses on the light squares. Next he will play Re1+, Qb3 and Ne4 with a strong attack against Black's king that cannot leave the center. } { 11.Bc4 Black's pieces look clumsy. 11...b5 12.Be2 Nxd5 Black is a pawn up but White has sufficient compensation with the more active pieces, lead in development and weak b5-pawn. 13.O-O c6 Defending the b5-pawn, but now it will take awhile to activate the c8-bishop. 14.Re1 Be7 15.Rc1 Maybe an engine can hold Black's position, but for humans it will be hard. White will play Nd4 and either start attacking the weak c6-pawn or chase the knight on c5 away and land the d4-knight on e6. So White's next moves include Nd4, Bf3, b2-b4 or Nd2-b3. } ) 
6. e3 Nf5 { Black's most logical reply. } 
7. cxd5 Nge7 
8. Qa4+ { Again Black had ideas of playing c7-c6 and exchanging queens on d1. } Bd7 
9. Qb3 Nd6 
10. Nf3 ( { And not } 10.Nd2 { as in the line with 6...Nc6, because here Black has the idea to play } 10...c6 { and after } 11.dxc6 Bxc6 { Black wants to play Nd5 and take on c3. White should then be able to take back with his knight from b1, put a rook on d1 and play Nd5, so his knight needs to stay on b1 for now and not move to d2. } ) c6 
11. dxc6 Bxc6 
12. Be2 { Preparing kingside castling. } Nd5 {[%cal Gb1c3,Ga1d1,Gc3d5]} 
13. O-O { Just to repeat: if Black takes on c3, White will take back with his knight, put a rook on d1 and play Nd5. } Qb6 
14. Qc2 { There is no reason for White to exchange queens. In the long term there could be some weaknesses along the c2-h7 diagonal (imagine a bishop coming to d3). } Be7 {[%cal Re2d3,Re5e4]} 
15. Rd1 ( { The move } 15.Bd3 { would be a blunder because of } 15...e4 { winning material. } ) O-O 
16. Be1 { Maintaining his pair of bishops and making space for the knight to come out. } Rac8 
17. Nc3 {[%cal Ga1c1,Gf3h4,Gh4f5,Gc3a4]} { The position is about equal but is also quite complex. Black's structure around his king is a bit weak but he has the more active pieces in the center. White may follow up with moves like Rac1, Nh4-Nf5 or even sometimes Na4. } *

[Event "The Trompowsky: Simplified"]
[White "5) Pseudo-Trompowsky: 1...d5 2.Bg5 f6"]
[Black "3...c5 #1"]
[Date "2023.01.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D00"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21651854"]

1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist, and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } f6 { Black's most critical reply and I have dedicated a separate chapter to it to make sure you get complicated positions where it is easy to go wrong for your opponent. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 Trompowsky chapter [/variation/21553258/#/2/b]. } ) ( 2...Nc6 { is typical for Chigorin players, so I wanted to include one little line against it. } 3.e3 f6 4.Bh4 { The only time in the entire repertoire we go to h4 while Black can still put the knight on h6! } 4...Nh6 5.Nc3 Nf5 6.Bg3 h5 { Black is going to win a piece, but at what price? } 7.Be2 g6 8.Nf3 h4 9.Bf4 g5 10.Nxg5 fxg5 11.Bh5+ Kd7 12.Bxg5 { My engine says 0.00, but my eyes tell me that it will be very hard to defend this with Black as a human player. } ) 
3. Bd2 ( { It took many years before Black players realized that after the natural } 3.Bh4 { the move } 3...Nh6 { with the idea } 4.-- Nf5 { is a serious challenge for White's setup. } ) c5 { The start of sharp play. } 
4. dxc5 {[%mdl 32768]} { White can also play the more quiet 4.e3, but the disadvantage is that Black gets the choice to define the type of play then. } e5 
5. e4 { An aggressive move, opening the road to h5 for the white queen. } dxe4 { This move doesn't really work for Black. } 
6. Nc3 f5 { This is Black's idea, but it doesn't work. } 
7. Nxe4! fxe4 
8. Qh5+ { And now we are having some fun with White! } Ke7 
9. Qxe5+ Be6 
10. Bc4 { The pin on the bishop on e6 turns out to be the decisive factor. The engine gives White a winning advantage, but it is useful to know how to conduct the attack. } Qc8 ( 10...Qd7 11.O-O-O { Not just bringing the king in safety but also the rook on } { d1 will be important in attacking the queen and cutting off the king. 11...Kf7 Hoping to survive by getting out of the pin. 12.Nh3 h6 } { 12...Bxc4 Black will need to give up a lot of material to avoid mate: 13.Ng5+ Kg6 14.Qxe4+ Qf5 15.Qxc4 Black can hardly move. 15...Be7 16.g4 A big problem for Black, who, according to the engine, should now take on g5 with his queen and it is only +17 for White. 16...Qf8 Now it is mate in two. 17.Qe4+ Kh6 18.Nf7# } { 13.Bc3 Instead Nf4 is also winning and there are probably some other winning alternatives as well. 13...Qc6 } { 13...Qc8 14.Nf4 Because Black played h7-h6, he no longer has g7-g6 when White plays Qh5+. Even with such a big attack such subtleties can beautiful. 14...Bxc4 15.Qh5+ g6 16.Qxg6+ Ke7 17.Rhe1 And mate will follow soon after Rxe4+. } { 14.Rd6 A nice trick. Black is completely lost. 14...Bxc4 Hoping that White will take on c6, which is by the way also winning for White, but he has even stronger. 15.Qh5+ Ke7 16.Nf4 There are moments when Black can take on d6 with his queen but after cxd6 White is material up and the attack will continue with Rd1 coming soon. 16...Nd7 17.Ng6+ Kd8 18.Ba5+ Now Black can play 18... b6, avoiding mate, but after taking the queen there is no doubt White will win. 18...Kc8 19.Ne7+ The final combination. 19...Bxe7 20.Qe8+ Bd8 21.Qxd8# } ) 
11. O-O-O { White should keep adding pieces to the attack. The rook on d1 is useful in a lot of lines. } Nc6 
12. Qxe4 { This is not just about taking a pawn, it opens the e-file and Re1 is a big threat. } Nf6 
13. Qe2 { You want to keep the pressure on e6. Re1 is still a threat. } Nd4 ( 13...Kf7 { Trying to escape with the king. } 14.Nf3 h6 15.Rhe1 { White's attack is simple to play: keep adding pieces, now e6 is hard to defend. } 15...Bxc4 { 15...Nd8 Trying to keep e6 under control, but White will just sacrifice his rook on d8. 16.Bc3 Bxc5 17.Rxd8 Rxd8 18.Bxe6+ This is game over. 18...Kf8 19.Nh4 There is nothing wrong with picking up the queen on c8, but playing for mate is even stronger. 19...Qc6 20.Bxf6 gxf6 21.Qg4 And mate will follow soon. } 16.Qxc4+ Kg6 { There are multiple ways for White to win here. An alternative is to play with g4 followed by g5. } 17.Bc3 { The start of a simple sequence that will result in a lot of White pieces near Black's king. } 17...Kh7 18.Bxf6 gxf6 19.Qf7+ Bg7 20.Rd7 Rg8 21.Re6 { Black can hardly move a piece. } 21...Kh8 22.Nh4 a5 { What else can Black do? } { 22...Ne5 doesn't help. White has a simple mating combination with queen and knight. 23.Rxe5 fxe5 24.Ng6+ Kh7 25.Qf5 Qc6 26.Nf8+ Kh8 27.Qh7# } 23.Ng6+ Kh7 24.Nf4 a4 25.Qxf6 { This threatens Qxh6 mate. } 25...Qxd7 26.Qf5+ { And now White delivers mate in another way. } 26...Kh8 27.Ng6+ Kh7 28.Nf8+ Kh8 29.Qh7# ) 
14. Qe3 Nc6 ( 14...Nf5 { Black may think he can still defend, but his problems along the e-file are too big. } 15.Qd3 Qd7 16.Re1 g6 { 16...Qxd3 Black escapes to an endgame. 17.Rxe6+ Kd7 18.cxd3 And White has three extra pawns and the pair of bishops and Black's king is not out of danger. Note that Black cannot take with 18...Bxc5 because he loses a piece after 19.Re5 . } 17.Rxe6+ Qxe6 18.Bxe6 Kxe6 { Materially speaking Black is only slightly worse, but the problem is his king safety. } 19.Nf3 Kf7 20.Ng5+ Kg7 21.Qb3 Rg8 22.Qf7+ { And Black loses a lot more material. } ) 
15. Re1 { Simple chess: keep increasing the pressure. } Nd8 
16. Nf3 g6 
17. Nd4 { And White will regain the piece on e6 with a completely winning position. Black is likely to lose a lot more material if he wants to avoid mate. } *

