10. Qxd5 { Instead, exchanging queens is not so useful now that Black still has his e-pawn and the d5-pawn is not isolated. } e5 ( { Taking } 10...Qxb2 { doesn't work for Black. Play will continue } 11.Qxf5 Qxa1 { and then White plays } 12.Qc2 { to lock in Black's queen on a1 which cannot get out. Because Black needs to spend a tempo with e7-e6 for his f8-bishop to join, he will be late and lose more material. } ) 
11. Qb5 {[%cal Gd4d5][%csl Rc6]} { Now Black cannot avoid the queen exchange because White threatens to win a piece with d4-d5. } O-O-O 
12. Qxb6 axb6 
13. dxe5 fxe5 { Phase one is completed. Queens are exchanged and the center is stable. Now it's time to focus on development. } 
14. Nbd2 Bc5 
15. Be2 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gd2b3,Gd2c4,Re5e4,Gf3h4]} { And Black doesn't have full compensation for the pawn. White's next moves could be Nb3 or Nc4, castling kingside and on e5-e4 White will play Nh4. } *

[Event "The Trompowsky: Simplified"]
[White "6) Pseudo-Trompowsky: 1...d5 2.Bg5 h6"]
[Black "3...c5 and 4...cxd4 #2"]
[Date "2023.01.02"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D00"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21651908"]

1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 which were analyzed in a separate chapter. } ) 
3. Bh4 { As we've seen in the previous chapter, in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} cxd4 
5. exd4 Nc6 ( 5...Bf5 { is also possible, but is very likely to transpose back to 5... Nc6 & 6... Bf5. } ) 
6. Nf3 Bf5 { Now Qb6 could be annoying so White stabilizes his center first. } 
7. c3 Qb6 { Black should not play g7-g5, with the pawns on c3 and d4 the bishop will not be effective on g7. } 
8. Qb3 {[%mdl 32768]} e6 
9. Nbd2 Nge7 
10. Bg3 { The bishop was not effective on h4 anymore. } h5 
11. Be2 f6 { Black wants take control over the e5-square and maybe even push e6-e5 at some point in the future. } 
12. h4 Nc8 { Preparing to exchange the bishops, Black likes to trade one pair of pieces because he lacks a bit of space. } 
13. O-O Bd6 
14. Bxd6 Nxd6 
15. Rfe1 Kf7 
16. a4 {[%cal Rb6b3,Gd2b3,Gb3a3,Ga4a5,Gd2f1,Gf1e3,Gb2b4,Gb4b5]} { The position is about equal but quite complex. The queens may get exchanged and then White will put pressure on the queenside with Nc5 and a4-a5 and b2-b4-b5 while for Black pushing e6-e5 is not so clear because after exchanging on e5 there will be a large hole on g5. If the queens stay on White may go for Qa3 followed by Nf1-Ne3 and a4-a5 and b2-b4-b5 to gain space on the queenside. } *

