1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 which were analyzed in a separate chapter. } ) 
3. Bh4 { As we've seen in the previous chapter, in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} cxd4 
5. exd4 Nc6 ( 5...Bf5 { is also possible, but is very likely to transpose back to 5... Nc6 & 6... Bf5. } ) 
6. Nf3 g5 
7. Bg3 {[%mdl 32768]} e6 
8. Bd3 Nf6 
9. Nc3 {[%cal Gc3b5]} { Threatening Nb5. } Nh5 ( 9...Bg7 10.Nb5 { Not winning material, but it's still annoying for Black to face. } 10...O-O 11.Bc7 Qd7 { This is White's idea with Nb5. Black's queenside cannot develop. } 12.h4 g4 13.Ne5 Nxe5 14.Bxe5 a6 15.Nc3 b5 16.a3 Bb7 17.f3 { On this move and the next ones Black cannot take on f3, because after 17...gxf3 18.gxf3 White will put a rook on the g-file, play Qd2 and mate will follow soon. } 17...Qe7 18.Qd2 Rac8 19.Qf4 { And on the next move White will play fxg4 with a winning position. } ) 
10. Be5 Nf6 ( 10...Nxe5 { is not the way to go for Black. } 11.Nxe5 Nf4 12.Bb5+ { Pushing the king forward, which is not immediately game over, but it does look bad for Black. } 12...Ke7 13.g3 Ng6 14.Nxg6+ fxg6 { White is playing simple chess. First force the black king to e7, now double Black's g-pawns. } 15.Qd2 Kf7 16.h4 { The reason we 'help' Black solve his doubled pawns is to be able to target the weak pawn on g6. Potentially in the future h6 can also be a problem, especially with a king on g7. } 16...gxh4 17.Rxh4 Kg7 18.O-O-O { White has a clear advantage. Next he will play Bd3, Rdh1 and Ne2-Nf4 with a winning attack. } ) 
11. O-O ( { After } 11.Bg3 { we could get a move repetition with } 11...Nh5 { and draw, but that's not why we play 2. Bg5! } ) a6 
12. h3 { Creating a way back for the bishop. } Bg7 { If Black takes on e5, White takes back with his knight followed by f2-f4. } 
13. Re1 Nxe5 
14. Nxe5 O-O { Now there is no f2-f4 with the rook on e1, but White can also attack in a different way. } 
15. Ne2 Nd7 
16. Ng3 {[%cal Rd7e5,Gd4e5,Gg3h5][%csl Rc8,Rg8]} -- ( { Threatening Nh5 and the black king will be in danger. Black can of course play } 16...Nxe5 { followed by f7-f5 here, but then the bishop on c8 is pretty much dead and White will have a long-term strategic advantage. } )
*

