[ECO "D00"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21651915"]

1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 which were analyzed in a separate chapter. } ) 
3. Bh4 { As we've seen in the previous chapter, in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} cxd4 
5. exd4 Nc6 ( 5...Bf5 { is also possible, but is very likely to transpose back to 5... Nc6 & 6... Bf5. } ) 
6. Nf3 Bg4 
7. c3 { Defending the pawn on d4 so that if Black takes on f3 White can take back with the queen. } Qb6 ( 7...Qd7 8.Nbd2 e6 9.Bd3 Bd6 10.Bg3 { White is happy to exchange the dark-squared bishops, because in the long term he wants to gain control over the e5-square. } 10...Nf6 11.O-O O-O 12.Re1 { Preparing Ne5. White can continue with Bxd6 and h3 after which Bh5 is bad because of g4 and after Bxf3 Nxf3 White is ready to jump to e5. } ) 
8. Nbd2 Qxb2 { A risky choice. } 
9. Rb1 Qxc3 ( 9...Qxa2 { is not good. Black loses too much time. } 10.Rxb7 { Threatening Bb5. } 10...a6 11.Bd3 Nf6 12.O-O { Always first put the king in a safe place! } 12...g5 13.Bg3 Bg7 14.Rb6 { White is targeting the pawn on e7. } 14...Nd8 15.Re1 Ne6 { Black is hoping to castle without losing the e7-pawn. } 16.h3 Bh5 17.Bb1 Qa5 18.Qb3 O-O 19.Bf5 { and Black is in trouble. My engine gives +2.8 for White. Black is likely to lose the e-pawn and will then be left with a position full of weaknesses and a queen that needs to be careful not to get lost. } ) 
10. Rxb7 { Bb5 should not be allowed, so Black's reply is forced. } a6 
11. Be2 Nf6 
12. O-O {[%mdl 32768]} Nd8 { Other moves are even worse for Black. } 
13. Qa4+ Qc6 
14. Qxc6+ { We have seen the transition to a favorable endgame before. } Nxc6 
15. Rb6 g5 
16. Bg3 Bd7 
17. Bxa6 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gf1b1,Gb6b8][%csl Re8]} { Material is equal but White has his strong passed a-pawn and if you are not an engine you will have a difficult life being Black here. White intends to continue with Rfb1, Ne5 and Rb8+. } *

