[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/21651916"]

1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 which were analyzed in a separate chapter. } ) 
3. Bh4 { As we've seen in the previous chapter, in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} cxd4 
5. exd4 Qb6 { There are different positions where Black can go for Qb6, sometimes with a pawn on c5, sometimes without. To be consistent I have chosen in all lines to sacrifice the pawn. Just remember - we don't play b2-b3 because it weakens the dark squares too much. (Of course to every rule there are one or two exceptions!) } 
6. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} Qxb2 
7. Nbd2 { Forced to save the rook. } e6 
8. Rb1 { Now if Black takes on a2 White will play in similar fashion as in the main line, but because the knight on d2 is not pinned White can claim some advantage. } Qc3 ( 8...Qxa2 { is a risky decision by Black, challenging White to show what he has for the two pawns. } 9.Ne5 Nd7 10.Bb5 Ngf6 { So far White has played similarly to the line where Black doesn't take on a2 but plays Qc3 on move 8, but now White uses the fact that Black doesn't have any Bb4 ideas. } 11.Qf3 { Threatening to take twice on f6. } 11...Qxc2 12.Ke2 Qf5 { This is Black's only defence. Other moves already lose. } 13.Qxf5 { White is going for a better endgame. } 13...exf5 14.Bxf6 gxf6 15.Nxd7 Bxd7 16.Bxd7+ Kxd7 17.Rxb7+ { It is an endgame but the Black king is not out of danger yet. } 17...Kd8 18.Ra1 a5 19.Rb5 { White is clearly better, especially if you play this against another human. White is likely to win the pawn on d5 and go after the pawn on a5 (the pawn on f5 can wait). Black's problem is his pawn structure and his only hope is his a-pawn but it is hard to defend while his king is still on d8. White's next moves include Rxd5 and either Rxa5 or Nb3 or Rb5 threatening Rxb4 if Black tries to defend with Bb4. } ) 
9. Ne5 { Immediately going forward because Black is weak around his king. } Bb4 { If Black had played Qxa2 he would not have this move, meaning the b-file would still be open. } 
10. Bb5+ Bd7 
11. Nxd7 Nxd7 
12. a3 { A tricky move because after either capture on a3 White will be able to castle kingside and Black is in serious trouble with his king. } Qxa3 { This doesn't lose immediately for Black, but he does end up in trouble. } 
13. O-O Ngf6 
14. c3 { A tricky move in order to open the b-file. } Ba5 ( 14...Qxc3 { This just loses a piece. } 15.Bxf6 gxf6 16.Bxd7+ Kxd7 17.Qa4+ { And next is Qxb4 defending the knight on d2. } ) ( 14...Bxc3 15.Bxf6 gxf6 16.Rb3 { We will see that the black queen is even unhappier on a5 than on a3. } 16...Qa5 17.Bxd7+ Kxd7 18.Rxb7+ Kc8 19.Nb3 { Gaining an important tempo on the queen to bring another piece to the attack. From c5 the knight also defends the rook on b7 if needed. } 19...Qa4 20.Qc1 { Making use of the tactic 20...Kxb7 21.Nc5+ . } 20...Qc4 21.Rxf7 { Black is in big trouble with his king, the active rook on f7 and the knight coming to c5. White will also play Qf4 with a mating threat on c7 and if Black defends, the rook on f1 can come to c1 with devastating impact. } ) 
15. Bxf6 gxf6 
16. Bxd7+ Kxd7 
17. Rxb7+ Bc7 
18. Qh5 { It is not difficult to play this attack with White. } Qe7 
19. Nb3 {[%cal Rb3c5,Rf1a1,Rf1b1,Rh5h6][%csl Rd7,Rf6,Rf7,Rh6]} { White has a clear advantage because of Black's king position and the weak pawn structure. At the very least Black will have to return the extra pawn by giving up h6, but even after that Black's king will still not be safe, the knight on c5 is stronger than the bishop on c7 and the pawns on f6 and f7 are vulnerable. } *

