1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 which were analyzed in a separate chapter. } ) 
3. Bh4 { As we've seen in the previous chapter, in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} cxd4 
5. exd4 Qb6 { There are different positions where Black can go for Qb6, sometimes with a pawn on c5, sometimes without. To be consistent I have chosen in all lines to sacrifice the pawn. Just remember - we don't play b2-b3 because it weakens the dark squares too much. (Of course to every rule there are one or two exceptions!) } 
6. Nf3 e6 
7. Nbd2 {[%mdl 32768]} { White usually goes for a setup with Nbd2 and c2-c3 and later Ne5. } Ne7 ( 7...Be7 8.Bxe7 { Normally Bg3 is a fine option but here 8.Bg3 Qxb2 is a bit annoying. } 8...Nxe7 9.Nb3 O-O 10.Bd3 { There is no reason for 10. Be2 with Black's bishop still on c8. } 10...a5 11.a4 { We don't want to allow a5-a4. Also, sometimes the b5-square can come in handy for White. } 11...Qc7 12.O-O b6 13.Re1 { White focuses on controlling the e5-square. } 13...Ba6 { Taking out White's main weapon for an attack on the king. } 14.Nc1 { So that at least White wins a tempo by taking back with the knight that wants to control e5 anyway. } 14...Bxd3 15.Nxd3 Nd7 16.c3 { White's position is easy to play: Nfe5, Qf3, Ree3 and Rae1 and potentially start a kingside attack with g2-g4 and h2-h4. } ) 
8. Bg3 { Now that Black doesn't have Bb4 ideas for the moment, White can leave the pawn on b2 unprotected. } Nf5 { Black is taking a solid approach. } ( 8...Qxb2 { is once again quite risky for Black. } 9.Rb1 Qc3 { 9...Qxa2 10.Bxb8 Rxb8 11.Bb5+ Bd7 12.Bxd7+ Kxd7 13.Ne5+ Ke8 14.c4 Note that 14.Qf3 (like in the other line) doesn't work here because of 14...Nf5 and White doesn't win an exchange with Nc6. 14...g5 15.Ra1 Qb2 16.Qa4+ b5 17.Qxa7 Rd8 18.O-O White has a strong attack that is likely to bring him the full point. On 18...Qxd2 White has 19.Qb7 followed by Ra7 and Nc6, winning. } 10.Rb3 Qa5 11.Bxb8 Rxb8 12.Bb5+ Bd7 13.Bxd7+ Kxd7 14.Ne5+ Ke8 15.Qf3 { Now on 15...Nf5 White has 16.Nc6! } 15...f6 16.Qh5+ g6 17.Nxg6 { White is clearly better here because of Black's king in the middle. White will castle and continue with the attack, bringing in all his pieces. } ) 
9. Nb3 ( 9.-- Qxb2 { had become a real threat because Black can follow up with Bb4+. } ) Nxg3 
10. hxg3 Bd6 
11. c3 { White's strategy hasn't changed: stabilize the center and focus on the e5-square. } Bd7 
12. a4 { Making it more difficult for Black to exchange bishops with Bb5. } Nc6 
13. Be2 { Bd3 is also an option, but in this case I prefer to leave d3 open for a knight. } O-O 
14. O-O a6 
15. Ne1 Qc7 
16. Nd3 {[%cal Gb3d2,Gd2f3,Gf1e1,Gf3e5,Ge2f1,Gd1f3,Gg3g4][%csl Rd7,Rg8]} { It may seem strange to play this knight to d3, but the one from b3 can go via d2 to f3 and White has achieved his goal. He will combine this with Re1 and Bf1 and be ready for Nfe5 followed by Qf3 and g3-g4 to launch a kingside initiative. } *

