Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} cxd4 
5. exd4 Qb6 { There are different positions where Black can go for Qb6, sometimes with a pawn on c5, sometimes without. To be consistent I have chosen in all lines to sacrifice the pawn. Just remember - we don't play b2-b3 because it weakens the dark squares too much. (Of course to every rule there are one or two exceptions!) } 
6. Nf3 Bf5 
7. Bd3 { You don't want to sacrifice the pawn on b2 if the pawn on c2 then also hangs. } Bxd3 
8. Qxd3 Nc6 
9. Nbd2 {[%mdl 32768]} { This way White doesn't need to defend b2 yet. } e6 ( 9...Qxb2 { Here this capture is too risky for Black. } 10.Rb1 Qxa2 11.Rxb7 Qa4 { Preventing Qb5. } 12.O-O g5 13.Bg3 Bg7 14.Nb3 { White goes queen hunting and it turns out that the black queen can no longer escape. } 14...Qc4 15.Qe3 Nf6 16.Nfd2 Qa6 17.Nc5 Qa5 18.Bc7 Qa2 19.Qc3 O-O 20.Ra1 { and Black loses at least a piece to save his queen after } 20...Nxd4 { . } ) 
10. O-O Nge7 { We have seen Be7 in similar lines. } 
11. Rfe1 Ng6 { This loses. } ( 11...Qa6 { Not many Black players will voluntarily go for this exchange resulting in doubled a-pawns, but it is playable. } 12.Qxa6 bxa6 13.c3 Rb8 { Black is using the upside of the doubled a-pawns: he has a half-open b-file to put pressure on White's queenside. } 14.b4 Nf5 { On 14...a5 White can simply answer with 15.a3 . } 15.Bg3 Nxg3 16.hxg3 g5 17.Nb3 { The c5-square is a great outpost for a white knight. } 17...g4 18.Ne5 Nxe5 19.Rxe5 { Funnily enough, the engine says this position is about equal. I would think that with Black's weak a-pawns as well as the advanced (vulnerable) g-pawn White must be better. In practice such a position is much easier to play with White: you can play a2-a4-a5 so that Nc5 is always a threat, bring your king to d3 to protect the c3-pawn and use the a-rook to come to h1 to put pressure on h6 (or h5 if Black pushes it to defend the g-pawn). } ) 
12. Rxe6+ { Here we go! It's always nice if you can play such a move! } fxe6 
13. Qxg6+ Kd7 
14. Qf7+ Be7 
15. Ne5+ { You can easily find these moves for White, even in a blitz game. } Nxe5 
16. Qxe7+ Kc8 
