1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 which were analyzed in a separate chapter. } ) 
3. Bh4 { As we've seen in the previous chapter, in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} cxd4 
5. exd4 Qb6 { There are different positions where Black can go for Qb6, sometimes with a pawn on c5, sometimes without. To be consistent I have chosen in all lines to sacrifice the pawn. Just remember - we don't play b2-b3 because it weakens the dark squares too much. (Of course to every rule there are one or two exceptions!) } 
6. Nf3 Bf5 
7. Bd3 { You don't want to sacrifice the pawn on b2 if the pawn on c2 then also hangs. } Bxd3 
8. Qxd3 Qxb2 { Black accepts the pawn sacrifice, but objectively he is now lost! } ( 8...e6 { is a more solid move. Black refrains from accepting the pawn sacrifice. } 9.O-O { Here taking on b2 is out of the question for Black, because after Nc3 and Rab1 he would be too much behind in development and threats like Nb5 are hard to defend against. } 9...Be7 10.Bxe7 { Moving the bishop to g3 is also possible, but you need to play very precisely then because the bishop could become passive or get exchanged after a future Nh5. } 10...Nxe7 11.Nbd2 O-O 12.Rab1 { Now that Black has managed to castle it is time to defend b2. } 12...Nd7 13.c3 { Objectively speaking the position is equal, but it is in structure similar to a reversed Queen's Gambit or, from White's point of view, the exchange line in the Caro-Kann. It means Black plays on the queenside and can prepare a minority attack while White will try to launch a kingside attack. Therefore White's next moves are Rfe1 (or Rbe1 if Black moves his queen from b6), Ne5, f2-f4 and then perhaps a rook to the third rank followed by Rg3 or Kh1 and g4 and Rg1 and g5. } ) 
9. O-O {[%mdl 32768]} Qxa1 ( 9...Nd7 { Black doesn't take the rook, but he is still too much behind in development. } 10.Na3 { Threatening to win the queen with Rfb1. } 10...Qb6 11.Rab1 Qc6 12.c4 { And this advance is the reason why on move 10 I prefer Na3 over Nc3. White is opening the position. } 12...dxc4 13.Nxc4 { My engine already gives +6. Black hasn't started developing his kingside yet and he is completely lost. White will next play Nfe5 and then either win the pawn on b7 or play Qf3 with a double attack on f7 and b7. Again, it is likely White will get a rook on b7 with a winning advantage. } ) ( 9...Qb4 { Trying to escape. } 10.Na3 { The problem is that Nb5 is a serious threat. } 10...a6 11.Rfb1 Qa4 12.Rxb7 Nc6 13.c4 { White has a winning advantage: all his pieces are active while Black still needs to start developing his kingside. White will take on d5 to open the position further and the rook can come back to b3 if it gets attacked. } ) 
10. Qb3 {[%csl Ra1]} { Locking in the black queen. } Nd7 
11. Na3 Qxf1+ 
12. Kxf1 {[%csl Re8,Rf8,Rg8,Rh8]} { From a material point of view Black is not doing so badly but the problem is that he has developed only one piece so far. } Ngf6 
13. Nb5 {[%cal Rb5c7]} { The check on c7 is a big threat and Black doesn't have a good answer. } Rc8 
14. Nxa7 Rc7 
15. Bg3 {[%cal Rg3c7,Rb3b7]} { Black is busted. The engine says +7 and White will soon win material by either taking the rook on c7 or playing Qxb7 with Qa8+ as a winning threat. } *

