1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 which were analyzed in a separate chapter. } ) 
3. Bh4 { As we've seen in the previous chapter, in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} Nc6 
5. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} g5 
6. Bg3 Bg7 { This concept is recommended by Boris Avrukh. } 
7. c3 { As usual, we play against the bishop on g7, which is not so strong when the pawn on d4 is supported by pawns on e3 and c3. } Qb6 
8. Qb3 ( { White could also have played } 8.Qc2 { but it results in a very different type of play. } ) Qxb3 
9. axb3 { This is a good structure for White as long as he doesn't end up with a single pawn on d4, but here there is always a pawn on c3 or e3 and White has even stronger. } cxd4 
10. Nxd4 { Taking back with one of the pawns isn't bad either, but this is even stronger. } e5 ( 10...Nxd4 { Black thinks that the more he exchanges, the quicker he will reach a drawish ending, but that's not the case in this line! } 11.cxd4 Nf6 12.Nc3 O-O 13.Bd3 { White is playing simple chess, just developing his pieces. Note that there is no need to castle kingside, the king is also fine in the center on d2 or e2. } 13...Bd7 14.h4 { Threatening to take on g5 after which the g5-pawn is weak and Black always needs to watch out for tricks with Be5 and later Bh7+. } 14...g4 { But now the bishop on d7 is quite passive. } 15.Kd2 { White has a nice advantage. He can put pressure on Black's queenside with moves like b3-b4-b5, Rhc1 and Na4-Nc5 and White's bishops have a lot more potential than Black's. } ) 
11. Nxc6 { Damaging Black's pawn structure on the queenside. } bxc6 
12. f3 { You don't want to allow a future Ne4 from Black with the threat of exchanging on g3. } Ne7 
13. b4 { Blocking Black's queenside. } O-O 
14. Nd2 Be6 
15. e4 { Regaining some control in the center which White had released when he took back on d4 with his knight. } f5 
16. Bf2 fxe4 
17. fxe4 d4 { Black is gaining space, but his d-pawn is going nowhere. } 
18. Bc4 Bxc4 
19. Nxc4 {[%cal Ga1a6,Ge1e2,Gh1d1][%csl Re5,Rg5,Rg7,Rh6]} { White is clearly better here. Black's bishop on g7 is quite bad compared to the one on f2 and the pawns on a7 and c6 are weak. White's next moves include Ke2, Rhd1 and Ra6. } *

