1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 which were analyzed in a separate chapter. } ) 
3. Bh4 { As we've seen in the previous chapter, in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} Nc6 
5. Nf3 g5 
6. Bg3 Bg7 { This concept is recommended by Boris Avrukh. } 
7. c3 { As usual, we play against the bishop on g7, which is not so strong when the pawn on d4 is supported by pawns on e3 and c3. } Qb6 
8. Qb3 ( { White could also have played } 8.Qc2 { but it results in a very different type of play. } ) c4 { Black is going for the most principled approach. } 
9. Qc2 {[%mdl 32768]} Bf5 { A sharp move that will result in huge complications. } ( 9...g4 { A valid alternative, but in practice I would expect all Black players to go for the line with 9... Bf5. } 10.Nh4 e5 11.Be2 { Normal development and kingside castling before starting any operations. } 11...Nge7 12.O-O O-O 13.b3 { A logical move to undermine Black's pawn center. } 13...cxb3 14.axb3 Be6 15.Na3 { Maybe White has a tiny edge, but more important is the fact that it is a complex position with a lot of play. White has ideas of playing f2-f3 after first playing Kh1 (so that sacrifices on d4 are not dangerous), but White can also play it more safely with dxe5 followed by Nb5 and Nd4. } ) 
10. Qxf5 Qxb2 { Black has sacrificed the bishop on f5 in order to win the rook on a1. } 
11. Qxd5 Nf6 { Not the only move for Black, but quite an obvious one. } 
12. Qxc4 Qc1+ { It is important for Black to first chase the White king forward so he loses the right to castle and cannot easily develop. } ( 12...Qxa1 { It is not good for Black to immediately take the rook. } 13.Qb3 { Locking in the black queen. } 13...O-O 14.Bd3 Na5 15.Qc2 Rac8 16.O-O { This is the key difference with the line with Qc1+: White is able to castle. Soon Black will have to give up material to save his queen and White will have a winning position. } ) 
13. Ke2 Qb2+ 
14. Nfd2 { And not the knight from b1 because White really wants to try to lock up Black's queen on a1. } Qxa1 { So far we are following the line that Boris Avrukh gives in his book Beating 1.d4 sidelines. But the line should not end here! } 
15. d5 Nxd5 ( 15...Nd8 { Moving the knight backwards is too slow. } 16.Qb3 { Simple chess: taking away the b2-square from the black queen. } 16...O-O 17.Be5 { Protecting the pawn on c3 and preparing ideas like Bd4 followed by c3-c4, winning the queen. } 17...b6 18.g3 { And White has a winning advantage. He has multiple ways of going after the queen, for example Bg2 followed by Na3 and there is not much Black can do. } ) 
16. Qxd5 { Of course White takes the piece. He now has sufficient material for the rook, but his king is still in the way of the bishop on f1. White will try to exchange queens and then unravel on the kingside. Play through the remaining moves to see how play could develop. } Bxc3 
17. Nxc3 Qxc3 
18. Qb3 { If the queens are exchanged, the white king will not be in danger in the center and White's two bishops are likely to decide the game. } Qc1 
19. Qb1 Qxb1 
20. Nxb1 O-O 
21. h4 {[%cal Gh4g5,Gh1h5,Gf2f4,Ge2f3,Gf1d3][%csl Rg5,Rg8]} { The engine says it is about equal, but I think White players have a great chance of outplaying their opponent from this position. White has two bishops for a rook and a pawn and the bishops will soon become active. White can take on g5 and then play, for example, f2-f4 with the idea that if Black takes on f4, White takes back with the bishop and the black king becomes vulnerable.

White also has the simple idea of playing Kf3 and then activating the bishop from f1. Meanwhile for Black it is not so simple, as White doesn't have any major weaknesses. } *

