1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 which were analyzed in a separate chapter. } ) 
3. Bh4 { As we've seen in the previous chapter, in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c5 { A direct attack on White's center. Black is trying to prove that the bishop on h4 is offside and that both d4 and b2 are now a bit weak. } 
4. e3 {[%cal Rd8b6,Rb8c6][%csl Rb2,Rd4]} Qb6 
5. c4 ( { Here White can play 5. Nf3 and try to transpose to the line with Black first taking on d4 (cxd4) and then Qxb2. However, Black is not forced to take on d4, so for example after } 5.Nf3 Qxb2 6.Nbd2 { Black can play } 6...c4 { and I don't trust this variation. That is why we don't play 5.Nf3 here. } ) Qxb2 ( { If Black plays } 5...e6 { we will transpose back to the variation 5...Qxb2 with } 6.cxd5 Qxb2 7.Nd2 { . } ) 
6. Nd2 e6 { Opening the line for the f8-bishop to help the queen. Black would love to play Bb4 at some point. } 
7. cxd5 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Rc5d4,Ga1b1,Gf1b5,Gd5e6]} exd5 ( { Now Black is not in time to take on d4: After } 7...cxd4 { White plays } 8.Rb1 { followed by Bb5+ and dxe6, winning. } ) 
8. dxc5 Bxc5 
9. Rb1 Qa3 { A slightly more solid approach, declining to take the second pawn. } 
10. Bb5+ Nd7 ( 10...Bd7 { Again the most solid option for Black. } 11.Ngf3 Ne7 12.O-O Bb6 { I'm not sure how many Black players would be able to find this move. } 13.Rb3 Qc5 14.Qb1 { White has also many other options that are good, such as 14. a4. This shows that White has sufficient compensation in general and he doesn't need to play very accurately. } 14...O-O 15.Bxd7 { White wants his pawn back. If he prefers to keep the tension he can continue with 15.Rc1 with long-term compensation for the pawn. } 15...Nxd7 16.Rb5 Qd6 17.Bxe7 Qxe7 18.Rxd5 { The position is about equal. White's next moves include Nb3 or Nc4 followed by Rfd1. } ) 
11. Rb3 {[%cal Ra3a2,Gd1c1,Gc5b6,Gb3a3]} { And now taking on a2 would fail to Qc1 threatening Qxc5 and if Black plays Bb6 White wins the queen with Ra3! } Qa5 
12. Ngf3 Be7 
13. Bxe7 Nxe7 
14. Qa1 {[%cal Ra1g7]} { Defending the pawn on a2 and threatening to take on g7. } O-O 
15. Bxd7 Bxd7 
16. Rxb7 {[%cal Ge1g1,Gb7d7,Gf1c1,Gc1b1,Gd2b3,Gb3c5]} { White has his pawn back, an active rook on the seventh rank and in the long term the isolated pawn on d5 could become weak. White's next moves will be castling followed by Rc1 or Rfb1 and Nb3-Nc5. } *

