1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. } h6 { This move is played a lot in practice. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the Trompowsky lines [/variation/21553258/#/2/b] with 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 which were analyzed in a separate chapter. } ) 
3. Bh4 { As we've seen in the previous chapter, in the lines with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/ppp1pppp/8/3p2B1/3P4/8/PPP1PPPP/RN1QKBNR b KQkq - 1 2@@EndFEN@@ 2...f6 we don't go to h4 with the bishop because of 3.Bh4 Nh6 and Nf5, but here that is not an option for Black so retreating to h4 is fine.

Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } c6 
4. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} { Not just developing but also defending the bishop on h4. } ( { Note that } 4.e3 { is not a good move here. We need to be careful! We cannot exactly play in the same way as in the position without h6 Bh4. } 4...Qb6 5.Qc1 { And now Black has a breakthrough based on a small tactic. } 5...e5 { And White cannot take on e5 (which is possible if his bishop was still on g5): } 6.dxe5 Qb4+ { and Black wins a piece. } ) Qb6 
5. b3 { This move is fine if Black has lost a tempo with c7-c6. Usually b3 is not a good idea if Black has played c7-c5 in one go. } Bf5 ( { Of course, Black has some alternatives here, so let me point out a few. Rizzitano recommended } 5...a5 { in 'How to beat 1.d4', but I don't think it threatens anything, so White can just continue with his development. } ) ( { Graham Burgess in 'An Idiot Proof Opening Chess Opening Repertoire' has } 5...Nd7 { as a main line. Here I like the simple move } 6.Bg3 { to maintain control over the e5-square, followed by playing e2-e3 and continuing with development.

None of these lines will result in large advantages for White, but it is important to realize we want to determine the type of play and get positions on the board we are familiar with! } ) 
6. e3 e6 
7. Bd3 { Instead, putting the bishop on e2 feels a bit passive. } Bxd3 
8. Qxd3 Nd7 
9. O-O Be7 
10. Bxe7 ( { The alternative } 10.Bg3 { is also playable, but you need to be careful with White that you don't end up with a passive bishop. For example, after a later Nf3-e5 Nxe5 dxe5 and the bishop on g3 is looking at its own pawn. } ) Nxe7 
11. c4 O-O 
12. Nc3 {[%cal Gc4c5,Gb3b4,Gb4b5,Ge3e4,Gg1h1,Gf1g1,Gg2g4]} { And White had a tiny advantage in the top-level game Artemiev,V -Dominguez Perez,L chess24.com INT 2020. The position has also been played by great players like Caruana and Kramnik on the black side, but we need to remember that we don't play at their level (nor do our opponents).

Objectively speaking, White is a little better. He has a bit more space and has three different plans: 1) Play c4-c5 followed by b3-b4-b5 to generate some initiative on the queenside. 2) Play e3-e4 to gain more space in the center. 3) Play Kh1, Rg1 and g4-g5 to launch a kingside attack. } *

