Because the bishop is on h4 far away from the queenside, there are quite a few lines where Black plays Qb6 with the idea to take on b2. These are complicated lines with very good winning chances for White and I will discuss them in great detail. } g5 ( 3...Nf6 4.Bxf6 { is similar to the lines with 1...Nf6 and 2...d5 where we take on f6. The only difference is that the black h-pawn has moved from h7 to h6, which sometimes doesn't make a difference (when the pawn later moves to h5), but usually is slightly worse for Black because his bishop from f8 can no longer go to h6 directly (Black first needs the extra move h5 and there the pawn might be weak). } ) 
