1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. In this chapter we will deal with setups where Black tries to ignore the bishop on g5. } Nd7 { Black prepares Ngf6 without allowing doubled f-pawns. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 Trompowsky chapter [/variation/21553258/#/2/b]. } ) 
3. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} Ngf6 
4. Nf3 { White is playing a hybrid of a Torre attack and London system, the main difference being the bishop on g5 and the knight on d7 locking in the bishop on c8 for now. } g6 { A rare move. Most black players who fianchetto their bishop prefer to do this without a pawn on d5. } 
5. c4 Bg7 ( { If Black now takes } 5...dxc4 { , White plays } 6.Bxc4 { , castles kingside followed by Nc3. Black will play c7-c5 after which White can choose between d4-d5 and allowing cxd4 after for example Re1. } ) ( { If Black supports his d-pawn with } 5...c6 { , White will play } 6.cxd5 { followed by Nc3, Bd3 and O-O. We'd arrive in a kind of exchange Slav structure in which White's pieces are more active. Black probably needs to play Nb6 at some point but if this knight cannot go to c4 (White may have queen on e2, bishop on d3 and rook on c1), the knight is rather passive on b6. } ) 
6. Nc3 ( { White can also take on d5, but then after } 6.cxd5 Nxd5 { we transpose to a Grunfeld structure. There White has lost a tempo with e2-e3 in case he wants to play e4 some day, while on the other hand Black's knight on d7 is misplaced. I'm not sure who is better, but the main reason I am not recommending it is because we don't face this structure anywhere else in the repertoire. } ) c6 
7. Bd3 dxc4 ( { If Black doesn't take on this move or the next (he can also first castle) his position becomes quite passive if he plays something like } 7...Nb6 { or } ) ( 7...e6 { . } ) 
8. Bxc4 O-O 
9. O-O Nb6 
10. Be2 { This square is better for the bishop than d3 where it blocks the d-pawn and the pin with Bg4 is sometimes annoying. In these types of positions, White wants to keep the option open of playing e3-e4 (but there is no hurry to do so) and even sometimes d4-d5 if Black manages to get c6-c5 in. } Nbd5 
11. Rc1 { Preparing the minority attack. } Bf5 
12. h3 h6 
13. Bh4 Rc8 
14. Na4 {[%cal Ga4c5,Ga2a3,Gb2b4,Gb4b5]} { White has a small advantage based on the initiative on the queenside where he can put a knight on c5 followed by a2-a3 and b2-b4-b5 to weaken Black's queenside structure. Black struggles to become active. His normal plans of breaking the center open with either his c-pawn or e-pawn are hard to realize. } *

