1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. In this chapter we will deal with setups where Black tries to ignore the bishop on g5. } Nd7 { Black prepares Ngf6 without allowing doubled f-pawns. } ( 2...Nf6 { transposes to the 1...Nf6 and 2... d5 Trompowsky chapter [/variation/21553258/#/2/b]. } ) 
3. e3 Ngf6 
4. Nf3 { White is playing a hybrid of a Torre attack and London system, the main difference being the bishop on g5 and the knight on d7 locking in the bishop on c8 for now. } e6 ( 4...c5 { hardly has any independent value. We quickly transpose to structures that are also covered in other lines with c2-c3, Nbd2 and Bd3, for example the lines with 4...e6 followed by a later c7-c5: } 5.c3 e6 6.Nbd2 Bd6 7.Bd3 O-O 8.O-O { And we have reached a position where normally the black knight is on c6. On d7 it either transposes in case Black manages to get e6-e5 in, or it is slighly worse positioned because it doesn't put pressure on d4. White's plan remains the same: prepare e3-e4, then take on c5 followed by e3-e4. } ) 
5. Bd3 {[%mdl 32768]} Be7 
6. Nbd2 { The move order is not so relevant. White needs to play c2-c3, Nd2, and Bd3. } O-O 
7. c3 { For the time being White keeps the option open of castling kingside or queenside. } c5 { This position can also be reached by an earlier c7-c5, for example on move 4. } 
8. Ne5 { This move is an essential part of White's strategy and the beginning of an attack. } Nxe5 ( { If Black plays something like } 8...Qc7 { White is happy to support his knight with f4 and after developing his queen and castling queenside he will launch an attack. } ) 
9. dxe5 Nd7 
10. Bxe7 { You don't want to go back with the bishop to f4 where it would be passively staring at its own pawn on e5. } Qxe7 
11. f4 f6 ( { If Black now plays passively White is ready to attack with } 11...-- 12.Qh5 { . After } 12...h6 { White has queenside castling followed by g4 and if Black plays } { 12...g6 instead of h6 White has 13.Qh6 followed by queenside castling and h2-h4-h5. } ) 
12. Qh5 { Threatening Qxh7+ and Bg6 mate. } g6 
13. Qh4 { Winning a tempo because of the pin on the f6-pawn. } Qg7 
14. exf6 Qxf6 
15. Qxf6 { Many attackers forget that sometimes it is better to exchange to an endgame, especially if you analyze with an engine in the background which won't fall for a cheap mate! } Nxf6 
16. Nf3 a5 
17. O-O-O {[%cal Gh2h3,Gh1e1,Gd3c2][%csl Rc8,Gd3,Re6]} { White has a nice advantage because the pawn on e6 is weak, White's bishop on d3 is stronger than its counterpart on c8 and on e5 there is a beautiful square for the knight. White's next moves could be h2-h3 (to prevent Ng4), Rhe1 and Bc2. It's fine for White to exchange the bishop on d3 for Black's knight because in the resulting position White's knight on f3 is stronger than Black's bishop. } *

