1. d4 d5 
2. Bg5 { This move really takes Black players out of their comfort zone and it is known as the Pseudo-Trompowsky. Some lines can transpose to familiar setups from the Queen's Gambit Declined or a kind of London setup, but almost always with a little twist and if Black players are not aware they can quickly get in trouble. In this chapter we will deal with setups where Black tries to ignore the bishop on g5. } c5 
3. e3 { Usually when Black plays c5 we answer with e3. We don't want to give away the center by taking on c5 and defending with Nf3 is not ideal because a knight on d4 can easily be chased away. White can sometimes answer c7-c5 with c2-c3, but that results in a symmetrical pawn structure after pawns are exchanged on d4 and I prefer to have a bit more imbalance. } f6 {[%cal Rg8h6,Rh6f5,Gg5h4]} 
4. Bf4 { Whenever Black plays f6 and still has the option of Nh6 we don't play Bh4 because a later Nh6-f5 would be annoying. } Nc6 ( 4...cxd4 5.exd4 Nc6 6.Nf3 Bg4 7.Be2 { is a transposition to the line with 4...Nc6 and 6...cxd4. } ) 
5. Nf3 Bg4 { The human move. } 
6. Be2 { You want to get rid of the pin on the knight on f3 so that the pawn on d4 stays protected. } cxd4 
7. exd4 e6 
8. O-O {[%mdl 32768]} { White has castled and is ready to develop his b1-knight. Normally in these types of positions you don't play c2-c4 with White because it would weaken the d4-pawn after ...dxc4. The exception is if almost immediately White would win the pawn on e6. } Nge7 { Black doesn't want to exchange the dark squared bishops and aims to put his knight on g6 to drive away the f4-bishop. } ( 8...Bd6 9.Bxd6 Qxd6 10.Nbd2 { The position is equal, but at the same time quite complex. Black can decide to push for e6-e5 at a later stage but then after dxe5 fxe5 the pawn on d5 could be weak and White may also have the option of playing Ne4, exploiting the fact that Black's queen on d6 is undefended.

If Black doesn't play for e6-e5 White can increase the pressure on the e6 pawn by playing Re1 and offering the exchange of light-squared bishops, intending to take back with the queen on e2. Meanwhile, Black also still needs 2 moves (Ne7 and O-O) to catch up with White in terms of development. } ) 
9. h3 Bxf3 
10. Bxf3 Ng6 
11. Be3 { White has a pair of bishops and if he manages to open the position Black will be in trouble. } Nh4 { A precise move. Black limits the power of White's bishop pair. } ( 11...Bd6 { Black misses one tempo to equalize: if only he had castled here already... } 12.c4 { Opening the position with brute force. } 12...dxc4 13.d5 Nce5 { Taking 13...exd5 is suicide. White takes back 14.Bxd5 and I don't see a human holding it for Black, as the center has opened up with Black's king unable to castle. } 14.Qa4+ Kf8 15.Be4 { White has a nice advantage. Black's king is still in danger, the rook on h8 is not participating and White has multiple ideas: he can play f2-f4 with the idea to open the f-file at some point (for example if Black plays f6-f5), he can take on e6 followed by taking on b7 and of course the simple Nc3 and then Rad1 is also strong. } ) 
12. Be2 Nf5 
13. c4 {[%csl Re8]} { A sharp pawn sacrifice to open the position while Black's king is still in the center. } dxc4 
14. Bxc4 Ncxd4 
15. Bxd4 Nxd4 
16. Nc3 {[%csl Re6,Rf7]} { White is now going to maximize the pressure on e6. Black could at some point play e6-e5, but this creates a lot of weaknesses around his king, especially the squares f7 and e6. } Qb6 
17. Qa4+ Kf7 
18. Rfe1 {[%cal Ga4c2,Gc3b5,Gc2f5,Ge1e2,Ga1e1]} { White has sufficient compensation for the pawn and some good attacking chances. His main idea is to go Nb5 next to exchange the knight on d4 that defends e6. The pawn on e6 is the real target for White and not easy to defend for Black in the long run. So after exchanging knights White may continue with Re2 and Rae1 and Qc2-Qf5 once the bishop is back on c4. } *

