5. Bg3 {[%mdl 32768]} c5 ( 5...Nf6 { transposes to the variation [/variation/21673515/#/5/b] 2... h6 #2. } ) ( { If Black plays } 5...d6 { we should answer } 6.h4 g4 7.Bc4 { and now most of Black's tries will result in similar play as discussed in this chapter. The only move with independent value is } 7...e5 { , but then White continues with } 8.dxe5 dxe5 9.Qxd8 { (9.Bf7+ is also ok) followed by Nc3 and queenside castling with a clear advantage. } ) 
6. c3 {[%csl Rg7]} { Similar to many other lines in the repertoire we defend the pawn on d4 with pawns on c3 and e3, making the bishop on g7 inactive. } Qb6 
7. Nf3 Qxb2 { Accepting the pawn sacrifice is quite dangerous. } 
8. Nbd2 Nc6 ( { Grabbing more material with } 8...Qxc3 { is not ok for Black. } 9.Rc1 Qb4 { White has now multiple strong alternatives, but we like simple chess so we play } 10.Rxc5 Nc6 11.Rxf5 { and we have regained our sacrificed material with a large advantage based on our development and the weak squares in Black's camp. } ) 
9. Ne5 { The engine actually prefers 9. Bc7, but at the end of the line White has won a queen against a rook, a bishop and two pawns and it is not that clear to me that White is better. } Nxe5 
10. dxe5 d5 { Black tries to gain some space so he can develop his pieces. } ( { The capture } 10...Qxc3 { is too dangerous. } 11.Rc1 Qa5 12.Bd3 { Simple chess: threatening to take on f5 and getting ready to castle. White is not in a hurry with Qh5+, as for the moment the king on e8 is not going anywhere. } 12...e6 13.O-O Ne7 14.Nc4 { Oops! There is a nice square on d6 for this knight. } 14...Qd8 15.Nd6+ Kf8 16.Qh5 { Threatening mate in one is usually not a bad idea. } 16...Kg8 17.f4 g4 18.Bh4 Kh7 19.e4 { Game over. Black's queenside is still not participating while his kingside is collapsing. He cannot take on e4 because of } 19...fxe4 20.Bxe4+ { and } 20...Kg8 21.Qf7 { mate and he can also not defend f5, it is simply under attack too many times. } ) 
