10. Rb1 Qa3 { We should also consider what happens if Black continues grabbing pawns: } ( 10...Qxa2 { Surprisingly, even this move is still playable for Black. } 11.Bb5+ Bd7 12.O-O O-O 13.Nd4 { White's pieces are more active than Black's and the pawns on b7 and f5 are weak: White has sufficient compensation for the sacrificed pawn. } 13...Nc6 14.Bd3 Ne4 15.Nxe4 dxe4 16.Bc2 Kh8 { Note that 16...Qa6 would lose to 17.Ra1 when the black queen has no squares. } 17.Rxb7 { White has won back his pawn and still has the advantage based on the more active pieces and the better pawn structure. Also, the pawn on c5 could become a dangerous passed pawn. White's direct threat is Rxd7 and if Black defends against that White can increase the pressure with moves like Ba4, Rc7 or Bb3. } ) ( 10...Qxc3 { is playable, but with precise play White gets an advantage: } 11.Be5 Qa5 12.Bb5+ { similar to the other lines, this check is important. } 12...Bd7 { If instead Black puts his knight on c6 White can take on c6 or play Nd4 with similar play as in the main line. } 13.Nd4 Nc6 14.Bxc6 bxc6 15.O-O { and White has the advantage because Rb7 is coming and the pawn on f5 is weak. } ) 
