3. Bf4 {[%mdl 32768]} ( { Not to g5, I know, but after } 3.Bg5 { Black has the solid } 3...Be7 { . The idea of Bf4 is to make it unattractive for Black players to go for a Stonewall because he cannot put his bishop on d6 without it being exchanged. } ) Nf6 
4. h3 { Just to make sure the bishop can always drop back to h2 if needed. } d5 { Black goes for the Stonewall setup. } 
5. e3 c5 ( { If Black now plays } 5...Bd6 { , White can just ignore it and play } 6.Be2 { because if Black would be foolish enough to take on f4, we recapture exf4. As a result Black has a huge weakness on e6 and a bishop on c8 that is going nowhere. } { Instead of Bd6 Black can also play 5...c6 followed by Be7 and pretend to play a Stonewall setup, but White's play will be similar as if Black plays 5... Bd6: ignore what Black is doing, play O-O, c2-c4, Nc3 followed by c4-c5, b2-b4-b5 and Rb1 with a clear initiative on the queenside. } ) 
6. dxc5 { Not allowing Black to take on d4; White will follow up with c2-c4 realizing that Black is unlikely to take on c4 in the future because after Bxc4 the pawn on e6 feels really weak. } Bxc5 
