1. d4 { I really wanted to develop a complete repertoire, so in this chapter I will discuss a number of rare first moves for Black. I have tried really hard to ensure the recommended lines fit with the rest of the repertoire and that the look and feel of the middlegame positions is similar. } e6 ( { Of course a full repertoire is not complete without considering the move } 1...e5! ) ( 1...e5 2.dxe5 { Thank you, that is an extra pawn! } 2...Nc6 3.Nf3 { White is ready to defend the pawn with Bf4 so Black needs to make it a real sacrifice. } 3...f6 4.e4 { There is no need to take on f6. Black has weakened his light squares. } 4...fxe5 5.Bc4 Nf6 { Now } 6.Ng5 { is strong, but White can also first castle with } { 6.O-O . He has a clear advantage based on his powerful bishop on c4. } ) ( { Now after } 1...e6 { , the move } 2.Bg5 { is not White's most optimal try, so I want to suggest a simple approach. } ) 
2. Nf3 { And now we are ready to play 3.Bg5 next which often will result in a transposition to our repertoire. in my experience most players who play 1...e6 either want to go for a French opening after 2.e4 or for the Dutch with 2... f5. } f5 
3. Bf4 ( { Not to g5, I know, but after } 3.Bg5 { Black has the solid } 3...Be7 { . The idea of Bf4 is to make it unattractive for Black players to go for a Stonewall because he cannot put his bishop on d6 without it being exchanged. } ) Nf6 
4. h3 { Just to make sure the bishop can always drop back to h2 if needed. } d6 { Black is playing in the spirit of the classical Dutch. } 
5. e3 {[%mdl 32768]} {[%cal Rg7g6,Rf8g7,Gf1e2,Ge1g1,Gc2c4,Gb1c3,Gb2b4,Gd1b3,Gc4c5,Gf4h2]} { Simply preparing development. It is better to wait with c2-c4 and first focus on the e4- square. Black wants to put a knight there to create space for his other pieces. } Be7 { Instead Black can opt for a Leningrad -Stonewall hybrid with g6 followed by Bg7. White will play Be2, 0-0, c2-c4, Nc3 followed by typical queenside play with Qb3 or b2-b4 followed by c4-c5, and if needed, the bishop from f4 will drop back to h2. } 
6. Bd3 O-O 
7. O-O Ne4 { Ideally Black plays next Nd7, Bf6 and e6-e5, but White comes first! } 
8. Nbd2 { Exchanging Black's only active piece. } g5 
9. Bh2 Nxd2 
10. Qxd2 Nd7 { The difference between Nc6 and Nd7 is that after Nd7 the knight is likely to go to f6 at some point. } 
11. e4 { This is a thematic break if Black has a pawn on f5 but no control over the e4-square. } g4 { A sharp counter by Black. } ( 11...f4 { Locking in the bishop on h2, but not for long. } 12.e5 { This is thematic in all structures where Black has played f5 and has a pawn on e6. White increases his space advantage in the center. } 12...Rf7 { Creating a square for the d7-knight. } 13.Rae1 { Threatening to win a pawn by taking on d6 and then on e6. } 13...Nf8 14.g3 { Creating a future for the bishop. If Black now takes on g3, White takes back with the f-pawn followed by a later g3-g4 with heavy pressure along the f-file and on the pawns on d6 and e6. } ) 
12. hxg4 fxg4 
13. Ne1 { Forced, as there is no other square. } e5 
14. Be2 { Suddenly the pawn on g4 is weak. } Bg5 
15. Qd3 h5 
16. Qb3+ { Giving the knight the d3-square with tempo. } Kh7 
17. dxe5 { Opening the d-file is much stonger than defending the pawn on d4 because it will take a long time before Black has caught up with White's development (bishop on c8, rook on a8). } dxe5 
18. Nd3 {[%cal Gb3c3,Gd3e5,Ga1d1][%csl Re5,Rg4,Rh5,Rh7]} { White has a clear advantage. Black has created weaknesses in his pawn structure on the kingside, leaving his king exposed and the pawn on e5 is weak. Moreover, White's pieces are a lot more active than Black's. White's next moves are either taking on e5 or Qc3 to increase the pressure or even the simple Rad1. } *

