1. d4 { I really wanted to develop a complete repertoire, so in this chapter I will discuss a number of rare first moves for Black. I have tried really hard to ensure the recommended lines fit with the rest of the repertoire and that the look and feel of the middlegame positions is similar. } c5 { A typical response for Black players who prefer Benoni type of positions. } 
2. d5 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 { Black is hoping White will play c2-c4 with transposition to a main line Benko or Benoni, but White has different plans. There are two good options and I give them both so you can decide which one you prefer. } ( { If Black instead plays } 2...d6 { we transpose to the line with } 3.Nc3 Nf6 { . } ) 
3. Bg5 { This is consistent with our repertoire of putting the bishop to g5. } Ne4 
4. Bf4 Qb6 ( 4...e6 5.f3 { We have to chase the knight away. } 5...Qa5+ 6.c3 Nf6 7.e4 { And we have a standard position we have seen in other places of the repertoire as well. White will continue with Bc4, Ne2 and kingside castling and it is not easy to see how Black will become active. } ) 
5. Bc1 { This is not forced, but I believe it fits best with the rest of the repertoire. It is of course a bit risky to move all your pieces back to their original squares. You are really challenging Black here, but soon White will chase away the knight from e4 and start developing. } c4 {[%cal Rb6f2][%csl Rf2]} ( { Threatening something on f2. If Black doesn't play this but goes for something like } 5...d6 { or } ) ( 5...e6 { we will get a position that is similar to the one where on move four Black doesn't play Qb6 but prefers 4...e6, which is discussed in a separate variation. } ) 
6. e3 e6 
7. f3 { This move White will always play at some point, regardless of whether Black would have gone for c5-c4 on move five. } Qa5+ 
8. c3 { Again consistent with our repertoire. } Nf6 
9. Bxc4 { Exchanging the pawn on c4 for the one on d5. } b5 
10. Bd3 { And not back to e2 because that is where our g1-knight is heading. } Nxd5 
11. e4 Nf6 
12. Ne2 Qb6 
13. a4 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd2c4,Rb5a4,Rb5b4,Ga4a5,Ge1g1]} { I think White can claim some advantage here. He has more control in the center and better piece development. Black now needs to decide whether to take on a4 (after which White plays Nd2 followed by Nc4 and kingside castling) or play b5-b4 (after which White plays a4-a5 followed by castling again). } *

