1. d4 { I really wanted to develop a complete repertoire, so in this chapter I will discuss a number of rare first moves for Black. I have tried really hard to ensure the recommended lines fit with the rest of the repertoire and that the look and feel of the middlegame positions is similar. } c5 { A typical response for Black players who prefer Benoni type of positions. } 
2. d5 g6 { Again Black is hoping to transpose to a kind of Benoni, Benko or even Kings Indian. } 
3. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} { Again I prefer this move over Bg5, although 3.Bg5 is possible here. The rationale of 3. Nc3 is to rule out transpositions to all the 1. d4-openings with a white pawn on c4 and to prepare to stabilize the center with e2-e4. } Bg7 
4. e4 d6 
5. Bc4 { Similarly to other lines, we put our bishop on c4 and the knight on e2. There is nothing wrong with other setups, for example the bishop to d3 and the knight to f3, but I like to be consistent so we recognize the overall themes and we are not in trouble if we forget the exact move order. } Nf6 
6. Nge2 O-O ( { If Black plays } 6...Bg4 { we have the option of } 7.f3 { . In general Black lacks a bit of space so he would like to exchange some pieces, but this is not easy to achieve. } ) 
7. O-O a6 
8. a4 {[%cal Gh2h3,Gc1e3,Gd1d2,Gf2f4]} { White has a nice space advantage. Next he can continue with h3, Be3, Qd2, and f2-f4 to threaten either e4-e5 or f4-f5 followed by Bh6 with a kingside attack. } Nbd7 
9. Ng3 Ne8 { Black needs a knight on c7 to get the b7-b5 break in. } 
10. Be3 Nc7 
11. Qd2 Rb8 
12. a5 { It is essential to prevent b7-b5. } b5 
13. axb6 Rxb6 { Yes, White's pawn on b2 is weak, but in return Black has a weakness on a6 and the c6-square is a nice place for a white knight. } 
14. Bh6 Rxb2 
15. Bxg7 Kxg7 
16. Bb3 {[%cal Gd2c1,Rb2b3,Gf2f4,Ge4e5,Gh2h4,Gh4h5,Gd2g5,Gg3f5,Gg3h5][%csl Rb2]} { And White will win an exchange with Qc1 next, forcing Black to take on b3 with his rook. The last few moves are an illustration of how to play these type of positions with White, but of course in practice you also see a lot of games with f2-f4 and then e4-e5, or with Qg5 and Nf5/Nh5+ playing for an attack. } *

