1. d4 { I really wanted to develop a complete repertoire, so in this chapter I will discuss a number of rare first moves for Black. I have tried really hard to ensure the recommended lines fit with the rest of the repertoire and that the look and feel of the middlegame positions is similar. } c5 { A typical response for Black players who prefer Benoni type of positions. } 
2. d5 e5 { This setup is only seen occassionally in practice because it is quite passive for Black. } 
3. Nc3 {[%mdl 32768]} { I prefer the setup with the pawn still on c2. There is no reason to play c2-c4 because the pawn on d5 doesn't need more support and a pawn on c4 would limit the effectiveness of the bishop on f1. } Nf6 
4. e4 d6 
5. Bb5+ { We can also play Bc4, but given the chance I prefer to offer the bishop exchange (if Black would play Bd7) considering our central pawns are on d5 and e4. } Bd7 
6. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 
7. a4 { Now that the light-squared bishop is gone it is good to put our pawns on the light squares. This move anticipates b7-b5 from Black. } Be7 
8. Nf3 O-O 
9. O-O { Black is a bit passive here and normally most Black players here go for a setup with g6 and f5, which may look threatening to White players if you don't know what to do. } Ne8 
10. Qe2 g6 
11. Bh6 { In the far future White can always take the knight on g7 with his bishop because the bishop on e7 is just a bad piece. White's knights are likely to be stronger. } Ng7 
12. a5 ( { White has also other moves such as } 12.Nd2 { . } ) f5 
13. exf5 gxf5 
14. Nd2 { The knight is on its way to c4. } Nf6 
15. f4 { Blocking the center so that Black cannot become active. } e4 
16. Nc4 {[%cal Gg1h1,Gh2h3,Gg2g4,Gc4e3,Ga1a3,Ga3b3]} { White has a clear advantage. The pawn on f5 is weak (which Ne3 can accentuate) but White can also increase the pressure on the queenside with Ra3-Rb3. And White also has the aggressive plan of Kh1, h3, and g4 when Black may lose the pawn on e4. } *

