1. d4 { I really wanted to develop a complete repertoire, so in this chapter I will discuss a number of rare first moves for Black. I have tried really hard to ensure the recommended lines fit with the rest of the repertoire and that the look and feel of the middlegame positions is similar. } c5 { A typical response for Black players who prefer Benoni type of positions. } 
2. d5 e5 { This setup is only seen occassionally in practice because it is quite passive for Black. } 
3. Nc3 { I prefer the setup with the pawn still on c2. There is no reason to play c2-c4 because the pawn on d5 doesn't need more support and a pawn on c4 would limit the effectiveness of the bishop on f1. } Nf6 
4. e4 d6 
5. Bb5+ { We can also play Bc4, but given the chance I prefer to offer the bishop exchange (if Black would play Bd7) considering our central pawns are on d5 and e4. } Nbd7 
6. a4 {[%mdl 32768]} { This is an important move! White wants to be able to withdraw his bishop to c4 or d3 or even e2 if Black plays a7-a6, but doesn't want to be hit with b7-b5, so you have to play a2-a4 before Black gets the chance to play a7-a6. } Be7 
7. Nge2 { The knight could also have gone to f3, but in most other lines we put it on e2 and here that is fine as well. It makes it a little easier to play f2-f4 later on. } O-O 
8. O-O a6 
9. Bd3 { If the bishop goes back to c4 Black may attack the bishop again with Nb6 so on d3 the bishop is safe. } Rb8 {[%cal Rb7b5]} { Black is dreaming of b7-b5, but it will take a long time. The problem is that he doesn't really have any active plan. } 
10. Ng3 { The knight is ready to go to f5, not just to take the bishop on e7, but to start an attack. If after Nf5 White gets the chance to continue with Qf3-Qg3 it is pretty much game over. } ( { Ng3 also defends the pawn on e4, just in case Black was playing for tricks with } 10.-- b5 11.axb5 axb5 12.Nxb5 Nxe4! ) g6 
11. Bh6 Re8 
12. a5 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4,Gf2f4,Gd1d2,Gh2h4,Gh4h5]} { White has a clear advantage. Black suffers from a lack of space and has no active plan while White has different plans: 1) He can prepare b2-b4 on the queenside after Rb1, but we may not want to give the c5-square to the black knight. 2) White can go for f2-f4 but after exf4 Bxf4 Black may play Ne5 (especially if his bishop is on f8 and the knight is defended by the rook on e8), so we may not want to do this. 3) The plan I prefer is to play for a kingside attack with Qd2 followed by h2-h4-h5 followed by a later Qg5 and Nf5. } *

