1. d4 { I really wanted to develop a complete repertoire, so in this chapter I will discuss a number of rare first moves for Black. I have tried really hard to ensure the recommended lines fit with the rest of the repertoire and that the look and feel of the middlegame positions is similar. } g6 { A typical move for Kings Indian players. These are players who have probably spent a lot of time on studying all the different sharp lines well beyond move 20. Note that on the first three moves Black can also play 1...d6 and we transpose to the main line a few moves later. } ( { It's also possible for Black to play into a Old Indian setup with d6, Nd7, Ngf6 and e5. This is rare, especially from a } 1...d6 { move order, but here is a sample line: } ) ( 1...d6 2.Bg5 Nd7 3.Nf3 Ngf6 4.e3 e5 5.c4 h6 6.Bh4 Be7 7.Nc3 O-O 8.Be2 c6 9.O-O { and White is a little better. He can play Qc2, Rab1 and b4. } ) 
2. Bg5 {[%mdl 32768]} { From a theoretical point of view not the most critical reply. But the idea is that we play the opening in a solid way and we get a structure that we are familiar with from the rest of the repertoire. } Bg7 ( { Of course, in case Black plays } 2...Nf6 { we can exchange the knight } 3.Bxf6 { and transpose to the 2...g6 lines in chapter 4 [/course/134623/3]. } ) 
3. e3 c5 { Because the bishop is already on g5 White is weak on the queenside, especially the pawns on d4 and b2. Also, in certain lines Black has the tactical trick Qa5+ followed by Qxg5. } 
4. c3 { I like this move because it plays against the bishop on g7 which cannot do much against the pawn on d4 that is so well defended by the pawns on c3 and e3. } cxd4 
5. exd4 {[%cal Rd8a5,Ra5g5]} ( { And not } 5.cxd4? { because of } 5...Qa5+! ) Nf6 
6. Nf3 O-O 
7. Be2 { Putting the bishop on d3 is not so effective because of the pawn on g6. } d6 
8. O-O {[%cal Gh2h3,Gd4d5,Gb1a3,Gf1e1,Ga3c4]} { And it is not so easy for Black: on 8...Bg4 there is h3 and if Black takes on f3 White has a clear advantage with the pair of bishops. If Black plays 8... Nc6 White has the annoying 9. d5. So Black should probably start with h6 or b6, but we have succeeded in our strategic plan: we have a position with a lot of play, Black can make mistakes and it is far away from a main line Kings Indian. } *

