1. d4 { I really wanted to develop a complete repertoire, so in this chapter I will discuss a number of rare first moves for Black. I have tried really hard to ensure the recommended lines fit with the rest of the repertoire and that the look and feel of the middlegame positions is similar. } g6 { A typical move for Kings Indian players. These are players who have probably spent a lot of time on studying all the different sharp lines well beyond move 20. Note that on the first three moves Black can also play 1...d6 and we transpose to the main line a few moves later. } ( { It's also possible for Black to play into a Old Indian setup with d6, Nd7, Ngf6 and e5. This is rare, especially from a } 1...d6 { move order, but here is a sample line: } ) ( 1...d6 2.Bg5 Nd7 3.Nf3 Ngf6 4.e3 e5 5.c4 h6 6.Bh4 Be7 7.Nc3 O-O 8.Be2 c6 9.O-O { and White is a little better. He can play Qc2, Rab1 and b4. } ) 
2. Bg5 { From a theoretical point of view not the most critical reply. But the idea is that we play the opening in a solid way and we get a structure that we are familiar with from the rest of the repertoire. } Bg7 ( { Of course, in case Black plays } 2...Nf6 { we can exchange the knight } 3.Bxf6 { and transpose to the 2...g6 lines in chapter 4 [/course/134623/3]. } ) 
3. e3 d6 
4. Nf3 {[%mdl 32768]} { This looks a bit like the London system against the Kings Indian, but the bishop is on g5 much more effective than on f4 where at some point it gets hit by e7-e5. } Nf6 
5. Be2 ( { I also had a look at } 5.Bc4 { because in the London system against the Dutch Leningrad this can be annoying, but here with Black's pawn still on f7 the bishop is better placed on e2. } ) O-O 
6. O-O h6 { Black is chasing away White's bishop. } 
7. Bh4 g5 
8. Bg3 Ne4 ( { Going for the pair of bishops. In some lines Black plays } 8...Nh5 { which comes down to the same thing after taking on g3. } ) 
9. Nbd2 Nxg3 
10. hxg3 { If Black now plays f7-f5, White will attack this pawn with e3-e4 to create weaknesses on the light squares. } Bf5 
11. e4 Bh7 { The bishop is safe on h7 but not very active. Especially if White could support his pawn on e4 with f2-f3 he may use his light pieces on the queenside while the bishop on h7 is out of play. } 
12. c3 { Reducing the power of the bishop on g7. } e6 
13. Bd3 Nd7 
14. Nc4 { If the knight comes to e3 and the d-pawn to d5, White gets a firm grip on the light squares. } Qe7 
15. Re1 g4 { A risky move, but Black has to create some counterplay. } 
16. Nh4 c5 
17. d5 {[%cal Gd5e6,Gc4d6,Ge4e5,Gc4e3][%csl Rd6,Rf5]} { White has a nice space advantage and good control over the f5-square if Black were to move his pawn on e6. The pawn on g4 needs to be defended by h6-h5, but it all feels a bit exposed on Black's kingside. Black can try to go for active play with b7-b5 followed by c5-c4 or b5-b4 but White is prepared for this and may strike back in the center with dxe6 and Nxd6 or, if Black defends against this, with a later e4-e5. } *

