1. d4 { I really wanted to develop a complete repertoire, so in this chapter I will discuss a number of rare first moves for Black. I have tried really hard to ensure the recommended lines fit with the rest of the repertoire and that the look and feel of the middlegame positions is similar. } g6 { A typical move for Kings Indian players. These are players who have probably spent a lot of time on studying all the different sharp lines well beyond move 20. Note that on the first three moves Black can also play 1...d6 and we transpose to the main line a few moves later. } ( { It's also possible for Black to play into a Old Indian setup with d6, Nd7, Ngf6 and e5. This is rare, especially from a } 1...d6 { move order, but here is a sample line: } ) ( 1...d6 2.Bg5 Nd7 3.Nf3 Ngf6 4.e3 e5 5.c4 h6 6.Bh4 Be7 7.Nc3 O-O 8.Be2 c6 9.O-O { and White is a little better. He can play Qc2, Rab1 and b4. } ) 
2. Bg5 { From a theoretical point of view not the most critical reply. But the idea is that we play the opening in a solid way and we get a structure that we are familiar with from the rest of the repertoire. } Bg7 ( { Of course, in case Black plays } 2...Nf6 { we can exchange the knight } 3.Bxf6 { and transpose to the 2...g6 lines in chapter 4 [/course/134623/3]. } ) 
3. e3 d6 
4. Nf3 { This looks a bit like the London system against the Kings Indian, but the bishop is on g5 much more effective than on f4 where at some point it gets hit by e7-e5. } Nf6 
5. Be2 ( { I also had a look at } 5.Bc4 { because in the London system against the Dutch Leningrad this can be annoying, but here with Black's pawn still on f7 the bishop is better placed on e2. } ) O-O 
6. O-O Nc6 
7. c3 {[%mdl 32768]} ( 7.c4 { Just to show you an alternative setup for White. In nearly all cases we put our pawn on c3, but there is nothing wrong with c2-c4 - it is just a different way of playing. } 7...h6 8.Bh4 e5 { Black is following the standard moves from the Kings Indian. } 9.Nc3 exd4 { This is rarely seen but it makes sense to open the diagonal for the bishop on g7. } 10.Nxd4 { If White takes back with the pawn on d4, Black has the idea of g5 followed by Nh5 and Nxg3, which is now prevented because the bishop on e2 covers the h5-square. } 10...Nxd4 11.exd4 Re8 12.h3 { Making sure the bishop can always hide on h2 if needed. } 12...g5 13.Bg3 Bf5 14.Bd3 { There is a gap on f5, which is a bit of a weak square, so White would like to obtain control. } 14...Qd7 { Black refuses to give up control. } 15.Qf3 { And White insists! } 15...Bxd3 16.Qxd3 { Objectively speaking the position is equal, but White has the positional threat of d4-d5 followed by Ne2 (or Nb5) Nd4. Perhaps White will first play f2-f3 so Black doesn't have Ne4. Black can prevent all this by playing d6-d5 himself, but that opens the e5-square for our bishop again. So yes, the position is equal, but certainly not a draw yet! } ) h6 
8. Bh4 e5 
9. Nbd2 Qe8 ( { Now on } 9...e4 { White can just take the pawn with } 10.Nxe4 { because after } 10...g5 { the move } 11.Nxf6+ { comes with check! } ) { Threatening e5-e4. } 
10. dxe5 { With the idea that if in the future Black ever plays e5-e4, White has Nd4 and then usually Black regrets the advance because he has no active plan and a lot of weaknesses. } dxe5 
11. a4 a5 
12. Nc4 {[%cal Ge5e4,Gf3d4,Gd1b3,Ga1d1]} { And the position is about equal but quite complex. The black queen is not ideal on e8 but it is not easy to see where it could go to. On the advance e5-e4 White always has Nd4, but without playing e5-e4 Black may get under pressure after a future Bg3 (first h3 so the bishop can go to h2 after Nh5). White can play Qb3, Rad1 and double rooks on the d-file. }-- ( { A sample line: } 12...Ne4 13.Nfd2 Nxd2 14.Nxd2 Ne7 15.f3 Nd5 16.Bf2 Be6 17.Qc2 Qe7 18.Nc4 h5 19.g3 Nb6 20.Nxb6 cxb6 21.e4 { and I prefer White's position. His bishops are more active and the pawn on b6 is weak. } )
*

