1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Bg5 e6 
3. e4 { The true Trompowsky! } h6 
4. Bxf6 Qxf6 
5. Nc3 g6 
6. Qd2 { Perhaps the queen is better placed on d3 although here it is unlikely that the bishop will come to b4. } d6 
7. f4 { Typical play: White wants to control the center and then launch an attack. } Qe7 
8. Nf3 Bg7 
9. O-O-O a6 
10. Bd3 { White's play is simple and straightforward! } Nd7 
11. f5 { Here we go, White is already better! } e5 { Not good, Black should have castled, but isn't it great if normal moves like e5 don't work? } 
12. Nd5 { Maybe Black missed this? } Qd8 
13. dxe5 Nxe5 ( 13...dxe5 { does not work either: } 14.fxg6 fxg6 15.Qa5 { and the pawn on c7 is surprisingly weak. } 15...b6 16.Qc3 { again attacking c7. } 16...c5 17.Bc4 { and Black can forget about castling kingside, unless he can chase away the bishop with: } 17...b5 { but now White has a blow: } 18.Nf4 Qb6 { 18...exf4 19.Qxg7 }{ 18...bxc4 19.Ne6 } 19.Bd5 { and on Bb7 there is Bf7+ and on Ra7 there is Ne6. } ) 
14. Rhf1 { A simple move with a simple idea: push the f-pawn to f6. } c6 ( { Black has no time for castling: } 14...O-O 15.Nxe5 dxe5 16.f6 { and White is winning. } ) 
15. Ne3 O-O 
16. Nxe5 Bxe5 
17. Ng4 { Black resgined, his king will not survive White's attack. } ( 17.Ng4 Qh4 18.Nxe5 dxe5 19.fxg6 fxg6 20.Bc4+ Kg7 21.Rxf8 Kxf8 22.Qb4+ { And mate will follow soon. } 22...Kg7 { 22...Ke8 23.Qd6 } 23.Rf1 ) 1-0

