4. Bxf6 Qxf6 
5. Nc3 d6 
6. Qd2 g5 
7. O-O-O Bg7 
8. g3 { A standard plan for White to play f2-f4 followed by e5. Black's response is rare. } g4 
9. h3 { And this is the reason why! As we have seen in the repertoire, opening the h-file often makes the bishop on h8 passive and the pawn on g4 could become weak. } h5 
10. hxg4 hxg4 
11. Rxh8+ Bxh8 
12. e5 { Everything forced so far, Black has no options. } dxe5 ( { Also strong for White is: } 12...Qe7 13.Qh6 Qf8 14.Qh4 { and maybe one day White takes on g4 but maybe more important for now: Black is not allowed to castle queenside and Nb5 is a threat. } ) 
13. dxe5 { Almost mate on d8! } Qe7 
14. f4 { Of course, no reason to blunder the e-pawn. } gxf3 
15. Nxf3 { 15 moves played and White is already on +5. } Bd7 
16. Ne4 Bg7 
17. Nf6+ { Ouch, that hurts! } Bxf6 
18. Qh6 { The bishop has no squares. } Bg7 ( 18...Bxe5 19.Nxe5 { and the knight from b8 cannot come out, meanwhile White threatens a deadly check on h8. } ) 
19. Qxg7 Qf8 
20. Qf6 Nc6 
21. Bb5 { Using all his pieces in the attack. } a6 
22. Rh1 { Winning the queen. } Ne7 
23. Rh8 Ng8 
24. Qg5 { A powerful game from start to finish, Black never had a chance. } 1-0

