1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Bg5 e6 
3. e4 { One of the main lines in the Trompowsky. } h6 
4. Bxf6 Qxf6 
5. Nc3 { The alternative c3 is also discussed as part of the repertoire. } d6 
6. Qd2 { The queen typically goes to d3 if there is a black bishop coming to b4, if that is not possible, Qd2 is fine. } Nd7 
7. f4 c6 { Preventing all kind of ideas with Nb5 like in Benjamin-Yermolinsky [/variation/22640840]. } 
8. Nf3 Qd8 
9. O-O-O { Only 9 moves in the game and my engines says White has already a pleasant edge. } a5 { A slow move for which Black will be punished. } 
10. f5 { Here we go, opening lines against Black's king is a typical way of using your lead in development. } Nf6 
11. fxe6 Bxe6 { On fxe6 White has Bd3 and after a future e4-e5 there will be Bg6+. } 
12. d5 { White continues to open the position and put pressure on Black. } Bc8 { The bishop had to go to g4, only move, but then White is clearly better after Bc4. The game move just loses. } 
13. dxc6 bxc6 
14. e5 { Simple but effective, the d6-pawn is pinned. } Nd5 
15. Nxd5 cxd5 
16. Qxd5 { First Bb5+ was equally strong. } Be6 
17. Bb5+ Bd7 
18. exd6 { And Black resigned, he will lose a lot of material if he wants to avoid a direct mate. } 1-0

