6. Qd2 g5 { Quite a lot of Black players go for this setup against the Trompowsky. } 
7. O-O-O Bg7 
8. g3 { White wants to play f4 followed by e4-e5. } Nc6 
9. Nb5 O-O 
10. f4 { I wonder if the black player really calculated the following line or whether he took a gamble which turned out to be justified. } ( 10.Nxc7 Rb8 { now if White defends the pawn on d4 with Ne2 or c3, he may lose the knight after a7-a6. } 11.Nb5 Rd8 12.f4 a6 { with the idea that on Nc3 Black plays Nxd4 and he has a clear advantage. } 13.Nxd6 { That is the move I wonder whether Black anticipated when playing 9...O-O. } 13...Qxd4 { 13...Rxd6 just loses after 14.e5 } 14.Qxd4 Bxd4 15.e5 { Defending the knight but now the pawn on f4 is lost because if White plays gxf4, there is Be3+. } 15...gxf4 16.Nf3 { With about equal play. } ) gxf4 { Not a great move, White is happy to have an open g-file towards Black's king. Black should have played Qe7 so that he has a free move when White plays e4-e5. } 
11. gxf4 { Taking on c7 also came into consideration. } a6 
12. e5 Qe7 
13. Nc3 { The bishop on c8 is still not participating and the Black king could easily get under fire. } dxe5 
14. fxe5 Rd8 { Black should have played f6, trying to swindle by creating a mess. } 
15. Nf3 { Black was threatening Nxe5. } f5 
16. Rg1 { So simple, Qxh6 is the threat. } Kh7 
17. Qg2 { White's attack can be played on autopilot. } Qf8 
18. Ne2 { Extra piece to the attack. } Ne7 
19. Nf4 Bd7 
20. Qh3 { Black resigned, White has many ways to win, Nh5 is a threat but he can also attack e6 with Bc4 and Ng5+. } 1-0

