1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} { It is not often that we see a White player winning against a grandmaster with 200 rating points more in 24 moves! } Nf6 
2. Bg5 e6 
3. e4 h6 
4. Bxf6 Qxf6 
5. Nc3 d6 
6. Qd2 g5 
7. O-O-O Bg7 { We have seen this position before and there White continued with g3 and f4. } 
8. Nf3 g4 
9. Ne1 Nc6 { This is a well-known theme in these structures: Black is attacking d4. } 
10. Nb5 Qe7 
11. d5 { I like this better than the somewhat passive c3. } exd5 
12. exd5 Ne5 
13. Qa5 { A sharp move but maybe the simple Kb1 was stronger. } O-O 
14. Qxc7 Bd7 ( { Black could have continued with sharp play: } 14...Qg5+ 15.Kb1 Bf5 { sacrificing a second pawn, Rac8 is the threat. } 16.Qxd6 Rfd8 17.Qb4 { And it's a total mess. Black has attacking chances for the two pawns but both sides can win. } ) 
15. Nxd6 Qf6 
16. Kb1 { Now if the knight from e5 moves White can defend against mate with for example Nd3. } b5 { A typical attacking move, preparing Nc4 ideas. } 
17. Ne4 Qf4 
18. f3 { Great move by White, he wants to stabilize his knight in the center. } Rac8 
19. Qd6 { The engine suggests taking on a7, but I don't trust that at all! } gxf3 { Not a good move, Bf5 was required. } 
20. gxf3 Bg4 
21. Rg1 { Always that open g-file! } Bxf3 
22. Nxf3 Qxf3 
23. Rxg7+ { Black must have missed this, but opening the g-file was a bad idea anyway. } Kxg7 
24. Qxe5+ { And Black resigned, White can just continue to build his attack with his two light pieces and Black has no defense. } 1-0

