9. g3 { A strange move, not bad but the immediate f2-f4 would have been more logical. } Qf3 
10. Rg1 Bg5 { Not sure what Black wanted but this move doesn't work. } 
11. Nf4 { The black queen is suddenly locked in and can get lost. } Bxf4 
12. gxf4 { Now the g-file is open, a big plus for White. } Rg8 
13. Rg3 Qh5 
14. Rh3 Qg6 { The queen is still not in a comfortable place. } 
15. O-O-O d6 
16. d5 { Typical for the Trompowsky: White has a lead in development and tries to open lines against Black's king. } Nd7 
17. Nb5 Kd8 { Queenside castling is met by Nxa7, but the king on d8 is not safe. Positions with the king trapped in the center are discussed in detail in the repertoire. } 
18. Qc3 Nc5 
19. b4 Qxe4 ( { Also losing is } 19...Na6 20.Nd4 Rc8 21.dxe6 fxe6 22.f5 ) 
20. bxc5 { An extra piece for White. } Qxf4+ 
21. Re3 Bxd5 
22. cxb6 { Qc7 is big trouble. } c6 
23. Rxd5 { Ouch! } exd5 
24. b7 Kd7 
25. bxa8=Q Rxa8 
26. Bh3+ { An easy win for White! } 1-0

