1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Bg5 Ne4 { A typical move for classical players: they don't want to allow an imbalance to their position like a double pawn so early in the game. } 
3. Bf4 d5 
4. e3 { I think f3 followed by Nc3 is more promising. } c5 
5. Bd3 Qb6 { A risky move. } 
6. Bxe4 { White picks up the challenge! An alternative: } ( 6.Ne2 Qxb2 { 6...Nf6 This is always possible but if you don't take on b2 and you withdraw your knight from e4, what was then the point of Black's play? } 7.Bxe4 Qxa1 { 7...dxe4 8.Nbc3 This is already better for White. } 8.Bxd5 { White has sufficient compensation for the exchange and there are many ways for Black to go wrong. He is seriously behind with his development. } ) Qxb2 { Black is following a principal path. } ( 6...dxe4 7.Nc3 cxd4 8.Qxd4 { And White has some advantage. } ) 
7. Bxd5 Qxa1 
8. Nf3 { The problem with the prinicipal way of Black' play is that White is already clearly better, his lead in development will make the difference combined with the poor position of Black's queen. } e6 
9. Bb3 { Locking in the queen. } Nd7 
10. O-O { First king safety before taking any action! } cxd4 { Objectively speaking Be7 was a bit stronger, but even then Black is in serious trouble after c2-c4 with the idea of Qc2 and winning the queen on a1. } 
11. exd4 Bb4 
12. Qd3 { Immediately c2-c3 also works and could transpose. } Qb2 
13. c3 Be7 
14. Bc1 Qa1 
15. Qc2 { And Black resigned: White's next move will be Bb2 winning the queen. A typical game to show how to benefit from Black taking on b2. } 1-0

