1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Bg5 Ne4 
3. Bf4 c5 { One of the more critical lines in the Trompowsky. } 
4. f3 Nf6 
5. dxc5 b6 { This pawn sacrifice is also discussed in the repertoire. } 
6. e4 bxc5 
7. e5 Ng8 ( { Much simpler and stronger was } 7...Nh5 8.Be3 g6 { And Black is ok. } ) 
8. Nc3 Nc6 
9. Bb5 { Typical for the Trompowsky to put the bishop on b5. } Nd4 
10. Nge2 Nxb5 
11. Nxb5 Qa5+ { Developing/attacking with Ba6 is a better move. } 
12. Nec3 a6 
13. Nd6+ { Flashy but Na3 followed by Nc4 would have given White a large advantage. } exd6 
14. exd6 Qb4 { A mistake, instead Nf6 or Bb7 and Black can fight. } 
15. Qe2+ Kd8 { As we have seen in the repertoire, Black's king in the middle often gives White great attacking chances. } 
16. Bd2 Bb7 
17. O-O-O ( { White misses a win here: } 17.Nd5 Qb5 18.c4 Qa4 { 18...Qc6 this results in mate after: 19.Ba5+ Kc8 20.Qe8 } 19.Nb6 Qc6 20.Ba5 Nf6 21.O-O-O { And White is winning. } ) Nf6 
18. Rhe1 Bxd6 { A mistake, Black had one good move. } ( 18...Qb6 { The only way to continue. } 19.Na4 Qb5 20.Qe5 Qxa4 21.Qxc5 { Threatening mate on c7. } 21...Qc6 22.Ba5+ Kc8 23.Qe5 { Threatening Qe8+ and mate. } 23...Bxd6 24.Rxd6 Qb5 { And Black is still alive. } ) 
19. Ne4 Bf4 ( 19...Qb6 { is not possible due to } 20.Nxd6 Qxd6 21.Ba5+ { . } ) 
20. Bxf4 Nxe4 
21. fxe4 Re8 { Material is equal, king safety is a different issue. } 
22. Qg4 Re6 
23. Qxg7 { Not just taking a pawn, Qf8 is a big threat. } Bc6 
24. Qf8+ Re8 
25. Qxf7 { Black is lost. } 1-0

