1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Bg5 { Arjun Erigaisi also plays non-standard openings in his OTB tournaments with great success. } g6 
3. Bxf6 exf6 
4. e3 Bg7 
5. Nf3 { I prefer to put the knight on e2 and the bishop to g2 after exf6. } O-O 
6. c4 f5 
7. Be2 d6 
8. O-O g5 { White normally plays on the queenside, Black on the kingside. } 
9. Nc3 g4 
10. Ne1 Nd7 
11. g3 Nf6 
12. Ng2 { White has obtained good control over the kingside and can now focus on the queenside or...Erigaisi has a creative idea. } h5 
13. f3 { Here we go! Normally Black doesn't have a pawn on g4 yet, so White has to play something like b4. But as discussed in the course, when Black has an advanced pawn (could also be on d4 or e4) moves to attack it (f3, c3) are quite typical. } Re8 
14. Qd3 Bh6 
15. Rae1 Bd7 { The bishop is not becoming more active on d7. } 
16. e4 fxe4 
17. fxe4 { White has a great center, the f-file has been opened and there is a weak square on f5. } Nh7 
18. Nf4 { Suddenly the pawn on h5 feels weak. } Qg5 
19. Bd1 { A nice way to get the bishop to c2. } c6 
20. Bc2 { Ideas with e4-e5 threatening Qxh7 begin to appear. } Nf8 
21. e5 { A pawn sacrifice to optimize the activity of the white pieces. } dxe5 
22. Ne4 { This knight was not doing much on c3 and now it is a monster. } Qf5 
23. Nxh5 { Black cannot take on h5 because of Nf6+. } Qe6 
24. Nef6+ Kh8 
25. Nxe8 { Not just winning material but also vacating square f6 to continue the attack. } Rxe8 
26. Rf6 e4 
27. Rxe6 { And Black resigned, he is losing nearly all his pieces. } 1-0

