1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Bg5 g6 
3. Bxf6 exf6 
4. e3 f5 
5. c4 Bg7 
6. Nc3 d6 
7. g3 { The standard way of playing for White after exf6: bishop to g2 and knight to e2. } Nd7 
8. Bg2 O-O 
9. Nge2 Nf6 
10. O-O c6 
11. b4 { A standard position, White plays on the queenside, Black on the kingside. } Rb8 
12. a4 a6 
13. Qd3 d5 { I guess Black didn't see how to continue but this cannot be good. White now gets an extra target on d5. A better move was something like Bd7 although even then White has already a pleasant edge. } 
14. cxd5 Nxd5 
15. Nxd5 cxd5 
16. Nf4 { This looks really bad for Black with his two passive bishops. } Be6 
17. Qb3 b5 { Black misses the chance to fight: } ( 17...g5 18.Nd3 { 18.Nxd5 This just loses a piece for White: 18...Qd6 19.Rfc1 Rfd8 And the knight on d5 cannot be defended anymore. } f4 { A good pawn sacrifice! White would like to take with his e-pawn, but then d4 will drop at some point. So gxf4 is the main option. } 19.gxf4 Kh8 { And at the cost of a pawn Black has managed to create space for his bishops and after Rg8 he can put pressure on the g-file. White will surely play Kh1 on one of the next moves. } ) 
18. Bxd5 Bxd5 
19. Qxd5 { The endgame is totally winning for White with the passive bishop on g7 and the weak black pawns on the queenside. } bxa4 
20. Rxa4 Qb6 
21. Rfa1 Rfd8 
22. Qa2 Bf8 
23. h4 { I assume Black resigned here, but not 100% sure. White can next play Nd3 followed by either Rxa6 or Nc5 and Nxa6. } 1-0

