1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Bg5 g6 { A rare move. } 
3. Bxf6 exf6 
4. e3 f5 
5. Ne2 Bg7 
6. g3 { This type of setup with a knight on e2 and a bishop on g2 is quite effective when Black has taken back on f6 with his e-pawn and it comes back multiple times in the repertoire. } O-O 
7. Bg2 d6 
8. c4 { Normally in these type of positions White plays on the queenside and Black tries to create some initiative on the kingside. } c5 { I think the more modest c6 was a better option. } 
9. Nbc3 cxd4 
10. exd4 { I would have preferred Nxd4 to play against the weak d6-pawn. } Nc6 
11. Qd2 f4 { A typical move, Black is trying to create play on the queenside and using the fact that White hasn't castled yet and also needs to cover the d4-pawn. } 
12. gxf4 { White had an interesting alternative: } ( 12.Qxf4 Qb6 13.Rd1 Qxb2 14.O-O { And maybe White has a tiny edge but mostly it is a complex position where both sides can make mistakes. } ) Qh4 
13. d5 Ne7 
14. O-O { Finally White has managed to castle! } Nf5 
15. Ng3 { With the idea that Black can never take on g3 because after hxg3 the pawn on f4 is suddenly defended again and no longer weak. } Nh6 { With the idea to play for mate after Ng4. } 
16. Nce4 Ng4 
17. h3 Nf6 
18. Ng5 { Again White had another choice, not necessarily better, but just to show you how complex the position is: } ( 18.Nxd6 Bxh3 19.Rad1 Bh6 20.Qd4 Bg7 21.Qe3 { And maybe White is a little better, his d-pawn could become dangerous. } ) Nh5 
19. Nxh5 Qxh5 
20. Kh2 { White has a sneaky idea that Black completely missed! } Bh6 
21. Kg3 { Ooops, Bf3 is the big threat. } f6 { Black had only one move: } ( 21...Bxg5 22.fxg5 Bf5 { And Black is not lost yet. His queen cannot escape, but White can also not attack it yet. White has ideas like Qf4, h4 and then Bf3, but should not allow Qe2 from Black, so maybe best to start with a rook to e1. } ) 
22. Bf3 { Game over. } 1-0

