1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Bg5 g6 
3. Bxf6 exf6 
4. e3 Bg7 
5. h4 { A rare move but not necessarily bad. Often Black plays h5 and then White responds with h4. } h5 
6. Ne2 { In these structures f4 is usually a good square for the knight. } d5 
7. c4 { This move feels a bit early, I prefer g3, Bg2 and castling. } dxc4 
8. Nf4 c5 { Black is trying to open the position for his bishop pair. } 
9. d5 f5 
10. Nc3 b5 { If White had already castled before playing c4 these kind of tricks would not be possible. } 
11. d6 O-O { Bb7 was probably stronger. } 
12. Be2 b4 { Again Bb7 or even Nd7 were to be preferred. } 
13. Nb5 { And White should have played Na4. } Nc6 
14. Bxc4 { Now we get to the reason I included this game: White is going to attack over the light squares, a theme that also comes back in the repertoire. } Ba6 
15. a4 Bxb2 
16. Nxg6 { Probably missed by Black. } Qf6 
17. Nxf8 Bxa1 { Taking back on f8 would have given sufficient compensation. } 
18. Nd7 Bc3+ 
19. Kf1 Qg7 { And now White creates an attack by using the one piece that was still doing nothing: } 
20. Rh3 Ne5 
21. Nxe5 Bxe5 
22. f4 Qg4 ( 22...Bf6 23.Qf3 Qf8 24.Rg3+ Bg7 25.Qc6 { And White is winning. } ) 
23. Be2 Bxb5 
24. axb5 { A messy game, but we don't play as perfect as the engines. Still some good lessons on castling before playing c4, generating an attack on the light squares and using all your pieces including rooks. } 1-0

[Event "The Trompowsky: Simplified"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Hodgson, Julian M vs. Shepley, Julien M. 1990"]
[Date "2023.01.02"]
[Result "1-0"]
