[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22640857"]

1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} d5 
2. Bg5 Nc6 { A rare move, Black may want to go for some kind of Chigorin setup. } 
3. e3 Qd6 { Clearly Black wants to play e7-e5. } 
4. Bf4 { The bishop was not doing much on g5 anymore with Black's queen no longer being on d8. } e5 { Logical but also quite risky. } 
5. dxe5 Nxe5 { A clear mistake. } ( 5...Qb4+ { This was the way to go for Black. It is surprising to see that we have just played 5 moves and already Black has to play this only move, no alternatives! } 6.Nd2 { And now Black has two options. } 6...Qxb2 { We have seen these type of captures a lot in the repertoire, but here there is one key difference: the black bishop from f8 is already mobile and can come to b4. } { 6...Nge7 Developing your pieces is usually not a bad idea. 7.Ngf3 Ng6 Threatening to take on f4. 8.Bg3 Bg4 9.Qb1 A nice move, not just protecting b2, but also preparing expansion on the queenside. 9...O-O-O In the spirit of the Chigorin, Black castles queenside and now wants to win back the sacrificed pawn on e5. 10.c3 Qe7 11.h3 Bd7 12.Be2 White is ready to castle. 12...Ngxe5 13.b4 And White has a nice advantage, his attack is much quicker and the knight on c6 does't have any good squares. If he plays something like f6 White will not play b4-b5 yet (Black takes on f3 with check and then Ne5), but first play a2-a4. } 7.Ngf3 Bb4 8.Be2 { Whote focusses on development. } 8...Bxd2+ 9.Nxd2 Nge7 10.O-O O-O 11.a4 { White is a little better, he has the pair of bishops and the black queen on b2 could get into trouble. Still, in most of the repertoire lines White can build upon a lead in development after Black has taken on b2, here that is not the case. Black has castled and is ready to develop his bishop from c8. The good thing for White is that he is not a pawn down, he basically exchanged b2 for the pawn on e5. } ) 
6. Nc3 { The pawn on d5 hangs, Nb5 is a threat and the knight on e5 is in a pin. } c6 { This is too slow. } 
7. Qd4 { Not a bad move but White had much stronger. } ( 7.Qh5 { A simple move, I don't understand why Hodgson missed this. White threatens to take the knight oon e5 and Black cannot defend it. } 7...g5 { The only way for Black to save his piece. } 8.Qxg5 f6 { with the queen on h5 this move was not possible but now Black can at least dfend his knight. } 9.Qh5+ { And White has a winning advantage: an extra pawn and the Black king is in danger. } ) f6 { Only move for Black. } 
8. O-O-O { Of course! White wants to attack and first puts his king on a safe place. } g5 
9. Bg3 Ne7 { A big mistake because now the queen on d6 is no longer defended by the bishop on f8. Black should have played something like Bg7 (defending the knight on e5 and the pawn on f6). } 
10. Ne4 { And Black resigned. On Qe6 White takes on f6. } 1-0

