1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} f5 
2. Bg5 { This may well become the main line against the Dutch considering it scores well for White. Of course, when you check with the engine you will find multiple ways to equalize with Black, but there are quite a few practical problems White can create. } Nf6 { I don't like this move. } 
3. Nd2 ( 3.Bxf6 { And this is the reason why! } 3...exf6 4.c4 { And White is clearly better because he has control over square d5. } ) b6 
4. f3 { Taking on f6 still looks strong to me. } Bb7 
5. e4 { Only 5 moves in the game and White has already a nice center. } fxe4 ( 5...e6 { This was Black's best chance. } 6.exf5 { Damaging Black's pawn structure. } { 6.e5 White cannot win a piece: 6...h6 7.Bh4 g5 And Black is ok. } 6...exf5 7.Qe2+ Qe7 8.Bxf6 { A typical way of creating weak pawns. } 8...gxf6 9.Qxe7+ Kxe7 10.Bd3 Nc6 11.c3 { And White has a clear advantage based on the weak f5-pawn. } ) 
6. fxe4 Nxe4 { Common sense already tells you this cannot be ok for Black, he has hardly developed any piece. } 
7. Nxe4 Bxe4 
8. Bd3 { Exchaning pieces to highlight the weaknesses on the light squares. } ( 8.d5 { Even stronger. } 8...d6 9.Qd4 Bf5 10.Bb5+ Bd7 11.Be2 { And Black struggles to develop while White can castle either side, play Nf3 and rook to e1 and there will be trouble on e7. } ) Bxd3 
9. Qxd3 Qc8 
10. Nf3 { White is just developing, I have no idea what Black is doing. } Qa6 
11. c4 { There is no reason to exchange, although even then White would be better. } Nc6 
12. O-O d5 { I assume Black was worried about White playing d5, but preventing d5 was not an option anymore, Black had to think about safety. } ( 12...O-O-O { The healthier choice, although after } 13.d5 Na5 14.Ne5 { White is likely to win material. } ) 
13. Qf5 { Maybe Black missed this move? } dxc4 { Another mistake but Black's position was already hopeless. } 
14. Qd5 { Actually Ne5 would have resulted in mate, but this is good enough, Black resigned! } 1-0

