1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} f5 
2. Bg5 g6 { The move I recommend for Black is my Chessable Leningrad course. } 
3. Nc3 Nf6 { Strange that Black plays this before Bg7. } 
4. h4 { These advances with the h-pawn have become quite topical in all kind of openings. } h6 { This is a mistake, Black is losing too much time. Developing the bishop to g7 was a must. } 
5. Bxf6 exf6 
6. Nh3 { The pawn on g6 is a concern. } h5 
7. Nf4 Kf7 { This doesn't feel right for Black, but neither was Rg8. } 
8. e3 Bh6 
9. Bc4+ Kg7 { And now we get a combination that is similar to one we have in the repertoire. } 
10. Nxg6 Kxg6 
11. Qxh5+ Kh7 ( 11...Kxh5 12.Bf7+ Kg4 13.f3+ Kg3 14.Kf1 { and Rh3 is mate on the next move. } ) 
12. Qf7+ Bg7 
13. Nd5 { Adding pices to the attack. } Rf8 
14. Qh5+ Bh6 
15. Qxf5+ Kh8 
16. Qg6 Bg7 
17. Qh5+ { A flashy win from White based on an important motive in this Lg5-h4 Leningrad. } 1-0

[Event "The Trompowsky: Simplified"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Mamedyarov, Shakhriyar vs. Anastasian, Ashot 2002"]
[Date "2023.01.02"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A45"]
[SourceTitle "https://www.chessable.com/variation/22640846"]

1. d4 {[%mdl 32768]} Nf6 
2. Bg5 e6 
3. e4 h6 
4. Bxf6 Qxf6 
5. Nc3 d6 
6. Qd2 g6 
7. O-O-O Bg7 
8. f4 { All these moves we have seen before, now instead of c6 Black plays a6, also with the idea of avoiding Nb5 tricks. } a6 
9. g4 { Pure aggression! } Nd7 
10. Nf3 { Never forget to develop your pieces! } b5 
11. e5 { This move we have seen multiple times in the repertoire with a black bishop on g7. } Qe7 
12. f5 dxe5 { Perhaps Black should have sacrificed a piece: } ( 12...Bb7 13.f6 { Many players would think this is game over, but it is not that simple. } 13...Nxf6 14.exf6 Qxf6 15.Bg2 b4 16.Na4 Bxf3 17.Rhf1 Qxd4 { And now White should either take the queen or on f3 immediately. } 18.Qxd4 { 18.Bxf3 Qxd2+ 19.Rxd2 and White is better. } 18...Bxd4 19.Bxf3 Be3+ 20.Kb1 { Black has three pawns for the piece and it is not easy for White to break through but I find it hard to believe Mamedyarov would not win this. } ) 
13. dxe5 Nxe5 { Black had an alternative but I am not convinced: } ( 13...b4 14.Ne4 { Now f5-f6 is the big threat so Black has no choice. } 14...exf5 15.gxf5 gxf5 16.Ng3 Nxe5 { Black is two pawns up but they don't mean much here and White still has a big initiative. } 17.Nxe5 Bxe5 18.Bg2 Rb8 19.Bc6+ Kf8 20.Rhe1 { And this looks like a position in which Black may not last much longer. } ) 
14. Nxe5 Bxe5 
15. Bg2 { Again White develops and attacks. } Rb8 
16. Rhe1 { All his pieces developed, rooks in the center on open files, Mamedyarov probably counted the point already. } f6 ( { Black's best chance was } 16...Bf6 { threatening Bg5. } 17.Kb1 O-O 18.Nd5 { using the pin on the e-file. } 18...Qd8 19.Nxf6+ Qxf6 20.fxg6 Qxg6 21.h4 { and White still has a big attack, but at least Black can still fight. } ) 
17. fxg6 { I don't know what Black missed. } Rb6 
18. Rxe5 { A classical exchange sacrifice to weaken the dark squares, especially f6. } fxe5 
19. Ne4 Rg8 
20. Qxh6 { And Black resigned. } 1-0

